<FIRST>r i AM-BRF---Honduras-US     11-14 0154</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-BRF---Honduras-US,0159</SECOND>
<HEAD>Embassy Says U.S. Troops Will Hold Three Exercises in Honduras</HEAD>
<DATELINE>TEGUCIGALPA, Honduras (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   About 24,000 U.S. military
personnel will take part in joint military exercises in Honduras
during the coming year, U.S. Embassy spokesman Mark Jacobs said
Tuesday.
   He said that during the U.S. fiscal year 1989-1990, which
started Oct. 1, U.S. and Honduran troops would participate in at
least three joint training programs.
   Jacobs did not give any specific dates or time periods for the
maneuvers. In the past, the embassy usually released more detailed
plans for the exercises about a week in advance.
   Some 25,000 U.S. military personnel took part in two, six-month
training programs in Honduras in 1988-89. Military exercises
involving thousands of American troopers and Honduran forces have
been held frequently since 1982.
   The United States has some 1,200 military personnel based at the
Enrique Soto Cano air base, 37 miles northwest of Tegucigalpa, the
capital.
</TEXT>
