<FIRST>r i AM-Germany-Brandt 1stLd-Writethru a0628 11-14 0525</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Germany-Brandt, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0628,0534</SECOND>
<HEAD>Brandt Says Part of Berlin Wall Should Stand as a Cold War Reminder</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: Inserts 3 grafs after 8th pvs bgng: He rose to world... with
comments about Allies and President Kennedy. Pickup 9th pvs: Brandt said
he thinks...</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By TERRENCE PETTY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BONN, West Germany (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Former West German Chancellor Willy
Brandt said Monday he hopes some of the crumbling Berlin Wall will
stand permanently, not as a barrier but as a reminder of the Cold
War.
   ``A part of it should be allowed to remain standing, to serve as
something of a museum,'' said Brandt, who was mayor of West Berlin
when the wall was erected in 1961.
   East German officials have opened new passages through the wall
but have made it clear they will leave much of it standing for now
to continue marking the line between East Berlin and West Berlin.
   Brandt, 75, said he was deeply moved when he visited Berlin over
the weekend and watched people freely moving through _ and over _
the wall.
   He said he would never forget how, for the first time, he saw
East German border guards smiling at East German residents as they
passed through border control points.
   ``They were so friendly. And the (East) Berliners who came back
called over to the police _ `Hey look, we're back!'''
   Even though Brandt is from the northern city of Luebeck, there
are few politicians in West Germany whose personal histories are so
closely linked with the Berlin Wall.
   He rose to world prominence in 1961 when Communist East Germany
constructed the wall, which became the scene of dozens of fatal
escape attempts. Angered by the wall's deadly threat to East
Berliners, Brandt immediately condemned the structure as a human
rights violation.
   In an interview shown Monday night on the Macneil-Lehrer
NewsHour broadcast in New York, Brandt was reminded of his anger in
1961 when the three Western Allies _ America, Britain and France _
did nothing to tear the wall down and he was asked if President
John F. Kennedy was right not to take action.
   ``I never asked President Kennedy to take military action,''
Brandt said. ``What I was angry about at the time ... was that
there had been so much talk about the four-power responsibility
(the Western Allies and Soviet Union) for Berlin as a whole and
when it came to a critical point, we had to acknowledge that
four-power responsibility had to be reduced to a three-party
responsibility for Western Berlin.
   ``I was happy that we could count on that protection _
responsibility and protection. No, I think looking back at it, it
was the right thing not to take the kind of military action which
could have brought us into a new World War.''
   Brandt said he thinks West Germany should not intervene in what
is happening in East Germany but be ready to offer its help.
   ``Leave it to people in the other part of Germany to find their
proper answers to their problems, but be as helpful as possible,
especially in the field of economic cooperation,'' he said.
</TEXT>
