<FIRST>r w PM-Whistleblowers     11-14 0543</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Whistleblowers,530</SECOND>
<HEAD>There's No Reward for Being a Whistleblower, Senate Panel Told</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DONNA CASSATA</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The federal government should reward _ not
punish _ workers who blow the whistle on fraud, say employees in
telling a Senate subcommittee how they were thwarted in efforts to
expose abuse.
   ``There's no reward for being a whistleblower,'' complained a
Defense Department worker in Pittsburgh who went public with
allegations about a Western Pennsylvania defense contractor.
   Nancy Kusen said Monday that the government saved $3.3 million
on a contract when she brought allegations of fraud to their
attention, but all she got in return were two lines of commendation.
   ``When someone finds a wallet, they get a reward,'' she told the
Senate Governmental Affairs subcommittee on general services,
federalism and the District of Columbia, which held a hearing into
the inspectors general fraud hotlines.
   The 16-year federal employee described for the committee her
nearly five-year effort to persuade the Defense Department to
investigate pricing irregularities by the Elliott Co., then a
subsidiary of United Technologies Corp.
   Twenty-six letters to the Defense Department hotline describing
contract problems, including some with audit reports, progress
payment records and copies of contracts, produced little action,
Kusen said. Finally, she took her information to The Pittsburgh
Press.
   After a series of articles in the newspaper, the U.S. Navy Price
Fighter Detachment conducted its own inquiry. The Detachment found
that on an order for 26 rotor assemblies, Elliott Co. charged
$6,613.49 for items that should have been $1,485.89, Ms. Kusen said.
   Federal employees fear retaliation for reporting waste and
abuse, said the Pittsburgh worker who said she would never use the
hotline again.
   Phillip T. Doe, an employee with the Bureau of Land Reclamation
who blew the whistle on a land scandal, said he never considered
the inspectors general hotline.
   ``Friends ... said the reaction would be one of damage
control,'' Doe told the committee.
   William M. Diefenderfer, deputy director of the Office of
Management and Budget and chairman of the President's Council on
Integrity and Efficiency, said the testimony was ``the most
demoralizing thing I've heard.''
   But he said he did not think ``it is that bad,'' and suggested
an increase in congressional oversightof the day-to-day operations
of the inspectors general hotline.
   Dina Rasor, director of the Project on Military Procurement
which recently released a 52-page survival guide for the
whistleblower, said one problem with the system is that
confidential complaints to the hotline, after proceeding through
the investigative channels, usually end up on the desk of the
whistleblower's boss, and ``it doesn't take long to find out who
the employee is.''
   The other problem is that investigators rarely work with the
whistleblower on their inquiries. ``They go through a stack of
documents without understanding the problem,'' Ms. Rasor said.
   ``I've never known a whistleblower to be successful with the
hotline,'' said Rasor, who has spent nine years investigating the
military.
   The General Accounting Office, the investigative arm of
Congress, said their study of the hotline system found that some
telephone hotline numbers were not listed and others did not have
an 800-number, like the Department of Housing and Urban Development.
   Overall, the GAO said the hotlines ``can be useful in receiving
calls and complaints.''
</TEXT>
