<FIRST>r a AM-MilitaryJetCrash     11-14 0321</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Military Jet Crash,0330</SECOND>
<HEAD>Report: Catastrophic Engine Failure Caused Jet Crash</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MARIETTA, Ga. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A Navy jet crashed last week because its
engine suddenly failed, The Atlanta Constitution said in a report
on the accident that destroyed 12 apartments and killed two people
in this Atlanta suburb.
   Investigators have pinpointed which engine parts caused the
sudden, catastrophic failure of the A-7E Corsair II's engine
Thursday, the newspaper, quoting an unidentified source close to
the investigation, reported in Tuesday editions.
   The source, however, declined to say exactly what went wrong.
   Air traffic controllers said engine and radio failure may have
occurred about two minutes before the crash, the time of the
tower's last contact with the pilot.
   They said there was no indication the plane was in trouble
before it hit the apartment complex. An investigation of the crash
is expected to take at least 30 days.
   The Navy on Monday said it would pay the funeral expenses of the
two people who were killed when the jet slammed into their
apartment complex: Richard Dick, 24, and Margie Padovani. Padovani,
28, who was two months pregnant, died of burns Friday.
   Dick's body was transported to Meridian, Miss. Ms. Padovani's
body will be transported to her hometown of Hempstead, N.Y.
   Her 5-year-old daughter, Jacquelyn Padovani, 5, remained in
critical condition at Grady Memorial Hospital with burns over about
half of her body.
   The jet's pilot, Lt. Cmdr. Robert M. Conlyn Jr., 37, was listed
in serious condition at Kennestone Hospital in Marietta.
   Conlyn was the only person aboard the unarmed attack plane when
it crashed.
   The jet was returning to the NAS at Dobbins Air Force Base,
about two miles from the apartments and 15 miles from downtown
Atlanta, when it went down.
   The crash destroyed 12 of the 76 units at the Pine Village North
apartment complex and heavily damaged another 20, said Kathie
Barton, Smyrna's director of community relations.
</TEXT>
