<FIRST>r w PM-Baker-OAS     11-14 0568</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Baker-OAS,580</SECOND>
<HEAD>Baker Suggests Central America Could Dominate Summit</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By GEORGE GEDDA</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Secretary of State James A. Baker III is
raising the possibility that reported Soviet arms deliveries to
Central America may be the most contentious issue at the
Soviet-American summit meeting in three weeks.
   Baker told Organization of American States foreign ministers
Monday evening that the Soviet shipments to that region remain the
``biggest obstacle'' to a genuine superpower accommodation.
   ``The Soviet Union bears a special responsibility because its
arms and money, moving through Cuba and Nicaragua, continue to
support violence destruction and war,'' Baker said.
   In previous statements, Baker has said he doesn't challenge the
Soviet claim that it has ceased direct weapons shipments to Central
America as of this year.
   But he has contended that Soviet shipments to the region through
third countries and deliveries by the Soviet bloc have meant that
the Kremlin's allies in the area continue to be well-stocked.
   His remarks Monday reinforced the notion that regional conflicts
_ particularly in Central America _ could produce fireworks when
President Bush and Soviet President Mikhail Gorbachev hold their
summit meeting in the Mediterranean starting Dec. 2.
   The OAS meeting, featuring about 25 foreign ministers, was
continuing today after a hectic opening session Monday that
included:
   _A sharp exchange in which Panamanian Foreign Minister Leonardo
Kam accused the United States of pursuing ``fascist'' policies
after Baker called Panama an ``outlaw regime'' that should be
spurned by ``self-respecting democracies.''
   _The introduction by Costa Rica of a resolution calling on all
OAS member states to withdraw their ambassadors from Panama until a
democratic process is under way there. The human rights commission
of the OAS released a report Monday accusing Panama of widespread
abuses.
   _The admission of Canada, amid numerous expressions of support,
as the 32nd active member of the OAS.
   _A demonstration by several dozen OAS employees outside the
headquarters demanding higher pay. The OAS is undergoing a cash
flow crisis that has resulted in numerous layoffs and declining
employee morale.
   _A call by Nicaraguan Foreign Minister Miguel D'Escoto for an
OAS appeal to the government of El Salvador ``to cease immediately
the bombing of the civilian population.'' Baker held the leftist
rebels responsible for the outbreak of fighting over the weekend,
calling their attacks ``acts of terror, pure and simple.''
   Shortly before foreign ministers opened their afternoon session,
representatives of the leftist Sandinista government and the
Nicaraguan Contras reconvened peace talks here after two days of
discussions last week at the United Nations.
   There was no report on the meeting, but D'Escoto, in an
interview with The Associated Press, said there was minimal
progress at the U.N. talks because the Contra delegates weren't
interested in discussing the demobilization of their forces.
   Central American presidents last summer called for the
demobilization of the rebels by Dec. 5. Both the Contras and the
Bush administration regard that deadline as essentially meaningless
because the presidents specified that the demobilization had to be
voluntary.
   D'Escoto said the United States could speed the peace process by
converting the humanitarian aid being received by the rebels to
demobilization aid.
   The Bush administration has insisted that the rebels must
continue to receive U.S. food, clothing, shelter and medical
supplies until after the Feb. 25 national elections in Nicaragua.
   That, the administration says, will give the Sandinistas
additional incentive to hold free and fair elections.
</TEXT>
