<FIRST>r w PM-HUDSued     11-14 0552</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-HUD Sued,560</SECOND>
<HEAD>HUD Lender Sues, Alleging Unfair Audits Tainted Its Reputation</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOHN KING</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A major lender in a federal housing program
involved in recent investigations of mismanagement is suing the
government, contending it was placed on probation because of faulty
audits.
   ``It seems as if HUD just doesn't want to deal with the fact
that the audit findings are incorrect,'' Fred Benton, chairman of
Benton Mortgage Co., said Monday. ``Apparently HUD was fishing for
scapegoats.''
   The company filed the U.S. District Court suit Monday against
the Department of Housing and Urban Development. A second suit
seeks a court order to force HUD to give final approval to two
Benton-financed projects whose mortgages are in limbo because of
the allegations against the lender.
   HUD spokesman William Glavin said the department had no comment
on Benton's lawsuits.
   The first lawsuit alleges that HUD unconstitutionally denied the
Knoxville, Tenn.-based lender a chance to rebut the charges in an
audit issued early this year by the department's inspector general.
   The report alleged that Benton had approved inflated mortgages
on more than a dozen projects, allowing the company to collect
higher fees and developers excessive subsidies because those
payments are based on the mortgage amount.
   Benton said the auditors violated generally accepted auditing
procedures and ignored evidence that HUD had approved the rents
cited in the report as being excessive.
   The suit alleged the auditors ``violated their duty to report
accurately and fairly the findings of their own investigation.''
   That suit also alleged that the department's Mortgage Review
Board could not objectively judge Benton's case because it is
headed by HUD assistant secretary for housing, C. Austin Fitts, who
the company said has accepted the findings of the audit.
   The board has been scheduled for weeks to meet today to discuss
the Benton audit.
   The two projects involved in the second suit are the 352-unit
Pebble Creek Apartments in Arlington, Texas, and the 312-unit
Kingsley Park Apartments in Essex, Md.
   Benton approved mortgages for those properties through HUD's
co-insurance program, under which private lenders are given the
power to endorse HUD insurance on roughly 80 percent of the
mortgage amount.
   HUD approved the projects at several steps of the endorsement
process, but in March notified Benton it was withholding final
approval because of the audit findings.
   In the suit, Benton said it was losing more than $30,000 a month
on the two projects because it has been unable to keep its
commitments to the developers.
   Benton also alleged it was unfairly placed on probation and that
as a result has suffered a competitive disadvantage because all of
its HUD work must be approved in advance by the department.
   One lender in the co-insurance program, DRG Funding Corp., has
more than $500 million in defaulted loans. Benton, however, says it
has never filed a claim for a default and has had its reputation
sullied because of the political climate surrounding the HUD
investigations.
   ``We've bent over backwards to be helpful, cooperative and
patient,'' Fred Benton said in a statement. ``We have nothing to
hide. Every project we co-insured was approved by HUD every step of
the way.''
   Justice Department investigators have reviewed the audit and the
working papers used to compile it but have declined comment on the
investigation.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
