<FIRST>r w PM-WashingtonInBrief     11-14 0569</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Washington In Brief,580</SECOND>
<HEAD>Delegation Seeks Investigation of Seabrook Rulings</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Members of the Massachusetts congressional
delegation are calling for a Senate investigation after a federal
panel said the Seabrook, N.H., nuclear power plant should receive a
full-power license.
   Members of the delegation were incensed with a ruling Monday by
the three-member Atomic Safety and Licensing Board that upheld
emergency evacuation plans for Massachusetts.
   The ruling said that concerns raised last week about New
Hampshire's evacuation plan in a decision by a higher-level Nuclear
Regulatory Commission panel should not prevent Seabrook from
beginning commercial operations.
   ``This is perhaps the most irresponsible action that I have seen
taken by any administrative agency in the 28 years that I have been
in the United States Senate,'' said Sen. Edward Kennedy, D-Mass.
   The 571-page decision reached Nov. 9 and made public Monday took
Seabrook a step closer to a full-power license.
   The next step involves a 30-day review period by the NRC, a
public meeting by the full commission at which the NRC staff makes
its recommendations and a final decision on issuing a license by
the commission.
   Edward Brown of New Hampshire Yankee, the company that operates
Seabrook, predicted the plant would have a full-power operating
license by mid-January and would be operating at 100 percent within
three months.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>Justice Department Ending Appeals in Case Against CIA Official</NOTE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Justice Department is ending its court
appeals involving the delayed Iran-Contra case against former CIA
station chief Joseph Fernandez.
   Department spokesman Dan Eramian said Monday that the department
would not contest a Sept. 29 appeals court ruling that concluded
the power to appeal decisions on classified material rests in the
hands of Iran-Contra prosecutor Lawrence Walsh.
   Fernandez, an ex-CIA operative in Costa Rica, was scheduled to
go on trial July 24, but the Justice Department obtained an
emergency stay from the U.S. Court of Appeals in Richmond, Va.,
after the CIA said it needed to protect certain classified
information that Fernandez wanted to use in court.
   The material concerned three CIA locations, including stations
in Honduras and El Salvador, and three CIA programs in Costa Rica.
   Fernandez, who assisted Oliver North's secret Contra re-supply
network, is accused of obstructing the Tower Commission and the CIA
inspector general's office and making false statements in the
Iran-Contra affair.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>Democrats Call for Defense Cuts</NOTE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Congressional liberals are promising to push
for sweeping defense spending cuts in response to the sweeping
changes in Eastern Europe when Congress begins debate on its first
``post-Cold War budget'' in February.
   A dozen lawmakers, led by Rep. Barney Frank, D-Mass., said at a
Capitol Hill news conference Monday that they represent the
beginning of a growing coalition of legislators pushing for a shift
from defense to domestic spending.
   ``America's military budget _ the $305 billion that we've just
passed as an authorization and are about to pass as an
appropriation _ significantly exceeds America's needs in the
current world,'' Frank said.
   ``What you see emerging here is a coalition of people who want
to talk about realities,'' said Rep. George Miller, D-Calif. ``This
is our opening shot and we're going to be tough on the budget next
year. ... This is hardball politics.''
   Frank said supporters of defense cuts are not all liberals and
that Rep. Charles Stenholm, D-Texas, who heads the Conservative
Democratic Forum, has endorsed the idea.
