<SECOND>AM-Japan-Markets,0216</SECOND>
<HEAD>Dollar Up, Stocks At Record High</HEAD>
<DATELINE>TOKYO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The dollar ended higher against the Japanese yen
Tuesday, while share prices on the Tokyo Stock Exchange made up for
morning losses and broke a record high set the previous day.
   The dollar finished unchanged from its opening at 143.80 yen, up
0.25 yen from Monday's close of 143.55 yen. The currency ranged
between 143.60 yen and 143.85 yen.
   The Nikkei Stock Average of 225 selected issues gained 18.52
points, or 0.05 percent, ending the day at 35,768.64, yet another
high. The index had reached a record Monday at 35,750.12, with a
86.92-point gain.
   Dealers said the index recovered when institutional investors
bought steel issues, expecting no immediate trend changes in
foreign exchange and interest rates.
   In currency dealings, the dollar-yen rate was moving narrowly,
as market players were reluctant to make major moves ahead of a
series of releases of U.S. economic indicators later this week, as
well as the auction for U.S. government bonds, said a foreign
exchange analyst with New Japan Securities Co.
   Among the major releases are the U.S. retail price index for
October, due out later Tuesday.
   The analyst said the West German mark, which had been bought
earlier, was lower due to profit-taking.
