<FIRST>r a PM-SFQuake     11-14 0293</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-SF Quake,0303</SECOND>
<HEAD>Energy Secretary Tours Quake-Hit Marina District</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto FX1</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JAMES O. CLIFFORD</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SAN FRANCISCO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Energy Secretary James Watkins toured the
earthquake-shattered Marina district, and praised San Franciscans
for the way they reacted to the disaster.
   Watkins' 40-minute walking tour took him past buildings that
were knocked from their foundations or burned in the Oct. 17 quake,
which measured 7.1 on the Richter scale, killed 66 people and did
an estimated $7 billion in damage.
   ``I am extremely impressed with the way this was handled,''
Watkins said.
   The secretary said several ambassadors had told him they admired
the way local officials and the public reacted to the disaster.
   ``There was no panic and a minimum of looting,'' Watkins said.
``There was positive control and people listened to those in
authority.''
   The tour covered about eight blocks of the largely residential
Marina district, which was built on landfill dumped in San
Francisco Bay to form the foundation for the 1915 Panama Pacific
International Exposition.
   John Ulrich, a spokesman for Pacific Gas &amp; Electric Co., said
power has been restored to most of 5,000 homes in the 100-block
area.
   Many of the apartment houses on the tour had yellow police lines
around them, meaning occupants are allowed to enter just for brief
periods. About 40 dwellings remain completely off-limits.
   Rubble from the demolished structures was taken to the Zanker
Road Recycling Facility in San Jose where workers sifted through it
and pulled out anything that seemed valuable.
   The material _ including such items as diplomas, paperback books
and kitchen utensils _ will be brought back to San Francisco this
week where it will be sorted and organized for distribution to the
owners, said city spokeswoman Suzanne Drabble.
</TEXT>
