<HEAD>Trial Set for Former FBI Agent Accused of Espionage</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LOS ANGELES (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A federal judge set May 15 for the third
trial of former FBI agent Richard W. Miller, accused of selling
documents to a Soviet agent.
   Miller was arrested in 1984 on espionage charges and remained in
custody until his release on bond last month.
   U.S. District Court Judge Robert M. Takasugi, who set the trial
date Monday, took over the case from U.S. District Court Judge
David V. Kenyon, who withdrew after overseeing the first two trials.
   A jury deadlocked in the first trial.
   Miller was convicted in the second trial and sentenced to two
life terms plus 50 years in federal prison. An appeals court
overturned the conviction, saying Kenyon improperly allowed
polygraph tests to be admitted as evidence.
   A Soviet emigre, Svetlana Ogorodnikov, and her husband, Nikolay,
entered guilty pleas in the case and are serving sentences in
federal prison.
   Defense attorneys argue Miller was attempting to revive his
flagging career with a misguided attempt to infiltrate the Soviet
espionage agency, the KGB.
