<FIRST>r a PM-NynexSettlement     11-14 0494</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Nynex Settlement,0512</SECOND>
<HEAD>Tentative Accord in Long Phone Strike</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By LARRY NEUMEISTER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Nynex Corp. said it had reached a tentative
accord with two unions to end the last of the strikes that began in
August against regional telephone companies around the country.
   The company said Monday that the Communications Workers of
America and the International Brotherhood of Electrical Workers had
agreed to end the walkout that disrupted installation, repair and
directory assistance services to 10.5 million customers in New York
state and New England.
   However, CWA spokesman Steve Rosenthal insisted his union's
leaders had yet to approve the deal, which hinged on settlement of
a dispute over health care costs. The CWA negotiating committee was
scheduled to resume considering the accord today, he said.
   ``How the company wants to paint it is their business. We think
the statement was premature,'' Rosenthal said.
   The tentative three-year pact would raise wages 3 percent in the
first year and 1.5 percent in each succeeding year, said Nynex
spokesman Tony Pappas.
   It was the CWA's president, Morton Bahr, who first let slip in a
Washington, D.C., speech Monday that the two sides had resolved the
contentious issue of health insurance. The primary dispute was over
Nynex efforts to shift some costs presently borne by the company
onto workers.
   ``We have saved our health care,'' Bahr told an AFL-CIO
convention. ``There are no premiums.''
   Robert Silva, a spokesman for the IBEW in Boston, said the talks
progressed quickly after phone company officials agreed to continue
paying all health benefits.
   ``We look at it as a total victory,'' Silva said.
   About 60,000 workers in the two unions have been on strike for
100 days at Nynex subsidiaries New York Telephone and New England
Telephone, which serve New York, Connecticut, Rhode Island,
Massachusetts, New Hampshire, Vermont and Maine. CWA represents
40,000 New York workers and IBEW has 20,000 workers in New England.
   The bitter dispute, in which one striker died after being struck
by a car on a picket line and the company reported numerous
incidents of vandalism, began Aug. 6. At that time, 200,000 workers
struck four regional ``Baby Bell'' companies in 20 states,
including Nynex, Ameritech in the Midwest, Pacific Telesis in the
West and Bell Atlantic in the West.
   The other walkouts ended within weeks. Nynex was said to have
more to lose because its systems are in aging Eastern cities where
operating costs are higher.
   The company said the tentative pact was reached after it agreed
to pay all workers' health benefits and the unions agreed to give
up a bonus and profit-sharing plan that would have given them an
annual bonus of 1 percent of their annual pay.
   Nynex Chairman William C. Ferguson called the tentative accord
``a realistic solution to a very difficult set of issues facing not
only our company but the entire nation.''
   Nynex blamed the strike for a 14.8 percent decline in
third-quarter profits.
</TEXT>
