<HEAD>Most of Nation Enjoys Indian Summer</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   Snow fell in North Dakota early today but most of the nation
enjoyed an Indian summer.
   Unseasonably warm weather prevailed from the southern Plains to
the southern and middle Atlantic Coast states. Temperatures in the
50s, 60s and 70s were reported in many cities east of the Rockies.
   Snow fell on Bismarck, N.D., and rain dampened parts of Alabama.
   On Monday, strong southerly winds ahead of a cold front crossing
the central United States helped push temperatures into the 70s as
far north as southern Michigan.
   Thirty-two cities reported record high temperatures for the
date, including Flint, Mich., where the high of 71 degrees was also
the warmest on record for so late in fall. Other cities with record
highs for the date included Buffalo, N.Y., at 68 degrees, and
Columbia, S.C., at 86 degrees.
   The high for the nation Monday was 90 degrees at McAllen, Texas.
   Showers and thunderstorms also developed over southern Texas,
southern Louisiana and southern Mississippi Monday. Rain dampened
the northern Pacific Coast, while snow fell on parts of Montana and
northern Maine.
   Other reports at 3 a.m. EST:
   _East: Albany, N.Y. 48 fair; Atlanta 61 partly cloudy; Boston 51
fair; Charleston, S.C. 59 foggy; Chattanooga 56 cloudy; Cincinnati
57 fair; Cleveland 55 fair; Detroit 57 windy; Hatteras 70 fair;
