<FIRST>r a PM-MarcosProperty     11-14 0265</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Marcos Property,0274</SECOND>
<HEAD>Skyscraper Once Owned by Marcos Auctioned for $77 Million</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By VERA HALLER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A Wall Street skyscraper allegedly bought by
Ferdinand Marcos with money looted from the Philippine treasury was
auctioned off for $77 million.
   The 66-story office tower sold Monday is one of four New York
buildings owned by the late Philippine president and presently tied
up in an ownership dispute and in wrangling with the government of
his homeland.
   One of the other buildings, the Herald Center near Macy's
department store, sold last week for $25 million, and two other
buildings in prime locations are to be auctioned as well.
   The government of Philippine President Corzon Aquino is trying
to recover funds it accuses Marcos of spiriting out of the country
when he fled to Hawaii. He died in Honolulu in September.
   The tower at 40 Wall St. was sold at a foreclosure auction to a
group of investors led by real estate developer Burton J. Resnick,
who also was involved in a bid for the building in August.
   The previous bid of $108.6 million fell through when the buyers
were unable to come up with the money before an October closing
date.
   ``You just have a generally declining real estate market in
Manhattan, particularly in Wall Street,'' said Stephen Estroff, the
court-appointed special master in charge of the auction, explaining
the price difference.
   The bid was $77 million plus $100, just enough to top the bid
put in by the mortgage holder, Citibank, to ensure the purchase
price covered the bank's debts.
</TEXT>
