<FIRST>r a PM-Deaths 1stLd-Writethru a0497 11-14 0828</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Deaths, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0497,0868</SECOND>
<HEAD>Eds: CORRECTS day of death in 1st graf of Josef item to Monday, sted
Tuesday. PMs separates moved as a0482 on Josef and on sports wire on Victor
Davis.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Franz Josef</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>VADUZ, Liechtenstein (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Franz Josef II, Prince of
Liechtenstein, died Monday after a long illness at age 83.
   Franz Josef II was the 12th ruler of the 270-year-old nation,
last remnant of the ``Holy Roman Empire.''
   His 51 years as head of state spanned the rise of this tiny
democratic state from an underdeveloped and rural country to a
sophisticated industrialized nation with one of the world's highest
per-capita incomes.
   He took office in 1938, succeeding his uncle, Prince Franz.
   He made history when he used his powers to force the formation
of a national coalition government after Austria became part of the
Nazi Reich, and paid an official visit to Hitler in March 1939.
   After the war, Franz Josef led the country in resisting Soviet
demands to extradite some 500 Russians, including Grand Duke
Vladimir Cyrillovich, heir to the throne of All the Russias, who
had sought shelter in Liechtenstein.
   In 1984 he handed over his executive powers to his son, Hans
Adam. But he retained the ceremonial role of head of state, and
continued to meet many well-wishers every year during the
festivities marking his birthday on Aug. 16, a public holiday.
</TEXT>
<BYLINE>Oliver Francis Naquin</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Oliver Francis Naquin, commander of a sunken
submarine whose rescue captured national attention 50 years ago,
died Monday from an obstruction of the pancreas at age 85.
   Naquin commanded the submarine Squalus, which sank during a
trial dive off the New Hampshire coast in 1939. He and 32 sailors
were rescued by a diving bell that was lowered from the surface and
attached to the hatch of the Squalus. Twenty-six others died.
</TEXT>
<BYLINE>Rogaciano Mercado</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MANILA, Philippines (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Rogaciano Mercado, a veteran
legislator who served under five Filipino presidents, died Monday
of a heart attack at age 73.
   He was elected to Congress from Bulacan province in 1953 and
served for nearly 20 years until the late President Ferdinand
Marcos dissolved the legislature after declaring martial law in
1972.
   In 1984, Mercado was reelected to the newly constituted National
Assembly and served until 1986.
   Mercado also served as minister of public works and highways
under President Corazon Aquino.
   In the May 1987 congressional election, Mercado was elected to
the House of Representatives.
</TEXT>
<BYLINE>Fred Lutz</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>TOLEDO, Ohio (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Fred Lutz, a literature and film critic for
The Blade, died Sunday of an apparent heart attack at age 52.
   Lutz also edited the newspaper's book review page, published in
its Sunday entertainment section.
   Lutz joined The Blade in 1966 after stints with the U.S. Army
and the insurance industry. For four years, he was a general
assignment reporter who also wrote movie and theater reviews. He
transferred to the newspaper's promotion department for 12 years
before becoming a full-time critic.
   Surviving Lutz are his wife, Cheryl, an assistant managing
editor at The Blade; two daughters, Holly Poll and Ann; a son,
David; a sister, Patricia Lutz Talbut; his father, Fred; his
stepmother, Betty; and two grandchildren.
</TEXT>
<BYLINE>Donald MacLean</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>PHILADELPHIA (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Donald MacLean, who was president of St.
Joseph's University from 1976 to 1986, died Monday of cancer at age
59.
   During his presidency, St. Joseph's received university status
from the state, developed the College of Business and
Administration, established a college to administer night classes
and expanded graduate offerings in all fields.
   His fund-raising efforts gave the university a new library and
student recreation center.
   From Philadelphia, he went to Loyola University of Chicago to
serve as vice president for campus ministry.
   In August, he moved to Mobile, Ala., to serve as president of
Spring Hill College but became ill just three weeks later.
</TEXT>
<BYLINE>Victor Davis</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MONTREAL (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Victor Davis, a former world-record swimmer and
1984 Olympic gold medalist, died Monday from injuries incurred in a
hit-and run accident on Saturday at age 25.
   Davis set a world record when he won the 200-meter breaststroke
in the 1984 Olympics. He also won silver medals in the 100-meter
breaststroke and 400-meter medley relay.
   In the 1986 World Championships at Madrid, Davis won a gold
medal in the 100-meter breaststroke and a silver medal in the 200.
   Davis was fourth in the Olympic 100-meter breaststroke at Seoul
in 1988 and won a silver medal in the medley relay.
   Davis retired from competition in July to devote himself to a
pool safety company he helped found.
</TEXT>
<BYLINE>Wendell Davis</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>GRAND RAPIDS, Mich. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Wendell C. Davis, former president of
Steelcase Inc., died of congestive heart failure at the age of 90.
   After five years at the helm of the world's largest manufacturer
of office furniture, Davis in 1966 joined Kindel Furniture Co. as
president until he retired at the age 78.
</TEXT>
