<FILEID>AP-NR-11-14-89 0613EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r i PM-Israel-Elections     11-14 0475</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Israel-Elections,0492</SECOND>
<HEAD>Shamir's Bloc Makes Advances in Union Elections</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ALLYN FISHER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>JERUSALEM (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Prime Minister Yitzhak Shamir's right-wing
Likud bloc scored substantial gains in nationwide trade union
elections billed as a referendum on Likud's stance on Middle East
peace, returns showed today.
   However, the left-of-center Labor Party also claimed victory in
Monday's voting, saying it had cut Likud's momentum from recent
victories at the polls.
   Results released by Israel radio today showed that with more
than 90 percent of the vote counted, Likud won 27.5 percent, an
increase over its current 22 percent.
   Labor, Likud's partner in the coalition government, garnered
more than 55 percent support, just slightly more than its present
standing.
   The remaining votes went to three smaller left-wing parties.
   The elections were for leaders of the Histadrut Labor
Federation, a traditional Labor stronghold. The 1.5 million-member
organization helps determine Israeli labor policies and owns a
major chunk of the nation's farms and industries.
   Likud leaders claimed the electoral showing was a boost to
Shamir as he headed to Washington for talks with President Bush on
Wednesday about efforts to start Israeli-Palestinian peace talks.
   ``I can only say Likud has increased its strength in the
Histadrut by about 25 percent. This is a significant increase under
difficult conditions, in a game it is not used to playing in,''
Shamir said on the radio before boarding an airplane for his 11-day
U.S. trip.
   ``I think it is a serious achievement,'' Shamir added. ``I can
explain the addition to our strength on the basis of Likud's
political achievements.''
   Shamir had called the elections a national referendum on his
stance for talks with Palestinians which include an adamant refusal
to include the PLO in negotiations or trade territory for peace.
   Labor favors a more conciliatory approach, including withdrawing
from parts of the occupied West Bank and Gaza Strip in exchange for
peace.
   Labor saw the results as a victory because it stopped a
worrisome electoral losing streak to Likud. The right-wing bloc has
won national and local elections in the past year.
   Analysts also noted that Likud fell short of its goal of
attaining one third representation on the Histadrut's governing
council, which would have meant blocking exclusive Labor control.
   Labor Party leader and Vice Premier Shimon Peres, interviewed
after television projections Monday night, claimed his party had
emerged victorious.
   ``This shows the public has given renewed confidence to the
Labor Party and we will reach new heights,'' he said.
   In the elections, about 1.5 million Israelis chose delegates to
the 1,501-member Histadrut Conference, which selects the
organization's governing board. Voter turnout was more than 50
percent, Israeli media reported.
   The Histadrut, which is Hebrew for ``union,'' was founded in
1920. It in effect helps formulate national employment policies by
negotiating nationally binding wage and pension agreements with the
government.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
