<FIRST>r a PM-FarmSearch     11-14 0504</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Farm Search,0522</SECOND>
<HEAD>State To Seek Death Penalty For Copelands</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOSH LEMIEUX</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>CHILLICOTHE, Mo. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The state will seek the death penalty
for a couple accused of killing three men they employed on their
northwestern Missouri farm.
   Ray Copeland, 75, and his 68-year-old wife Faye were charged
Monday at the Livingston County Courthouse with three counts of
first-degree murder.
   County Prosecutor Doug Roberts and Missouri Attorney General
William Webster announced the decision to seek the death penalty at
a news conference before the Copelands were arraigned in separate
proceedings.
   Asked why the state would seek an execution of an elderly
couple, Webster said: ``It isn't the death penalty because of the
age. It's the death penalty because of the alleged offenses here.''
   The decision to seek capital punishment in the case was based on
allegations that the victims were killed for money and to cover up
another crime, he said.
   The Copelands' public defenders accused Webster of mounting ``a
media event or even a media circus.''
   ``We both feel strongly that Ray and Faye's rights are being
severely compromised by the daily flood of baseless innuendo,
particularly in light of their frail health,'' said attorneys
Barbara Schenkenberg and David Miller.
   Miller represents Mrs. Copeland, and Ms. Schenkenberg represents
Copeland.
   The victims were killed with gunshots to the head and buried on
farms where Copeland had done odd jobs for several years. Police
have said the men were transients who Copeland hired to buy cattle
with bad checks.
   The Copelands were not charged Monday for the death of a fourth,
unidentified man whose body was found in another barn more than a
week after the Oct. 16 discoveries of the first three bodies.
Prosecutors were reviewing evidence in the fourth case.
   Sheriff Leland O'Dell said a search for nine more former
Copeland employees would continue in the county. About 100 sites
already have been searched, he said.
   The Copelands were charged Oct. 9 with conspiracy to steal
cattle with bad checks from an account set up in August for an
employee. The conspiracy charge was dismissed Monday.
   At the arraignment, bond was set at $500,000 for each. A joint
preliminary hearing was scheduled Nov. 29.
   Copeland was emotionless and silent; his wife sobbed throughout
her separate proceeding and tried to make a statement before being
dissuaded by Miller, her attorney.
   The victims were Paul J. Cowart, 21, of Dardanelle, Ark., John
W. Freeman, 27, of Tulsa, Okla., and Jimmie Dale Harvey, 27, of
Springfield, Mo.
   Harvey's mother, Ann H. Netherton, filed a wrongful death suit
Monday alleging the Copelands ``knowingly, willfully and
wrongfully'' shot and killed her son.
   ``I feel very sad because it's all so senseless,'' Mrs.
Netherton said. ``He was a nice guy. He wouldn't have hurt
anybody.''
   The suit seeks damages, but does not specify them.
   Rose Marshall, Freeman's mother, said she found no solace in the
state's decision to seek the death penalty.
   ``There couldn't be justice,'' she said. ``They could never
replace my boy.''
</TEXT>
