<HEAD>Former East German Leader Recovering After Operation</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BERLIN (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Former East German leader Erich Honecker, whose
fall from power spurred three weeks of breathtaking changes in his
country, is in poor health and being treated at his home, a
government newspaper said today.
   ``My husband is sick, that means he has not yet recovered,'' the
Communist youth newspaper Young World quoted Honecker's wife,
Margot, as saying.
   Honecker's resignation Oct. 18 ushered in whirlwind changes in
East Germany, including freedom to travel to the West and promises
of free elections. Egon Krenz, 52, was picked to replace the
ailing, 77-year-old hard-liner.
   Honecker underwent gallbladder surgery in August and made no
public appearance until early October, when he led 40th anniversary
celebrations of the founding of East Germany.
   Following Honecker's resignation, West German news media
reported his condition worsened and that he had been hospitalized.
   Young World quoted Mrs. Honecker, East Germany's former
education minister, as saying her husband was being cared for at
their home outside East Berlin.
   ``He is not hospitalized but at home, where he is being
medically cared for,'' the newspaper quoted Mrs. Honecker as saying.
