<FIRST>r i PM-Philippines-Blast     11-14 0341</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Philippines-Blast,0351</SECOND>
<HEAD>Blast Kills One at Election Office Five Days Before Moslem Autonomy
Vote</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By CLARO CORTES</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MANILA, Philippines (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A powerful explosion ripped through
the national headquarters of the election commission today, five
days before a controversial referendum on Moslem autonomy. Police
said one person was killed.
   Police said the 7:05 p.m. blast damaged the left side of the
Commission on Elections building, destroying four rooms. The blast
also damaged windows in the nearby Manila Roman Catholic cathedral.
   A parttime maintenance man was killed, police said. Officials
said several employees were working overtime in the building at the
time of the explosion.
   There were no arrests and no one claimed responsibility. But
police said two passersby were taken into custody for questioning.
   Commission officials had requested additional security at the
building because of reports that Moslems planned a demonstration
there Wednesday to protest the upcoming referendum on regional
autonomy for Mindanao and other southern islands.
   On Sunday, voters in 13 southern provinces and nine cities will
decide whether to join an autonomous regional government aimed at
satisfying demands for self-rule by the estimated 4 million
Filipino Moslems and ending a nearly 20-year-old Islamic revolt.
   But critics and supporters of the autonomy plan, approved by
Congress and signed by President Corazon Aquino in August, fear it
may fall short of its goals and anger both Christians and Moslems.
   The Moro National Liberation Front, the main Moslem rebel
organization, has opposed the autonomy plan as inadequate.
   In Jiddah, Saudi Arabia, Front leader Nur Misuari claimed
President Corazon Aquino's government was setting the stage for a
``genocidal war'' against Filipino Moslems.
   The Front has been waging a nearly 20-year insurgency to
establish a separate state in Mindanao and other southern islands.
A cease-fire with the government has been in effect since Mrs.
Aquino met Misuari in 1986 on the island province of Sulu.
   Before the Moslem rebellion peaked in the mid-1970s, an
estimated 50,000 people were killed and thousands more fled for the
nearby Malaysian state of Sabah.
</TEXT>
