<FIRST>r a PM-RiotTrial     11-14 0354</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Riot Trial,0362</SECOND>
<HEAD>Policeman's Trial to Proceed With Disputed Second Black Juror</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: Lead prospects uncertain. Trial resumes early afternoon with
procedural matters.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By RICHARD COLE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MIAMI (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A state appeals court turned aside defense
objections and allowed a second black to remain on the jury for
today's start of the manslaughter trial of a policeman in the
shooting of a black motorcyclist.
   The court Monday upheld the decision of Circuit Judge Joseph
Farina, who maintained the defense opted to exclude the juror
illegally on the basis of race. Farina seated the juror Friday even
though defense attorneys have a right, known as peremptory
challenge, to exclude jurors without showing cause.
   The appeals court said there was no need to dissolve the
six-member jury and start the painstaking selection process all
over again.
   ``Obviously I'm happy that we're able to proceed,'' said
prosecutor John Hogan. ``We think it's a fair jury.''
   Hogan said the session would begin this afternoon, although
opening arguments may not start until Wednesday because of pretrial
motions and problems with sequestering a jury.
   The ruling came after three weeks of jury selection in the case
of officer William Lozano, who is charged in the slaying of the
motorcyclist and the death of his passenger in an ensuing crash
Jan. 16. The incident set off three days of riots.
   Lozano's attorney, Roy Black, accepted one black juror and
strenuously denied that race was behind his trying to exclude the
second black juror, Ezra Simmons.
   Black said he wanted Simmons excluded because, as a union
representative, Simmons defended workers fired for alleged drug
abuse. The defense intends to emphasize the victims' drug use to
support its contention that Lozano shot Clement Lloyd, 23, in
self-defense because the motorcyclist was trying to run him over.
   With Simmons, the jury consists of two blacks, one Hispanic and
three non-Hispanic whites.
   The issue of race has hung over the case since the shooting.
Three times in the 1980s, the killing of black men by white
officers or the officers' acquittals on similar charges have
sparked rioting in the Miami area.
</TEXT>
