<FIRST>r a PM-FaxNews 1stLd-Writethru a0455 11-14 0365</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Fax News, 1st Ld - Writethru, a0455,0370</SECOND>
<HEAD>New York Times, Journal of Commerce Announce Facsimile Newspapers</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: SUBS 3rd graf pvs, `The Times ...' to FIX typo in `compilation.'
Longer version moved on financial wires</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By STEFAN FATSIS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The familiar thump of the newspaper landing on
the doorstep may give way to the beep and hum of the fax machine
for some of the far-flung readers of The New York Times and The
Journal of Commerce.
   Both papers announced Monday they were joining the growing
number of newspapers that transmit abbreviated editions via
facsimile machine the day before publication.
   The Times said it would fax a four- to six-page newspaper to
subscribers in the Far East beginning in January. The service, to
be called Times Fax, will be a compilation of news, features and
editorials.
   The newspaper said the venture is geared to businesses and
travelers in Japan and would be sent the evening before the paper
is published. It will include shorter versions of top stories in
the newspaper.
   ``This service will reach people in parts of the world that
currently cannot receive the Times on a timely basis,'' said Times
Publisher Arthur Ochs Sulzberger.
   The price of the faxed paper, which won't contain advertising,
has yet to be determined, said Times spokeswoman Nancy Nielsen.
   Targeted subscribers include Japanese brokerages, banks and
other financial institutions, Japanese and U.S. companies and
hotels.
   The Journal of Commerce, which calls itself the nation's oldest
daily business newspaper, said it began a facsimile service
available in the United States and Europe on Monday.
   The two- to three-page edition, dubbed Datafax, is a summary of
news in the paper and is transmitted daily around 3 p.m. EST, the
newspaper said.
   After 3{ months of promotional discounts and free service, The
Journal of Commerce service will cost $650 domestically and $1,057
in Europe.
   The Journal of Commerce, which is owned by Knight-Ridder Inc.,
specializes in world trade and transportation news. It has a
circulation of about 25,000 nationwide.
   USA Today and The Hartford Courant have been selling facsimile
editions for some time, while other newspapers reportedly are
planning to do so.
</TEXT>
