<FIRST>r i PM-Soviet-Lithuania     11-14 0389</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Soviet-Lithuania,0400</SECOND>
<HEAD>Entire Lithuanian Politburo Summoned to Moscow</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ANDREW KATELL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MOSCOW (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The ruling Politburo has summoned the entire
Communist leadership of Lithuania to a meeting that likely will
press Kremlin efforts to rein in the Baltic republic's drive for
sovereignty, legislators said today.
   The Politburo of the Baltic republic's Communist Party will
travel to Moscow on Wednesday, but there was no immediate detail on
what would be discussed. The Politburo normally meets on Thursdays.
   Lithuanian sources said Moscow may want to discuss calls for the
republic's party to declare itself independent from the national
party, a series of laws that the Kremlin declared unconstitutional
on Friday, or to head off an attempt to follow Baltic neighbor
Estonia in annulling the 1940 decision to join the Soviet Union.
   Soviet Foreign Ministry spokesman Yuri D. Gremitskykh, asked
about the report at a news briefing, said he had no information but
that it was not unusual for a republic's entire party leadership to
attend a Politburo session.
   Eduardas Vilkas, a deputy of the Supreme Soviet parliament, said
he thought the topic would be proposals that the Lithuanian party
declare itself independent from the national Communist Party.
   That topic is to be discussed at a congress of the Lithuanian
party scheduled for Dec. 19.
   Soviet President Mikhail S. Gorbachev has criticized suggestions
that the Communist Party in the republics spin off into independent
organizations.
   Kazimieras Motieka, a second deputy, said the topic might be a
declaration by the Presidium of the Supreme Soviet parliament
canceling several decisions at the heart of the drive by republics
for more political, cultural and economic autonomy.
   The Presidium declared that laws passed by Lithuania, Latvia,
and Estonia in the Baltics as well as Azerbaijan in the southern
Caucasus region giving them the right to veto national laws,
violate the Soviet Constitution.
   Lithuanian law that restricts republic citizenship to those who
lived there when the law was passed earlier this year, have a
permanent job or means of subsistence also violate the
constitution, it declared.
   It also found that laws adopted by the three Baltic states that
make Lithuanian, Latvian and Estonian the official language in the
respective republics violate the rights of some people to hold a
wide range of jobs.
   The Presidium urged the republics to rewrite their laws.
</TEXT>
