<FIRST>r i PM-Kohl-Poland 1stLd-Writethru a0510 11-14 0537</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Kohl-Poland, 1st Ld - Writethru, a0510,0548</SECOND>
<HEAD>Kohl Lays Flowers at Death Camp, Seeks To Reassure Poles</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: LEADS with 4 grafs to UPDATE with governments signing declaration;
Picks up 3rd graf, `He did ...'; DELETES now-redundant last three grafs,
`Kohl was ...'</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DEBORAH G. SEWARD</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WARSAW, Poland (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Chancellor Helmut Kohl of West Germany
laid a wreath at the Auschwitz death camp today after assuring
Polish lawmakers that a reunified Germany would not threaten Polish
security.
   Later, Kohl and Solidarity Prime Minister Tadeusz Mazowiecki
signed a declaration that opens the way for greater economic and
political cooperation and repeats West German commitments to
respect Poland's western border.
   The 78-point document aims to ``heal the wounds of the past
through understanding and reconciliation.'' Leaders expressed hope
for a new chapter in relations between West Germany and Poland, led
by the first non-Communist government in the East bloc.
   At Auschwitz, Kohl laid the flowers at the ``wall of death,''
where the Nazis had prisoners of different nationalities shot, and
another in Birkenau where crematoriums incinerated the bodies of
millions of Hitler's victims.
   He did not speak. Polish television broadcast part of the visit
live to the nation to somber music of Chopin.
   Kohl was accompanied by Heinz Galinski, head of the West German
Jewish Community Council; and Poland's only rabbi, Menachem
Joskowicz of Warsaw. At least 2.5 million Jews were among the
victims at Auschwitz and Birkenau.
   A small group of people held up banners outside the camp saying
``Victims of the war demand compensation,'' and ``All of Germany is
responsible for the crime of genocide and the plunder of Poland and
Europe.''
   Kohl was not the first West German leader to visit Auschwitz;
Chancellor Helmut Schmidt visited the camp in 1977.
   But Kohl's five-day trip, which ends today, comes at a time of
tremendous upheaval in the East bloc and less than a week after
East German's Communist leaders punched holes in the Berlin Wall
and let their people travel freely to the West.
   The rapid pace of change in East Germany, where lawmakers on
Monday endorsed opposition calls for free elections, has prompted
serious discussion about prospects for a reunified Germany.
   The idea worries many Poles and West German officials have
sought during Kohl's visit to allay fears that a reunified Germany
would threaten Polish security.
   They have told their Polish hosts that such a Germany would
respect a 1970 treaty that pledges Bonn to respect the Oder and
Neisse rivers as Poland's western border.
   Some West German conservatives have suggested that reunification
be sought within 1937 borders, which encompass about one-third of
Poland.
   Speaking Monday to Polish lawmakers, Kohl stressed that a
reunified Germany would not be a threat to Poland because it would
be part of a new European order based on cooperation and respect
for freedom.
   Kohl's remarks were reported by Senate Marshal Andrzej
Stelmachowski, a Solidarity adviser.
   Stelmachowski said Kohl told the lawmakers that ``In general, he
thinks that the process of reunification would be a process
connected with the general process of unification of Europe, and
the 21st century would not be a time of national states.''
   Stelmachowski said he was ``satisfied'' with Kohl's appearance.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
