<HEAD>Inmate Accused of Shooting Two Detectives is Captured</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: LEADS with 2 grafs to move up procedural lapses. PICKS UP 3rd
graf pvs, `Detectives Keith ...'</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By BILL STIEG</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Authorities today investigated the procedural
lapses that resulted in the slaying of two detectives by a prisoner
riding alone in the back in their car with a gun stolen from a
police locker, police said.
   The inmate, Stoney Harrison, 25, was recaptured at his
girlfriend's house shortly before midnight Monday, 10 hours after
the shootings, said Sgt. Mary Wrensen.
   Detectives Keith L. Williams, 34, and Richard J. Guerzon, 46,
were slain near LaGuardia Airport while driving Harrison back to
the Rikers Island prison.
   The detectives had driven Harrison to a prosecutor's office to
take a lie detector test and discuss a plea bargain.
   Police believe Harrison stole a gun from a detective squad
locker in the district attorney's office, where he had been left
unattended for a short time Monday.
   On the way back to Rikers, Harrison was seated alone in the back
seat, with the two detectives in front _ a violation of police
procedure, said Police Commissioner Richard Condon.
   Authorities said the detectives' car was pulled over to the side
of the highway before the shots were fired. Guerzon, who had been
driving, was shot twice in the head; Williams was shot twice in the
back and once in the head.
   Witnesses said they saw Harrison drag the driver out of the car
and into the roadway. He then got back in the car but ran off after
failing to start the engine.
   Harrison was handcuffed when the detectives put him into the
car, but witnesses said he had somehow managed to remove the cuffs.
A pair of handcuffs was found in the front seat.
   Police said Harrison has an extensive criminal record dating
back to 1984, including drug and assault charges. In 1985, he was
sentenced to a year in jail for biting off a girlfriend's ear.
   He was charged in July with strangling another girlfriend, and
in October, Harrison and his mother were arrested on charges of
conspiring to murder a witness against him in the July murder. He
allegedly had his mother offer $2,000 to a hit man who turned out
to be an undercover detective.
   The last time two New York police officers were killed in the
same incident was in April 1978, when two officers were slain in a
gunfight with occupants of a car they stopped.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
