<HEAD>Hoss Starts Consultations, Aoun Threatens Christian Leaders</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MOHAMMED SALAM</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BEIRUT, Lebanon (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The new premier today began talks aimed
at forming a government to end Lebanon's 14-year-old civil war, but
a defiant general warned Christian leaders about cooperating with
Moslem politicians.
   ``Those who take part in the (Salim) Hoss' Cabinet better stay
in Hoss land,'' Gen. Michel Aoun, leader of Christian forces, was
quoted as saying by the independent newspaper An-Nahar.
   Aoun, 54, a Maronite Catholic, controls most of the
310-square-mile Christian enclave northeast of Beirut.
   Four Maronite Parliament deputies held a meeting in the northern
Batroun province, outside the area of control of Aoun's 20,000
troops, to decide whether to take part in the new government.
   The four included Phalangist leader George Saadeh, the main
Christian negotiator in 23 days of parliamentary deliberations at
Taif, Saudi Arabia, last month which produced a peace pact to end
the civil war.
   Aoun has rejected the Taif accord because it failed to include a
clear timetable for the withdrawal of Syria's 40,000 troops from
Lebanon.
   Fearing Aoun's wrath, most Christian legislators who
participated in the Taif talks have not returned to the Christian
enclave.
   Parliament deputies met at an airbase in Syrian-policed north
Lebanon Nov. 4 to ratify the Taif accord and elect Rene Mouawad
president.
   Mouawad, 64, also a Maronite, named Hoss on Monday to form a
National Reconciliation government representing all the warring
factions in Lebanon with the objective of ending the civil strife.
   Aoun rejected Mouawad's election and declared opposition to
Hoss' government, which he said ``will be an unconstitutional
government.
   ``It will not be a national reconciliation government. It will
represent one side,'' Aoun said. ``Even if the whole world
recognizes it, Hoss' Cabinet will be a government operating in the
shadow of Syrian occupation.
   ``Governments cannot survive only on foreign recognition.
Peoples topple governments,'' Aoun warned.
   Aoun, in an interview with The Associated Press, said his ``war
of liberation'' against the Syrians was ``continuing, through
political and diplomatic means.
   ``I will stand fast until Syria explodes from within,'' he said.
