<FIRST>r i PM-Hungary     11-14 0232</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Hungary,0239</SECOND>
<HEAD>Reform Countries In Majority But Danger Lurks, Foreign Minister Says</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BUDAPEST, Hungary (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Foreign Minister Gyula Horn said in an
interview published today that opponents of change could sabotage
reform efforts in East bloc countries by exploiting the disgruntled
masses.
   Hungary, Poland and the Soviet Union have been at the forefront
of East bloc reform, but the rapid changes in East Germany and the
recent leadership change in Bulgaria have left only Czechoslovakia
and Romania still resisting political reform.
   Even Czechoslovakia today, however, substantially loosened
travel restrictions on its citizens.
   In an interview with the government daily Magyar Hirlap, Horn
said the Warsaw Pact countries ``who want to carry out reform have
attained genuine majority.''
   The changes in East Germany reinforced Hungarian reforms, he
said, but he cautioned against being ``overly optimistic,'' saying
``there are still too many dangers lurking in wait.''
   ``I consider (the) economy in every Warsaw Treaty member state
to be in a critical state, which is a serious source of danger,''
Horn said, noting that economic reforms would take years to have an
effect.
   ``Disappointed and resigned people who are in a state of apathy
and cannot directly feel the effects of political changes on their
own living conditions can be easily exploited by the political
circles that want to slow down or halt transformation,'' Horn said.
   ``This is the gravest danger,'' he added.
</TEXT>
