<FIRST>r a PM-Dartmouth-SouthAfrica     11-14 0292</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Dartmouth-South Africa,0302</SECOND>
<HEAD>Students Cheer Dartmouth Decision to Divest South African Investments</HEAD>
<DATELINE>HANOVER, N.H. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Anti-apartheid protesters cheered Dartmouth
College's decision to stop investing in companies that do business
in South Africa.
   ``It was inevitable that the trustees divest. All credit should
be given to students, faculty and community members who have
applied pressure for the past 20 years,'' said Gamal Abouali, a
senior who protested Dartmouth's investments.
   The Ivy League school announced Monday it will sell by the end
of the year its $11.5 million in investments in companies doing
business in South Africa.
   The undergraduate faculty council voted unanimously in 1988 to
call on trustees to divest completely within a year. However, the
decision came unexpectedly at a weekend trustees' meeting at which
divestment was not on the agenda.
   Dartmouth President James Freedman read the decision at a
faculty meeting to cheers from the 250 to 300 students present.
   The trustees said in a statement that the investments have
``great symbolic meaning'' and the continuing dispute over them
``undermine Dartmouth's ability to achieve some of its educational
goals.''
   The board noted that Dartmouth's investments in companies doing
business with South Africa have declined from 15 percent, or $63
million, of its endowment in 1985 to less than 2 percent this year.
   The college already had accepted prohibitions against
investments in South African firms, financial institutions making
loans to the South African government, companies supplying goods
and services involved in the enforcement of apartheid and firms
doing business in South Africa that didn't adhere to certain
employment policies.
   In 1985, students built shanties on campus to protest apartheid.
In 1986, 12 students attacked the shanties with sledgehammers. A
confrontation over moving the shanties off campus resulted in 18
arrests.
</TEXT>
