<HEAD>Brazilian Elections at a Glance</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Brazil</HEAD>
<DATELINE>RIO DE JANEIRO, Brazil (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A look at Brazil's presidential
election Wednesday:
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
   AT STAKE _ The presidency. It will be the first direct election
for president in Brazil since 1960.
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
   CANDIDATES _ Twenty-one people, from parties ranging from the
Communists to the official party of the 1964-85 military regime,
are running. To become president, one candidate must win more than
50 percent. Otherwise, the top two vote-getters will compete in a
runoff Dec. 17.
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
   ELECTORATE _ Eligible to vote are 82.5 million of the nation's
150 million people. All Brazilians between 18 and 69 must vote.
Voting is voluntary for those aged 16-17, 70 and over, and
illiterates.
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
   ISSUES _ The main issue is the economy. Brazil's foreign debt is
$110 billion, the largest in the Third World. Its internal debt is
$120 billion, and inflation in the past year was 1,300 percent.
About 75 percent of the people earn less than $180 a month.
