<FIRST>r i PM-CoastGuardStrike     11-14 0265</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Coast Guard Strike,0275</SECOND>
<HEAD>Canada's Coast Guard Goes On Strike</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: Amounts are in Canadian dollars.</HEAD>
<DATELINE>VANCOUVER, British Columbia (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Canada's Coast Guard went on
strike for higher wages today, throwing up picket lines on the East
and West coasts.
   The 2,200 unionized seamen, deckhands, stewards and cooks _ who
conduct sea rescues, go on Customs and fishery patrols and work
aboard government research vessels _ said they would return only in
emergencies. None were immediately reported.
   At the Canadian Forces Base Equimalt on Vancouver Island, a Navy
tug was prevented from going on duty when crewmen belonging to the
union, Public Service Alliance of Canada, refused to cross picket
lines, said a base spokesman.
   Coast Guard spokesman Craig Dougans said the agency would ``do
the best we can, but you can expect some disruptions.''
   Ted Maher, a director for the Department of Fisheries and
Oceans, said Navy ships may be pressed into service for fishery
patrols within Canada's 200-mile limit.
   Gary Owen, a union spokesman, said the ``entire search and
rescue operation will not be functioning.'' However, the union and
Transport Canada, the nation's transportation department, agreed to
respond to emergencies.
   The union has been without a contract for two years.
   One of the major items in dispute is the wage disparity between
crewmen on the East and West coasts. A West Coast Guardsman earns
an average of $23,000, or about $1,900 more a year than an eastern
counterpart doing the same job.
   The union turned down an offer from Canada's Treasury Board for
a 3{-year contract with raises totaling 14.4 percent.
</TEXT>
