<FILEID>AP-NR-11-14-89 1305EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>u w PM-US-EastGermany 3rdLd-Writethru a0559 11-14 0909</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-US-East Germany, 3rd Ld-Writethru, a0559,880</SECOND>
<HEAD>Bush Hails Travel Liberalization Move by Czechs</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: Inserts new grafs 10-12 with new White House comments; picks
up at pvs 10th graf, Bush is; deletes last 4 grafs to shorten</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By BARRY SCHWEID</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Diplomatic Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   President Bush today hailed a move by
Czechoslovakia to ease travel restrictions on its citizens and said
it is just the latest sign that ``Europe will someday be whole and
free.''
   ``I'm very pleased at the move in Czechoslovakia,'' Bush told
reporters at the outset of an Oval Office meeting with Tunisian
President Ben Ali.
   ``The people of Czechoslovakia have the same aspirations for
freedom that others have, and I would expect we'd see further
changes there, just as we have seen in Poland, Hungary and in the
German Democratic Republic (East Germany.) So it's a very good and
encouraging step,'' the president said.
   ``This is further manifestation that Europe someday will be
whole and free. (Soviet President Mikhail S.) Gorbachev talks about
`a common home'; we talk about a Europe whole and free. It's a most
exciting time.''
   Bush was responding to the announcement in Prague by Czech
Premier Ladislav Adamec that Czechoslovak citizens will no longer
need exit permits to travel outside the country, a major reform in
one of the last hard-line East bloc nations. He did not say when
the new rule would take effect, but it was expected to begin in
January.
   Asked if he planned to stop in Brussels to brief the NATO allies
after the Dec. 2-3 shipboard summit off Malta with Gorbachev, the
president said, ``We are thinking right now how we might stay in
touch with our allies. That is very, very important.''
   Asked if he was concerned that the changes in Europe were
happening too fast, Bush said, ``No, I don't think it's moving too
fast and I don't know of anybody in my administration who feels
that it's moving too fast.''
   Earlier, two well-placed U.S. officials said that Bush, facing
pressure from Democrats to respond more strongly to the changes in
Eastern Europe, is considering a meeting with allied leaders in
Brussels after next month's summit.
   The aim of a meeting in the NATO capital would be to show
Western unity on the future of Germany and to discuss new political
and military strategy in light of the quickening change that is
enveloping Eastern and Central Europe.
   Asked if Bush favors the $738 million aid package for Poland and
Hungary nearing approval in the Senate, White House spokesman
Marlin Fitzwater said, ``We're generally supportive. We'd like to
get billions if we had them.'' Bush proposed a smaller package.
   Asked if the United States would like to see free elections in
East Germany, Fitzwater said, ``We would like to see the people's
rights and wills determined by themselves, and we think there is a
very constructive course of freedom under way in East Germany and
the other parts of Eastern Europe.''
   Fitzwater praised the lifting of travel restrictions in
Czechoslovakia and added, ``We're not surprised by anything
anymore.''
   Bush is under pressure from Democratic leaders in the Senate and
House to respond more energetically to developments in the
communist world.
   Renewing his criticism, Senate Majority Leader George Mitchell,
D-Maine, said today it was ``regrettable'' that Bush, through his
spokesman, has rejected the idea of going to Berlin to express
American satisfaction with the ``symbolic destruction'' of the wall
or to normalize trade relations with the Soviet Union.
   ``While the president has rejected all of these, he has reversed
himself on issues before and I hold out out hope he will do so
again,'' Mitchell told reporters.
   Mitchell on Monday had urged Bush to travel to the Berlin Wall,
now breached by unrestricted travel by East Germans, convene a
meeting of the Western allies and suspend trade restrictions
against the Soviet Union.
   House Democratic Leader Richard A. Gephardt of Missouri,
meanwhile, said: ``At the very time freedom and democracy are
receiving standing ovations in Europe, our president is sitting
politely in the audience with little to say and even less to
contribute.''
   The administration did not respond publicly. But privately, the
two officials, speaking on condition of anonymity, said Bush was
weighing a meeting with leaders of the 15 other North Atlantic
Treaty Organization countries after the Dec. 2-3 talks in the
Mediterranean with Gorbachev.
   At the top of the agenda would be the future of Germany, which
Vice President Dan Quayle said in a speech Monday inevitably will
be reunited once East Germany shakes off communism.
   ``East Germany is East Germany because of the communist
system,'' Quayle told the Republican Governors' Association at
Hilton Head Island, S.C. ``Do away with the communist system and
it's Germany.''
   Despite Quayle's confident statement, a number of U.S. officials
acknowledged in interviews that the Bush administration had to move
cautiously for two reasons: Nervousness in Western Europe about
restoring Germany to full strength and in Moscow about U.S.
intentions.
   A militarily powerful Germany has been at the center of two
devastating wars in Europe this century.
   The officials told The Associated Press that Gorbachev might
propose to Bush in their talks a reunited but neutralized Germany.
U.S. strategy, they said, is to undertake preparations within NATO
and the European Community for the potential integration of a
single Germany into a democratic Europe.
   ``On this, the Europeans will have to take the lead,'' a U.S.
official said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
