<FIRST>r a PM-StudentStrike     11-14 0257</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Student Strike,0267</SECOND>
<HEAD>UMass Students Boycott Classes to Protest Budget Cuts</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By TRUDY TYNAN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>AMHERST, Mass. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Students boycotted classes at the
University of Massachusetts for a second day today to protest state
budget cuts.
   The 25,000-student university said it planned no sanctions
against those involved and had no count of the students taking part.
   ``It's not massive. It's partial,'' Provost Richard D. O'Brien
said.
   The protest was prompted by a $25 million cut in aid to public
higher education to help eliminate the Massachusetts budget deficit.
   Lisa Nelson, a junior from Sunderland who helped organize the
protest, said students today targeted science classes, which many
professors agreed to cancel.
   ``It's been building up all fall,'' said John Schmertzler, a
junior from West Springfield. ``They cut out a thousand classes and
they expect us to pay more when we can't even get into a class.''
   The Amherst campus' share of the cutback is $6.4 million and
resulted in a $350 increase next semester in the university's
mandatory fees to $1,465. The fees come in addition to tuition,
which was raised 8 percent this fall to $1,512.
   University spokeswoman Joan Ashwell said the faculty union
estimated that 60 percent of classes were canceled Monday.
   The faculty union made it clear it supported the students.
   ``You need to convince your representatives and senators that
you are a force to be reckoned with _ that you will support them if
they support you,'' history Professor Bruce Laurie, union vice
president, said at a rally Monday.
</TEXT>
