<SECOND>AM-GOP Governors,210</SECOND>
<HEAD>New Head of GOP Governors Says Stick to Your Positions</HEAD>
<DATELINE>HILTON HEAD ISLAND, S.C. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Gov. John Ashcroft of Missouri
became chairman of the Republican Governors Association Tuesday and
advised GOP candidates of 1990 to stake firm clear positions on
abortion and other major issues and then stick to them.
   Gov. Carroll A. Campbell Jr. of South Carolina was elected vice
chairman of the association, and will take over as chairman next
year.
   Ashcroft said he felt ``voters were cheated'' in campaigns for
the elections one week ago because the candidates did not deal
adequately with real concerns, such as crime, drugs and education.
   ``We need to state our own positions, not be on the defensive
and not be characterized by others,'' Ashcroft said.
   Gov. Mike Hayden of Kansas added, ``First you tell them where
you stand and then you stand where you tell them. That's good
advice for every Republican candidate.''
   Campbell held up a newspaper clipping and quoted Democratic
Gov.-elect L. Douglas Wilder of Virginia as urging his party to
take mainstream positions, battling crime and drugs and holding the
line on taxes.
   ``They're trying to be Republicans,'' Campbell said. ``We've
been doing that all along.''
   The governors commented at a news conference winding up their
meeting.
