<FIRST>r w PM-Congress-EasternEurope 3rdLd-Writethru a0562 11-14 0715</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Congress-Eastern Europe, 3rd Ld-Writethru, a0562,670</SECOND>
<HEAD>Senate Moving Toward Compromise on Aid to Poland, Hungary</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: Inserts new 9th graf with White House comment; picks up 9th
graf pvs, Differences between</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By LAWRENCE L. KNUTSON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Senate moved today toward agreement on a
compromise $738 million plan to spur the rebirth of democracy and
free enterprise in Poland and Hungary.
   The bipartisan compromise was announced less than 48 hours
before Lech Walesa, leader of Poland's Solidarity union movement,
was to address a joint meeting of Congress.
   Formal approval of the plan, expected today, would be an
important step toward resolving a long dispute over the size of the
program.
   ``It almost sounds trite to say that what is happening in
Eastern Europe is mind-boggling, but thank God for it,'' Sen.
Gordon Humphrey, R-N.H., said as the debate resumed this morning.
   ``We must do all we can afford, as quickly as we can, to help
make these changes in Eastern Europe irreversible,'' Humphrey said
as the Senate approved his amendment to earmark 10 percent of the
private enterprise funds contained in the bill for Solidarity and a
Polish free-enterprise association.
   Humphrey said the change was necessary to permit some of the
money to move quickly, cutting through bureaucratic delays as
applications are considered.
   Senate Democrats originally had sought a three-year
authorization level for the two East European nations of $989
millions, while Republicans called for a $585 million ceiling.
   All the proposals, including the $840 million authorized earlier
by the House, overshadow the total $455 million proposed over the
last several months by President Bush.
   Asked today if Bush favors the $738 million aid package for
Poland and Hungary nearing approval in the Senate, White House
spokesman Marlin Fitzwater said, ``We're generally supportive. We'd
like to get billions if we had them.''
   Differences between the House and Senate versions of the aid
package are expected to be resolved quickly.
   The Senate builds on key elements advocated by the president,
including an Enterprise Fund to help both nations move away from
communist centralized planning and toward free-market systems.
   The funds, intended to help both countries establish free-market
systems, would allocate $260 million for Poland and $65 million for
Hungary.
   In recognition of Poland's serious economic problems, the bill
allocates $657 million for that country while Hungary would receive
$81 million.
   Senate Republican Leader Bob Dole of Kansas noted Democrats had
dropped a $200 million credit stabilization plan for Poland, a plan
he said Republicans believed would be unworkable and merely add to
Poland's large foreign debt.
   The compromise trimmed the rival Democratic plan to ``a more
realistic size,'' Dole said.
   Poland and Hungary remain members of the Warsaw Pact, according
to Dole, who said the compromise has a number of safeguards,
including barring any funds from being used for military aid to
Cuba or Nicaragua.
   Meanwhile, congressional Democrats opened fire on the
president's approach to other crucial events in Eastern Europe,
including East Germany's decision to open the Berlin wall 28 years
after it was erected across the divided city.
   Senate Majority Leader George Mitchell said today it is
``regrettable'' that Bush has rejected the idea of going to Berlin
to express American satisfaction with the ``symbolic destruction''
of the wall or to normalize trade relations with the Soviet Union.
   ``While the president has rejected all of these, he has reversed
himself on issues before and I hold out out hope he will do so
again,'' the Maine Democrat told reporters.
   Mitchell said he also believes Bush should convene an emergency
conference of the Western allies to chart the future of Europe in
the light of events in the Soviet Union and Eastern Europe.
   ``Obviously the post-World-War II era is coming to an end,
marked by the upheaval in Eastern Europe and the new economic era
order in Western Europe,'' Mitchell said.
   It is important, he said, that the United States now assert its
full leadership in ``shaping that new order.''
   Presidential spokesman Marlin Fitzwater said Monday he couldn't
``foresee any set of circumstances at this moment that would
induce'' Bush to go to Berlin.
   On Monday, the Senate unanimously adopted a resolution welcoming
the opening of the wall, condemning it as a ``symbol of
oppression'' and demanding.
</TEXT>
