<HEAD>Firefighter Gives Mouth-To-Mouth To Kitten</HEAD>
<DATELINE>DURHAM, N.C. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A firefighter used mouth-to-mouth
resuscitation and oxygen to revive a pair of 2-week-old kittens
overcome in a fire that damaged a house.
   ``We did it once before on a puppy, but it was too late,'' said
Fire Department rescue specialist A.J. Green. ``I do love animals.''
   No people were injured in the blaze, but firefighters found four
kittens in the house and took them outside, said Battalion Chief
D.R. Maynard.
   A neighbor began chest massage on a kitten that was not
breathing and Green began mouth-to-mouth resuscitation on a second
unresponsive kitten. The other two kittens died.
   After both surviving kittens started to breathe on their own,
Green gave them oxygen. Following about 20 minutes of rescue
efforts, a neighbor took the now-active kittens home for the night.
