<FILEID>AP-NR-11-14-89 1406EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r a AM-People-Reagan     11-14 0261</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-People-Reagan,0269</SECOND>
<HEAD>Reagan to Kids: Make a Bad Thing Good</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Former President Ronald Reagan told troubled
teen-agers Tuesday that everything happens for a purpose _ even bad
things.
   ``I know you haven't had it easy,'' Reagan told more than 120
young people at Covenant House. ``There must have been times when
you wondered if anyone cared.''
   ``People do care,'' he assured them. ``I care about you and
that's why I'm here.''
   Covenant House shelters about 25,000 runaway, homeless or
neglected children each year at houses in three nations and seven
states. Reagan visited the agency's building in the Chelsea section
of Manhattan, where he handed out writing pens and spoke briefly.
   Reagan told the youths that when he was young his family was
poor and his father was an alcoholic. ``There were nights when I
was angry and frustrated and wondered, `Why?'''
   But he said he was sustained by his mother, who insisted
``everything happens for a reason. ... Down the road something good
will happen, and you'll realize it was for the best.''
   He gave an example: During the Depression he went to the
Montgomery Ward department store in his Illinois town and applied
for work. When he was turned down, he recalled, ``I felt about as
low as could be.''
   But Reagan next went to a radio station and was hired as a
sportscaster, beginning his road to Hollywood and the White House.
   If he had gotten the first job he'd applied for, Reagan said,
``I'd still be in working at that Montgomery Ward.''
</TEXT>
