<FIRST>r a AM-TaxCommissioner     11-14 0200</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Tax Commissioner,0205</SECOND>
<HEAD>Former West Virginia Tax Commissioner Sentenced</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CHARLESTON, W.Va. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A former state tax commissioner who
blamed his failure to file federal income tax returns on marital
and business problems has been placed on probation for three years.
   Richard L. Dailey, 49, who pleaded guilty to misdemeanor charges
of failing to file returns in 1985 and 1986, was sentenced Monday.
   U.S. District Judge John T. Copenhaver Jr. also ordered Dailey
to perform 150 days of public service and to pay $95,000 in taxes
plus penalties on $295,000 he earned during 1985 and 1986. If he
fails to make the payments within three years, his probation will
be extended by two years, Copenhaver said.
   The judge told Dailey he didn't impose a fine because Dailey's
``tax obligation is staggering in comparison to your lack of
assets.''
   Dailey said he experienced marital problems and business
setbacks in coal mining equipment leasing ventures.
   ``I made substantial mistakes and caused humiliation and
embarrassment to my son and my father,'' said Dailey, who was state
tax commissioner during 1972-77 under Gov. Arch Moore.
   Dailey, who works for an insurance firm in Columbus, Ohio, said
he expects to earn $40,000 this year.
