<FIRST>r i AM-Egypt-Iraq     11-14 0410</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Egypt-Iraq,0425</SECOND>
<HEAD>Egyptians-Iraqis to Discuss Deaths of Egyptians in Iraq.</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CAIRO, Egypt (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Senior Egyptian and Iraqi officials will
discuss the welfare of about 1 million Egyptian workers in Iraq
following reports that more than 100 Egyptians died in Iraq last
month.
   ``The foreign ministry is following the issue of Egyptian
workers in Iraq and this will be reviewed during the meeting of the
higher joint Egyptian-Iraqi committee on Saturday,'' said Foreign
Minister Esmat Abdel-Meguid.
   The government has been handling the affair cautiously, and he
did not refer to reports in the state-owned al-Akhbar newspaper
that 102 bodies of Egyptians had been flown to Cairo in October,
compared with one body in October 1988.
   The newspaper also reported that ``thousands'' of Egyptians were
buried in Iraq because they did not leave enough money for their
bodies to be sent home, and that Egyptians were badly treated by
Iraqis.
   Al-Akhbar also reported that starting Wednesday, Iraqi Airlines
would start 10 extra flights from Baghdad to Cairo daily for the
next three months to fly home Egyptian workers.
   It quoted Iraqi officials in Baghdad as saying return of
Egyptian workers in large numbers was not because of
``maltreatment'' but because soldiers discharged after Iran-Iraq
war ended were taking jobs once held by Egyptians.
   Some Egyptian government officials and the opposition newspaper
al-Wafd attribute most of the Egyptian deaths to friction between
Iraqis and Egyptians and rivalries over jobs.
   Al-Akhbar said Prime Minister Atef Sedki demanded a full report
from Egypt's ambassador to Baghdad, Ibrahim Ouf.
   On Monday, a senior security official at Cairo International
Airport confirmed that about 100 Egyptian bodies were flown from
Iraq in October, an average of ``three or four'' a day. The
official also said autopsies have been ordered to determine the
cause of the death.
   Al-Akhbar said that Iraqi certificates initially attributed
death to ``bullet wounds'' and later switched to other formulas
like ``killed in an accident'' or ``died in butane gas cylinder
explosion.''
   The Egyptian government has been cautious in handling the issue
because of close ties between the two countries. Millions of
Egyptians work abroad, about 1 million in Iraq.
   One Egyptian security official said he did not believe the
bodies arriving in recent weeks were related to reports of an
August explosion and fire at an Iraqi missile plant that killed 700
people, including many Egyptians. The high death toll was reported
by Iraqi dissident sources and the London newspaper The Independent.
</TEXT>
