<FIRST>u a PM-DeathWish 1stLd-Writethru a0464 11-14 0519</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Death Wish, 1st Ld - Writethru, a0464,0526</SECOND>
<HEAD>Right-to-Die Case Goes Before Georgia Supreme Court</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: LEADS with 5 grafs to UPDATE with arguments, CLARIFY that McAfee's
delay in carrying out death was not related to appeal. PICKS UP 5th graf,
`The trial ...'</HEAD>
<DATELINE>ATLANTA (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Lawyers for the state asked the Georgia Supreme
Court today to rule that a quadriplegic with no hope of improvement
has the right to shut off the machine that has kept him alive for
four years.
   Assistant Attorney General William M. Droze argued that Larry
McAfee's death if he disconnected his ventilator would not be
suicide but the result ``of the natural progression of his
condition.''
   McAfee, whose motorcycle injuries four years ago left him
paralyzed from the neck down and dependent on a respirator, already
won consent in September from a Superior Court judge to disconnect
the breathing apparatus.
   After ruling in the case, Judge Edward Johnson instructed
Attorney General Michael Bowers to appeal to the state's highest
court for guidance in future cases.
   McAfee decided to delay shutting off his ventilator, offering
others more time to try to talk him out of it. But his attorney,
Leigh Smith, urged the court to uphold the ruling, saying that
would amount to an affirmation of ``a competent adult's right to
refuse medical treatment.''
   The trial judge held that McAfee's constitutional right to
privacy permitted him to disconnect the respirator and that the
state had no interests outweighing McAfee's right to refuse medical
treatment.
   With a friend's help, McAfee devised a method by which he could
turn the respirator off himself. But he also asked to be given a
sedative so that he would not suffer once the respirator was
removed.
   On that point, Johnson ruled that any physician or lawman who
administered a sedative to McAfee or who helped him in turning off
the respirator would not be subject to any civil or criminal
liability.
   Bowers said Monday the issue is legally murky and should be
resolved by the state's highest court.
   ``The question, I believe, is whether what we have is explicit
and clear enough concerning the right of a competent person to
refuse medical treatment,'' Bowers said.
   ``We believe that if you take the law as a whole and try to
distill it, you come up with this right. But we acknowledge there
is nothing one could point to and say, `There is this right.'''
   Bowers and other parties in the lawsuit have urged the Supreme
Court to use the case to write guidelines allowing people similarly
situated in the future to gain the removal of life-sustaining
equipment through non-judicial means.
   The state already has such guidelines for people who have signed
a ``living will'' directing their physicians not to engage in
heroic means to preserve them in a non-conscious state.
   Although most ``right-to-die'' cases involve comatose patients
or those who cannot make their wishes known, a case similar to
McAfee's came up in July. A Michigan man paralyzed in a surfing
accident died after a court decided he had the right to have his
life-support system shut off.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
