<FIRST>r i AM-Dhaka-Dogs     11-14 0380</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Dhaka-Dogs,0393</SECOND>
<HEAD>Dhaka Tries to Curb Its Dogs</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By FARID HOSSAIN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>DHAKA, Bangladesh (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Squads of men armed with iron tongs and
a poisonous liquid are prowling this populous city's streets and
alleys with one mission in mind: kill as many dogs as possible.
   Authorities say they have no choice.
   ``We know it is cruelty to kill the dogs,'' says Dr. Rezaul
Karim, chief veterinarian of the Dhaka Municipal Crporation. ``We
must find out an alternative.''
   Karim said the explosion in the numbers of stray dogs has
created a potential health threat. About 30 dogs are killed daily,
which puts only a small dent in a population estimated in the tens
of thousands.
   He said eight dog-killing squads began operating in Dhaka on
Oct. 1 and killed at least 646 stray dogs in one month. ``The
campaign will continue'' until all stray dogs are killed, he said.
   The dogs are caught by large iron tongs and a poisonous solution
of magnesium sulfate is injected into the heart, killing the
animals within two minutes, said a corporation veterinarian who
spoke on condition of anonymity.
   There is no dependable estimate of the street dog population of
the capital, the country's largest city with 6 million people.
Officials believe the figure is between 70,000 and 80,000.
   ``September-October is the breeding season for dogs when their
population sometimes reaches 80,000,'' said Karim.
   The corporation pays 10 takas, about 30 cents, to the dog
catchers for every canine captured and killed.
   Authorities say the main complaints against the animals are that
they are likely to bite people and spread rabies.
   There are no statistics on dog bites, but newspapers often
report dogs attacking and biting people at night when streets are
deserted.
   An official of the Veterinary Public Health Department said
Japan has offered about $2.5 million for a project to vaccinate
stray dogs against diseases.
   The extermination has not evoked any public reaction. Few
Bangladeshis keep pets, and there is no branch of the Society for
Prevention of Cruelty to Animals in the country. In 1978, some
owners of pet dogs formed a kennel club, but it closed in 1980.
   ``The dog-killing campaign is deplorable,'' said Sadia
Chowdhury, a TV newscaster who was a member of the kennel club.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP891114-0103 </DOCNO>
