<FIRST>r w AM-US-CzechoslovakIndustry     11-14 0337</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-US-Czechoslovak Industry,310</SECOND>
<HEAD>Czechoslovakia Invites U.S. Participation in Munitions Conversion</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-US-East Europe</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By GENE KRAMER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Czechoslovakia, promoting a cautious brand of
reform, will convert part of its renowned munitions industry to
civilian production, a senior Prague official said Tuesday.
   U.S. businessmen are invited to join the new ventures and also
to use Czechoslovakia as a beachhead to potential Soviet and other
East European markets, Richard Sumann, director general of the
Foreign Trade Ministry, told the U.S. Chamber of Commerce.
   He spoke as Czechoslovakia, trailing its neighbors in political
reform, announced the lifting of restrictions on foreign travel by
its citizens.
   ``We are highly interested in the quickest conversion of
armament production capacities and shift toward the civil sector
production,'' Sumann said.
   His statements reflected recent cautious efforts by
Czechoslovakia to join the trend toward ``perestroika,'' or
restructuring, now bringing dramatic changes in its Warsaw Pact
neighbors, Poland, Hungary, the Soviet Union and East Germany. In
reforming the economy, ``we would like to intensify trade and
cooperation with the West,'' he asserted.
   Cooperation ``with the former arms producers could ... be of
great interest to foreign partners, because of the existing modern
capacities and qualified personnel in the Czechoslovak armament
industry,'' Sumann said.
   Czechoslovak industry, led by the Skoda Works of Plzen,
producers of tanks and artillery, has been considered a major
arsenal of the Soviet Union and other pact nations.
   Despite a long industrial tradition, the country's economy is
stagnating from ``overregulation, overtaxation and overspending,''
Sumann said, and one of the most important cost-cutting measures
will be ``overall reduction of armament production.''
   He gave no figures on the planned cut.
   Sumann also said his country needs ``more democracy in public
life,'' but emphasized a gradual approach to reform by the
hard-line communist leadership.
   The economic reform in Czechoslovakia will be gradual, he said.
``We prefer a pragmatic step-by-step approach, and are determined
to avoid chaos in the transition.'' He made no mention of
privatizing the country's many government industries.
</TEXT>
