<FIRST>u a PM-PaAbortion 2ndLd-Writethru a0613 11-14 0561</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Pa Abortion, 2nd Ld - Writethru, a0613,0570</SECOND>
<HEAD>Pennsylvania Senate Takes Up Stringent Abortion Bill</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: LEADS with 5 grafs to UPDATE with Senate taking up bill, quote
from legislator. PICKS UP 5th graf pvs, `Before the ...'</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MICHAEL BLOOD</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>HARRISBURG, Pa. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The state Senate today took up a bill
that could give Pennsylvania the most restrictive abortion law in
the country.
   If the measure is passed and signed as expected by Democratic
Gov. Robert Casey, Pennsylvania could become the first state to
take advantage of a U.S. Supreme Court ruling in July allowing new
curbs on abortion.
   The House approved the measure 143-58 last month. The Senate
Rules Committee on Monday endorsed the bill 11-5 without discussion.
   Sen. James C. Greenwood, a pro-choice Republican from suburban
Philadelphia, noted that anti-abortion forces held the votes to
pass the bill and said as the debate got under way, ``We're about
to cross an historic threshold.''
   Pennsylvania's Legislature has traditionally been strongly
anti-abortion.
   Before the Senate session, more than 100 anti-abortion activists
held a prayer vigil in the Capitol rotunda. Outside, several high
school students from suburban Philadelphia ripped open cardboad
boxes and wrote slogans saying, ``Come help to do the right thing _
Keep it legal ... Vote pro-choice.''
   ``We think this country was founded on choice and we need to
have choice in this country,'' said Lisa Bruno, a high school
senior.
   A few steps away was an anti-aborttion sign with a graphic
picture of an aborted fetus, an American flag and the words,
``Abortion, babies suffer brutal pain.''
   Pennsylvania's chapter of the National Organization for Women
said it had delivered 50,000 names on petitions and thousands of
letters from pro-choice advocates to the office of Lt. Gov. Mark
Singel, who presides over the Senate.
   The bill would require women to notify their husbands if they
plan to get an abortion; prohibit abortions because of the fetus'
sex; ban abortions after the 24th week of pregnancy except in cases
where the mother faces death or irreversible harm, and establish a
24-hour waiting period.
   Also, the proposal would regulate the medical use of tissue from
aborted fetuses, and doctors would be required to inform a woman of
the likely age of the fetus before performing an abortion and
explain the risks and alternatives.
   An attempt by Florida's Gov. Bob Martinez to take advantage of
the U.S. Supreme Court decision upholding a restrictive Missouri
abortion law fell flat last month when the Legislature flatly
rejected a package of bills.
   In Pennsylvania, senators favoring a pro-choice position have
usually accounted for fewer than 20 votes in the 50-member chamber.
   Sen. Roy Wilt, a pro-choice Republican, said he would offer
amendments calling for a referendum on the bill, eliminating the
requirement that husbands be notified, and revising the waiting
period so that women living 50 or more miles from a clinic would
have to make only one trip.
   Because of a maze of procedural rules, pro-choice senators were
expected to face a tough time getting the amendments even
considered. At least 26 members must first approve a motion to
consider amendments before any can be offered.
   Around the Capitol, there was no sign of the swarms of
protesters that gathered before the House vote. Senators said they
received more calls than usual, and mail on abortion was heavy.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
