<FIRST>r n AM-SportsTV     11-14 0238</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Sports TV,240</SECOND>
<HEAD>Baseball, Football Commissioners Defend Rise Of Cable Programming</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   National Football League Commissioner Paul
Tagliabue assured a Senate panel Tuesday that the Super Bowl would
not move to a pay-per-view broadcast during the 1990s.
   Baseball Commissioner Fay Vincent, also before the Senate
Judiciary subcommittee on anti-trust, monopolies and business
rights, defended his sport's decision to shift 175 games to cable
television next year.
   Sen. Arlen Specter, R-Pa., asked Tagliabue for a ``flat
commitment'' that fans would not be assessed a flat fee to view a
broadcast of the Super Bowl. Such a ``pay-per-view'' arrangement is
used for some top-draw boxing matches.
   ``For the balance of this century, we do not foresee
pay-per-view for the Super Bowl game,'' Tagliabue said, but
couldn't predict beyond that.
   Lawmakers at the hearing repeatedly reminded the commissioners
that their sports enjoy special antitrust law exemptions enabling
them to behave differently than many other businesses.
   ``As a New York sports fan, I have suffered through the myriad
of problems of the pending extinction of local sports coverage on
free television,'' Rep. Charles Schumer, D-N.Y., said in prepared
testimony.
   ``Baseball shares a special compact with Congress that provides
it with a more sweeping antitrust exemption than any other sport
enjoys. If all the fan gets in exchange for this exemption is less
baseball on TV, then major league baseball is letting down its side
of the agreement,'' Schumer said.
