<FILEID>AP-NR-11-14-89 1501EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r i AM-Balloonist     11-14 0670</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Balloonist,0690</SECOND>
<HEAD>British Tycoon Attempting Pacific Balloon Crossing</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By LARRY THORSON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>TOKYO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A British tycoon who set a hot-air balloon distance
record two years ago despite crashing into the sea is about to try
to break the record with a 6,200-mile flight across the Pacific.
   Richard Branson plans to lift off from southern Japan, possibly
as early as this weekend, with ballooning expert Per Lindstrand,
who was the pilot in the 1987 record-setting flight over the
Atlantic. If all goes well, they will touch down four days later in
California.
   ``The weatherman is God on this venture,'' Branson said. ``He's
got a difficult equation to work out.''
   Ideal weather would be no wind on takeoff, 200 mph winds in the
jet stream, and no wind for the landing.
   Getting ready for a perilous flight is not all Branson is doing
in Tokyo. Before the interview, he met with Transport Ministry
officials to seek more flights on his Virgin Atlantic Airways' new
London-Tokyo route.
   Later he was visiting Fujisankei Communications Group, the
Japanese media company that recently bought a quarter of Branson's
Virgin Music Group for $150 million.
   The 39-year-old Branson dropped out of school at 15 to
concentrate on business and is one of the richest men in Britain.
His adventures, which also include crossing the Atlantic by
speedboat, are as much free advertising for his company as personal
challenges.
   None of his money will be needed for the Pacific flight, he
said, refusing to estimate the cost if sponsors hadn't been found
for everything.
   ``All my adventures of this kind I've done on the basis that it
wouldn't cost us any money,'' he said.
   The balloon, said to be the largest ever built, is named Virgin
Otsuka Pacific Flyer, honoring Otsuka Pharmaceuticals, which makes
a popular health drink and is footing among other local costs the
upkeep of 60 people at the launch site.
   A Pacific balloon crossing has been done only once, in 1981 by
three Americans and a Japanese with a helium balloon.
   Branson said he and Lindstrand hope to take their balloon
possibly as high as 40,000 feet.
   ``A balloon has never attempted this before _ to push our
balloon into this very fast jet stream,'' he said, describing the
planned ascent into winds up to 200 mph.
   ``The top of the balloon might be going 150 mph and the bottom
might be going only 50 mph. As we're going in, we'll be clinging on
for dear life as the top of the balloon heads off at great speed
and hope we don't get left behind.''
   Many weather balloons break up in the jet stream, he said, but
they don't have his strong new fabric of metallic polyester film
bonded to nylon.
   Other possible downsides: bad weather, breakdown of compressors
that keep the gondola's air livable, malfunction of the propane
burners that provide the heat to keep the balloon aloft, sudden
decompression _ ``We have eight seconds to put on oxygen masks'' _
or some disaster that might force Branson and Lindstrand to skydive
from altitudes where the temperature is as low as minus 58.
   Their training has included skydiving and physical conditioning
to help ward off seasickness if they ditch at sea and have to wait
to be rescued, as happened in the 1987 Atlantic trip.
   At that time, the 21-story-high balloon briefly touched down in
Northern Ireland and then flew out of control and splashed into the
sea a mile of Scotland. Both fliers were pulled from the water, but
they were credited with a distance record of 2,280 miles from Maine
to the point of touchdown.
   ``I'm confident we won't lose our lives,'' Branson said. ``I'm
absolutely convinced it can be done. Whether we will succeed in
doing it the first time, we won't know for two weeks. But as with
anything else we do in life, if we fail the first time, we'll be
back again next year to make sure we finish the job off.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
