<FIRST>r i AM-East-Travel-Glance     11-14 0528</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-East-Travel-Glance,0542</SECOND>
<HEAD>Travel Restrictions in East Bloc at a Glance</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Czechoslovakia</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   Relaxed travel and emigration restrictions stemming from reforms
in the East bloc are allowing more East Eh the
West. The country-by-country situation:
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
   CZECHOSLOVAKIA _ Czechoslovakia, one of the last hard-line East
bloc nations, announced Tuesday it would no longer require exit
permits for travel outside the country. The governmuropeans to reacent
previously
had eased some restrictions but had kept the requirement for an
exit visa when traveling to the West.
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
   EAST GERMANY _ More than 3 million East German visitors have
crossed into West Germany since the Communist country opened its
borders Nov. 9. The government provides a travel visa to nearly
anyone who applies. The changes were prompted by the illegal exodus
of tens of thousands of people to the West and by massive
demonstrations. East Germans t Germany, as are ethnic Germans from the
East bloc, which helps
account for the huge emigration influx into West Germany this year.
The newly opened Berlin Wall could conceivably become a new passage
for East bloc visitors allowed to travel to other Warsaw Pact
nations like East Germany but who have difficulty getting
permission to go West.
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
   SOVIET UNION _ Requirements for travel documents and permission
to emigrate have eased tremendously in the last two years. On
Monday, the Soviet legislature gave preliminary approval to a bill
lifting most travel restrictions. It would allow emigration for
virtually anyone who has entry permission from another country and
no outstanding alimony obligations, criminal charges or recent
knowledge of state secrets. An estimated 200,000 will emigrate in
1989 and more than 2 million will make visits abroad. Most
emigrants go to the United States or West Germany.
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
   POLAND _ Any Polish citizen is eligible for a passport for all
countries and can travel without problem. The main problem for
Poles is not getting a passport, but getting a visa from the
countries they want to visit. It often takes weeks to get a visa at
the West German or U.S. embassies because so many people want to go
to those countries. In 1988, 6.5 million Poles traveled abroad,
including 1.5 million to the West.
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
   HUNGARY _ Beginning Jan. 1, 1989, Hungarians were allowed to
apply for five-year passports giving them the right to travel West
as often as they can afford. By June 30, Hungarians had made 3.8
million trips abroad, 18 percent up from the first half of 1987.
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
   BULGARIA _ Bulgaria in September passed a law similar to
Hungary's with passports issued for five years. Bulgarians who are
refused a travel document have a right to appeal the decision. As
in many East bloc countries, the major drawback to traveling West
is a shortage of convertible currency.
  
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
   ROMANIA _ In this most hard-line Warsaw Pact state, Romanians
are allowed to travel to the West only once every two years, and to
other East bloc countries once a year. Romanians under retirement
age are virtually prevented from traveling West at all except in
urgent family matters, although pensioners can travel more freely.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
