<FIRST>u a PM-BloodDisorder 2ndLd-Writethru a0558 11-14 0587</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Blood Disorder, 2nd Ld - Writethru, a0558,0599</SECOND>
<HEAD>Nationwide Ban Urged on Sale of Suspect Diet Aid</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: LEADS with 7 grafs to UPDATE with CDC saying 17 states and District
of Columbia reporting suspected cases, FDA finding no contaminants; PICKS
UP 8th graf pvs, `At least ...'; SUBS grafs 16-18 bgng `The presence ...'
to UPDATE with CDC list of states affected and CORRECT by deleting Mississippi.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ED MORENO</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SANTA FE, N.M. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Sen. Pete Domenici urged the government to
ban L-tryptophan, a dietary supplement suspected of causing a
potentially fatal blood illness in 17 states and the District of
Columbia.
   Health officials were investigating whether one death was caused
by the non-prescription remedy touted as ``nature's sleeping pill.''
   New Mexico on Monday banned L-tryptophan. Oregon's Health
Division recommended the product be withdrawn, and other states are
expected to issue warnings.
   The number of reported cases nationwide of the disorder
eosinophilia reached 81 Monday, said Rep. Bill Richardson, D-N.M.
The congressman was briefed by the national Centers for Disease
Control.
   The Food and Drug Administration over the weekend warned
consumers to temporarily stop taking L-tryptophan, which is sold in
health food stores to treat sleeplessness and premenstrual syndrome.
   Domenici, R-N.M., asked the FDA to go a step further and halt
L-tryptophan sales nationwide until the product's role in the
eosinophilia outbreak is known. ``The entire nation could be at
risk,'' he said.
   FDA spokesmen did not immediately return a call today, but the
CDC said in a statement that samples of tablets tested by the FDA
so far have turned up ``no obvious contaminants.'' The CDC said it,
too, is analyzing samples.
   At least 12 different brands of L-tryptophan have been
identified as having been used by the individuals who became ill in
recent weeks.
   Makers of L-tryptophan have said they don't believe their
product is to blame for the outbreak, although they said small,
disreputable companies may have produced contaminated batches.
   Eosinophilia is an abnormal elevation of a type of white blood
cells, known as eosinophils. Symptoms include severe muscle pain,
fever, joint pain and weakness.
   New Mexico Health and Environment Secretary Dennis Boyd said the
ban followed an investigation that ruled out other causes for the
outbreak.
   Most New Mexico health stores and drug stores have voluntarily
removed L-tryptophan from their shelves. The order, which is in
effect until further notice, required all retail dealers to pull
the product.
   State epidemiologist Dr. C. Mack Sewell said 30 cases of
eosinophilia have been reported in six New Mexico cities.
   Dr. David Fleming, deputy state epidemiologist in Oregon, said a
woman from his state took L-tryptophan, developed eosinophilia-like
symptoms in January and died in midsummer in another state while
seeking treatment. The Oregonian of Portland reported today that
investigators were looking to see if her death was related to
L-tryptophan.
   Tom Schafer, a spokesman for the Illinois Department of Public
Health, said Illinois would probably recommend its use be
discontinued pending an investigation. Alabama was issuing a
warning today not to use the product until more studies are done.
   Potential cases of eosinophilia has been confirmed in Arizona,
California, the District of Columbia, Florida, Georgia,
Massachusetts, Michigan, Missouri, Minnesota, New Jersey, New
Mexico, New York, Oregon, South Carolina, Tennessee, Texas, Vermont
and Virginia, the CDC said today.
   Sixteen people died nationwide in 1986 as a result of
hypereosinophilic syndrome, a form of eosinophilia, and 12 died in
1987, said Sandy Smith of the National Center for Health Statistics
in Washington.
</TEXT>
