<SECOND>AM-Pell-Senate,0296</SECOND>
<HEAD>Pell Says He'll Run Again</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ROBERT W. TROTT</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>PROVIDENCE, R.I. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Democratic Sen. Claiborne Pell said
Tuesday he would run for a sixth term, squashing rumors that he
would retire in the face of an expected strong challenge from
Republican Rep. Claudine Schneider.
   ``I am humble in asking this of the citizens of Rhode Island
because I am very grateful for the trust they have placed in me for
the past 30 years and I only hope they will continue to judge me
worthy of that trust,'' said Pell, who turns 71 this month.
   Pell, chairman of the Senate Foreign Relations Committee, said
he wanted to continue ``to be part of the rapidly changing
international landscape as the prospects for peace come
increasingly within our grasp.''
   Pell, first elected in 1960, is best known for legislation that
created the system of Pell grants for college students.
   Pell said Miss Schneider would be a formidable opponent.
   ``I like her, admire her as a woman and as a member of
Congress,'' he said. ``I think she does a good job, but I think
that I will continue doing a good job as a United States senator.''
   Although Miss Schneider has yet to formally announce her
candidacy, President Bush will be the guest of honor at a
fund-raiser for her in Rhode Island on Monday and she has benefited
from several Washington fund-raisers for those planning to run
Senate campaigns.
   She has raised at least $325,000.
   ``We've been operating under the assumption that Senator Pell
would run again,'' said Robert J. Rendine, Miss Schneider's
executive director.
   In 1984, Pell trounced Republican Barbara M. Leonard with 73
percent of the vote.
