<FIRST>r i AM-Bulgaria     11-14 0510</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Bulgaria,0525</SECOND>
<HEAD>Head of Official Rights Committee Complains of Inaction on Reform</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ROLAND PRINZ</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SOFIA, Bulgaria (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The head of Bulgaria's official human
rights group said Tuesday the government has delayed reform but he
hopes for faster action from leaders who took over for Todor
Zhivkov, the ousted Communist Party chief.
   Zhivkov, 78, resigned Friday after 35 years of enforcing a
rigid, orthodox line in Bulgaria. He was succeeded by Petar
Mladenov, 53, who served 18 years as foreign minister and is
considered more amenable to change.
   Konstantin Tellalov, chairman of the Human Rights Commission,
told The Associated Press he actively seeks legal reforms to
guarantee human rights. Independent activists, however, are
suspicious of the commission's role.
   Before and after the Human Rights Committee was set up about 1{
years ago, unofficial groups have been established that criticize
government policy on the environment, human rights and labor. Some
of their leaders accuse Tellalov's commission of promoting
government policy.
   Reports since Friday have indicated extensive changes are
imminent in the top ranks of the party and government, and Tellalov
expressed hope that would help the work of his organization.
   Tellalov was ousted from the ruling Politburo in the 1960s _ for
being too outspoken, it is said _ and afterward served as
ambassador to Canada and Venezuela. Most recently, he was Bulgarian
delegate to the U.N. committee on disarmament in Geneva.
   He also said official media had been reluctant to publish or
broadcast his appeals.
   As an example, Tellalov said, no publicity was given a
resolution the commission adopted in July urging the government to
determine who was responsible for bloody suppression of protests by
ethnic Turks two months earlier.
   ``Some 15 Bulgarian journalists attended the news conference
when we presented the resolution, but it was not published
anywhere,'' he said.
   At least seven people were killed in May when force was used
against ethnic Turks who protested an earlier campaign of force to
make them adopt Bulgarian names. Western diplomats later said up to
30 people may have been killed.
   Tellalov said Tuesday the commission resolution also called on
the Turks, officially referred to as a Moslem minority, to
reconsider leaving the country and asked Turkey to treat the new
arrivals well.
   About 320,000 of the 1.5 million Bulgarian Turks fled religious
and cultural discrimination, but nearly 60,000 have returned
because they could not find jobs or housing.
   During the interview Tuesday, Tellalov said his commission was
pressing for constitutional changes to limit the death penalty,
which he said was included in 30 sections of the penal code.
   When asked about the approximately 200 political prisoners
reported held in Bulgaria, he acknowledged it was realitvely easy
to be convicted of a political crime.
   Members of his commission had been allowed to visit eight
political prisoners in Sofia, Tellalov said.
   He criticized failure to make the constitution conform with
international covenants on human rights signed by Bulgaria. A
commission for that purpose, led by Zhivkov, was established in
1988 but has never met, Tellalov said.
</TEXT>
