<FIRST>u i AM-China-Japan     11-14 0574</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-China-Japan,0593</SECOND>
<HEAD>Toyota Weighs Withdrawing Workers After Death Threats, Gunshots</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By TERRIL JONES</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BEIJING (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Toyota Motor Corp. is deciding whether to pull
its employees out of China after some said they were targets of
gunshots and a death threat, a spokesman for the Japanese automaker
and other sources said Tuesday.
   Three Toyota employees believe they were shot at while playing
golf in Beijing on Sunday, three days after Toyota's Beijing office
received an anonymous death threat, Japanese sources in Beijing
said on condition of anonymity.
   A letter received by the office Thursday contained a bullet and
ordered Japanese businessmen to leave China or face death, they
said.
   ``We are taking the letter fairly seriously,'' said a Toyota
spokesman in Tokyo, who would not disclose the letter's contents.
``We are currently working on details of whether to pull our people
out to Japan.''
   The Japanese sources quoted the letter as saying, ``Now that the
martial law troops are gone, our time has come. Go back to Japan.
From now, we will kill you Japanese.''
   Soldiers with automatic rifles were deployed on Beijing streets
under martial law after the army's crackdown on the pro-democracy
movement in early June, but were removed Nov. 1. Only a few armed
police stand guard in Beijing, primarily at Tiananmen Square.
   The Japanese Embassy in Beijing has asked the Chinese Ministry
of Public Security and the Foreign Ministry to investigate the
letter and the reported gunshots, a Japanese diplomat said.
   About 170 golfers, mostly Japanese, were on the course just
before lunchtime when some of them heard what sounded like bullets
whizzing by, said the diplomat, who refused to be further
identified.
   Witnesses, however, reported hearing two bursts of machine-gun
fire and believed 20-30 shots were fired, other Japanese sources
said.
   Some of the bullets hit trees on the Beijing Golf Club near the
golfers, the sources said.
   The golf course is slightly more than a mile from a shooting
range where people can rent hand guns, rifles and machine guns for
target practice.
   Three Toyota employees heard the shots, which were believed to
be stray shots from the rifle range, the Toyota spokesman in Tokyo
said.
   ``There was no feeling of threat to their lives, but they felt
uneasy and left the course immediately,'' he said.
   In July and August, letters sent to Japanese firms, including
Japan Airlines and signed by the ``Blood-Bright Dare to Die
Squad,'' threatened to kill Japanese for their ``economic
invasion'' of China.
   Japan has a large trade surplus with China, and tourists from
Japan are a major source of foreign capital. After last summer's
threats, security was increased at Japanese offices and hotels that
are home to many Japanese businessmen.
   Chinese Premier Li Peng said Tuesday before he left for a visit
to Pakistan, Bangladesh and Nepal that the shooting was ``merely an
accident'' and that authorities are investigating.
   ``Such an event could occur in any other country and I want to
say that in China there will be no greater number of such incidents
than in any other country,'' Li said.
   Li said he doubted the incidents would affect investment from
overseas.
   ``Just recently when I received an economic delegation from
Japan, that Japanese delegation was very optimistic about making
investments in China and about carrying out economic and
technological cooperation with Japan,'' Li said.
   Foreign businessmen have expressed concern over the political
and investment climate in China.
</TEXT>
