<SECOND>AM-ELN-Miami Elections,0455</SECOND>
<HEAD>Voters Choose Two Commissioners In Hotly Contested Races</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: Polls close at 7 p.m. EST, material below dash will stand.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DAN SEWELL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MIAMI (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Voters decided two bitter city commission races
Tuesday, with the only elected black on the commission locked in a
tough re-election battle.
   Dade County Elections officials expected 36 percent of the
registered voters to turn out for the runoff elections.
   Two-term incumbent Miller Dawkins, 64, said he didn't believe
his was ``the black seat,'' but he also said the city's blacks _
with about 30 percent of the voters _ deserved representation on
the commission.
   He was challenged by Joe Carollo, 34, a Cuban-born former
commissioner whose Spanish-language ads suggested ``all the Cubans
vote for Carollo.''
   In the other race, former commissioner Rosario Kennedy, 44,
trying to regain the seat she resigned this summer for an
unsuccessful run at Congress, faced Miriam Alonso, 48.
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
   Dawkins, an administrator at Miami-Dade Community College, led a
six-candidate primary Nov. 7 by 691 votes over Carollo. ``Black
Seat in Jeopardy'' was the front-page headline in The Miami Times,
a black-oriented weekly newspaper.
   Dawkins was supported by some Hispanic leaders who said it was
important symbolically to have at least one black on the commission.
   Carollo, a former police officer who served two terms on the
commission before losing the 1987 election, ran a slashing campaign
that linked Dawkins with a drug trafficker and called him the worst
commissioner in Miami history. In his fiery years on the
commission, Carollo often brought his anti-Communism into
commission debates.
   Some key Cuban-American leaders had backed Cuban-born attorney
Victor De Yurre in his 1987 defeat of Carollo.
   Mayor Xavier Suarez, easily re-elected last week to a new four
year-term, called Carollo disruptive and supported Dawkins.
   De Yurre and ``Anglo'' J.L. Plummer will be up for re-election
in two years. The mayor also sits on the commission.
   Ms. Kennedy charged Ms. Alonso with ``a penchant for
demagoguery.'' Her commercials called Ms. Alonso ``an opportunist
who does not respect the law,'' a reference to a 1988 court
decision that knocked Ms. Alonso off the Dade County commission
ballot because of a residency violation.
   Ms. Alonso, a Little Havana populist, concentrated her campaign
among Hispanic voters. She led the six-candidate primary by 235
votes.
   Athalie Range, who is black, was picked as interim commissioner
after Ms. Kennedy's resignation. She did not seek election to a
full term.
   Miami's 104,232 registered voters for the nonpartisan races
included 44,034 foreign-born Hispanics _ estimates of all Hispanics
range to 50 percent _ 32,021 blacks and 28,199 non-Latin whites, or
Anglos.
</TEXT>
