<HEAD>Gorbachev Praises E. Europe Changes But Says Cold War Victory Claims
Bad</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-East Germany, Bjt</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MOSCOW (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   President Mikhail S. Gorbachev on Tuesday praised
the dramatic reforms in Eastern Europe for opening opportunities
for human contact, but he said no one should claim a victory in the
Cold War.
   With a week of dramatic developments in East Germany, Bulgaria
and Czechoslovakia behind them, Gorbachev met with French Foreign
Minister Roland Dumas and made his most detailed remarks about the
changes.
   ``They are extremely different in their starting conditions,
economic possibilities, in their level of political culture and
historical heritage,'' Tass paraphrased Gorbachev as saying of the
East European countries involved. He did not name them, adding,
``But they have a common direction, which fosters the building of a
European home for it makes the countries closer, more open and
creates new opportunities for human contact and an equal exchange.''
   At the same time, the Kremlin chief told Dumas it was ``useless
to shout about a victory in the Cold War, about the collapse of
this or that social system.'' He said a realistic analysis of
changes and work toward a ``balance of interests'' should replace
such claims.
   In an earlier meeting, Soviet Foreign Minister Eduard A.
Shevardnadze and his French counterpart clashed over whether
