<HEAD>Rhode Island Senator Seeks Re-election</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Sen. Claiborne Pell, D-R.I., chairman of the
Senate Foreign Relations Committee, said Wednesday he will seek
election to a sixth term.
   ``I have the best job anyone could have and I would like to
continue in that job,'' the 71-year old senator said.
   Pell's announcement put to rest speculation he would retire, and
Democratic leaders said his decision would help the party retain
its control of the chamber in the 1990 elections. Democrats now
hold a 55-45 edge.
   The veteran senator is expected to face a tough challenge from
Rep. Claudine Schneider, R-R.I.
   ``She's a good woman, a good congresswoman, and I have great
respect and regard for her,'' Pell said of his likely opponent.
   Pell was first elected in 1960. Among current members, only two
Democrats and one Republican have served longer.
