<FIRST>r w AM-Bush-Education     11-14 0324</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Bush-Education,300</SECOND>
<HEAD>Bush Extols Link Between Education, Liberty</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By CHRISTOPHER CONNELL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   President Bush extolled the link between
education and liberty as he signed a proclamation Tuesday making
this American Education Week.
   ``We are here today not to flunk our system, but to earn a
higher grade,'' Bush said at a ceremony that drew 150 educators and
students to the White House.
   ``As a nation, we proclaim that America is serious about lifting
the hope and the dreams of young Americans, serious about education
and the future,'' he said.
   Bush displayed a ``Solidarnosc'' bracelet he was wearing as a
gift from Polish labor leader Lech Walesa, to whom he gave the
Presidential Medal of Freedom Monday night.
   ``This concern with education is to be found wherever men and
women seek to extend human liberty,'' said the president. He said
he was ``deeply impressed by the changes that are underway in
Poland and the fervent commitment of the Polish people to make that
change permanent through education.''
   Bush also made a pitch for parents to be given ``the power to
choose their children's schools,'' and for schools to be able to
hire ``knowledgeable'' non-education majors as teachers.
   American Education Week, Nov. 12-18 this year, has been observed
annually since 1921. It is sponsored by the Department of
Education, 10 national education groups and the American Legion.
   Bush was joined on stage by representatives of each group and
several local students, who presented him with a bronze statue of
children's hands holding the groups' ``Flag of Liberty and
Learning.''
   ``Look at that! Isn't that beautiful!'' Bush exclaimed as the
three-foot-high bronze was unveiled.
   As Bush began to depart, Kevin Dauray, 9, a fourth-grader in a
wheelchair from Patrick Henry School in Alexandria, Va., piped up,
``Can I have your autograph?''
   The president quickly obliged the boy, penning his ``G. Bush''
on one of the cards he had been reading from.
</TEXT>
