<FIRST>r w AM-Schroeder-BerlinWall     11-14 0245</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Schroeder-Berlin Wall,230</SECOND>
<HEAD>Congresswoman Calls on Bush to Withdraw Troops fro Europe</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A Democratic congresswoman on Tuesday called
on President Bush to withdraw all U.S. troops from Western Europe,
claiming the days in which the Warsaw Pact nations marched ``to the
beat of a Soviet drummer'' are over.
   Rep. Patricia Schroeder, D-Colo., a member of the House Armed
Services Committee, said in a two-page letter to Bush that the
``rusting and crumbling of the Iron Curtain'' provides an
unprecedented opportunity to foster democracy and reduce the budget
deficit by removing American combat troops from Europe.
   Schroeder suggested that Bush seize the initiative at his Dec.
2-3 summit meeting with Soviet President Mikhail S. Gorbachev in
the Mediterranean near Malta.
   ``What you should propose is this: An immediate withdrawal of
all U.S. combat troops from Western Europe in exchange for a
withdrawal of all Soviet combat troops from Eastern Europe,''
Schroeder said.
   Bush proposed at the 40th anniversary of the NATO alliance in
May a ceiling of 275,000 on U.S. and Soviet ground and air force
personnel, which would require a reduction of about 30,000 U.S.
troops and about 325,000 Soviet troops.
   But Schroeder said the dramatic turn of events in Eastern Europe
in the past few weeks makes it clear that ``the days during which
the Kremlin could count on the arms of Poland, the German
Democratic Republic and Hungary to march to the beat of a Soviet
drummer are over.''
