<FILEID>AP-NR-11-14-89 2038EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r w AM-SausageRecall     11-14 0273</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Sausage Recall,270</SECOND>
<HEAD>Massachusetts Firm Recalls 300 Pounds of Meat</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Lisbon Sausage Co. Inc. of New Bedford, Mass.,
has voluntarily recalled 300 pounds of product distributed to
grocery stores in southeastern Massachusetts and Rhode Island
because some of it may be contaminated by a food poisoning
organism, the Agriculture Department said Tuesday.
   The organism, Listeria monocytogenes, could cause serious
illness and possible death, officials said.
   ``Although no illnesses have been reported, we strongly urge
consumers to avoid even opening the product and to return it
immediately to the establishment where it was purchased,'' said
Lester M. Crawford, administrator of the department's Food Safety
and Inspection Service.
   The recalled product is ``Amaral's Chourico,'' described as a
Portuguese smoked pork sausage product. It is sold in one-pound
vacuum sealed plastic packages that contain two sausages. The name
``Amaral's Chourico'' is printed on the label, and ``Est. 219'' is
printed inside the USDA inspection seal on the label.
   All of the recalled product carries the sell-by date 1-29-90 or
Jan. 29 90'' stamped on the package. The product is sold
exclusively to grocery stores. No other product made by the firm
has been involved.
   Food contaminated by the bacterium can call listeriosis, a
``rare but potentially fatal disease,'' the agency said. ``In
general, healthy people are at little risk from listeriosis; most
vulnerable are those with weakened immune systems _ infants,
pregnant women, the elderly and the chronically ill.''
   Consumers with questions about the recall can phone the agency's
toll-free hotline at 1-800-535-4555 from 9 a.m. to 5 p.m. EST,
Monday through Friday. Callers in the Washington metropolitan area
should call 447-3333.
</TEXT>
