<FILEID>AP-NR-11-14-89 1638EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>u a AM-HomelessFashions Bjt   11-14 0530</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Homeless Fashions, Bjt,0547</SECOND>
<HEAD>Fashion Show For Homeless To Feature $500,000 Dress</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto Staffing</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By EVE EPSTEIN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BOSTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A liquor distributor and Boston models are using a
shimmering gold mesh dress to get the well-heeled to give money to
those who can barely afford their next meal, much less a pair of
shoes.
   Wednesday's fashion show will benefit the Massachusetts
Coalition for the Homeless, a statewide group that does everything
from lobby for the homeless to refinish furniture for people moving
out of shelters.
   The coalition says between 5,000 and 8,000 people inhabit
Boston's streets and shelters.
   After the benefit, Michel Roux, the president of the company
that distributes Absolut Vodka, which owns the golden dress, plans
to take the $532,000 garment on the road for similar fund-raisers.
   ``I don't think we have to look at it from the angle of gold,''
Roux said. ``I think we have to look at it from the angle of the
novelty, the uniqueness of the dress, which will certainly bring
attention to the cause.''
   Model Rachel Williams will be draped in the 8-pound, 18-karat
gold dress designed by Anthony Ferrara during the show at a Boston
nightclub. The Models for Boston Benefit for the Homeless hope to
raise $40,000 from the show, said Craig Sutton, a spokesman for the
event.
   The group will give 100 percent of the proceeds to homeless
causes, Sutton said, adding that Absolut and the models'
organization will cover costs of the evening.
   Roux got the idea of featuring the dress, a clingy short tank,
after he spotted Ferrara wearing a gold mesh scarf. Ferrara designs
for such stars as Cher and Barbra Streisand.
   Roux keeps the dress in a safe. ``You roll it in paper and keep
it like you keep any jewelry,'' he said.
   The show also features a warmup act: a sterling silver dress
valued at $100,000, also owned by Absolut.
   Fund-raisers say they recognize that the glitz and glamour of a
fashion show seems at odds with the hard reality of homelessness.
But Sandra Blevins, a model who helped create the idea three years
ago, said people in the fashion industry have an obligation to
contribute to the cause.
   ``It looks a little strange from the outside but it really makes
sense. Everybody should get involved,'' said Blevins, who has done
volunteer work at local homeless shelters. ``We make money off of
people who are well-dressed.''
   Meryl Langbort, of the Massachusetts Coalition for the Homeless,
said her group welcomes the chance to reach people who might not
otherwise think about the homeless.
   ``Certainly the money is important. Certainly we need it to
operate. But what's so important about something like this is it
gets the message out there,'' she said.
   Admission is $40, which pays for food but not drinks.
   The mesh for the dress was made by a Massachusetts firm that
specializes in metal wear for less fashionable garb: outerwear for
meatpackers.
   Whiting &amp; Davis makes a stainless steel ring mesh that protects
workers from knife wounds. Earlier in the century, the company,
which started out as a jewelry firm, created a line of small gold
mesh handbags.
</TEXT>
