<FILEID>AP-NR-11-14-89 1929EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r i AM-Lebanon     11-14 0468</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Lebanon,0482</SECOND>
<HEAD>Christian Lawmakers Defy Aoun, Hoss Works to Build Government</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DONNA ABU-NASR</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BEIRUT, Lebanon (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Premier-designate Salim Hoss began
parliamentary consultations to form a new government Tuesday, and
some Christian lawmakers appeared willing to defy Gen. Michel Aoun
and work with the Moslem leader.
   Rival Shiite Moslem militiamen clashed with machine guns and
rocket-propelled grenades in Beirut's southern slums. Three
militiamen were reported wounded.
   Aoun, the Christian army leader, told reporters any national
unity government would be a ``crime against Lebanon's sovereignty,
and anyone taking part in it will be a criminal.''
   Nevertheless, four Maronite Parliament deputies held a meeting
to consider an offer from Hoss to join his government, which will
institute reforms intended to end Lebanon's 14-year-old civil war.
   They included George Saadeh, leader of the right-wing Phalange
Party, the largest political force in the Christian enclave
controlled by Aoun's troops.
   ``The general wasn't able to push a single Syrian soldier an
inch backward in his so-called liberation war,'' said deputy Butros
Harb, another who participated in the meeting. ``Why doesn't the
general give peace a chance?''
   Aoun in March declared a ``war of liberation'' to drive the
40,000 Syrian troops from Lebanon, where they were deployed in 1976
under a mandate to quell the civil war. Aoun said they abrogated
the mandate by siding with the Moslems.
   The violence ended with an Arab League-brokered cease-fire in
September, and last month, Lebanese legislators meeting in Taif,
Saudi Arabia, approved a peace accord clearing the way for election
of a president and creation of a national reconciliation government.
   Newly elected president Rene Mouawad on Monday named Hoss prime
minister to form the government. Hoss remains prime
minister-designate until he forms a government endorsed by
presidential decree.
   Aoun has said any Christian politicians who join Hoss'
government will be banned from the Christian enclave.
   He pledged to block implementation of the peace accord because
it does not include a timetable for the withdrawal of Syrian troops.
   Saadeh has challenged Aoun to a televised debate over the accord.
   At his news conference, Aoun rejected the proposed debate,
saying, ``There is no need for any dialogue over the Taif accord. I
shall not allow it to pass.''
   No civilian casualties were reported from the one-hour flare-up
between the pro-Iranian Hezbollah and the Syrian-backed Amal
militias. But Hezbollah sources, speaking on condition of
anonymity, said three combatants from both sides were wounded.
   The two factions have long been vying for control of the 1.2
million Shiites, who make up the largest sect among Lebanon's 4
million people.
   An Amal spokesman, speaking on condition of anonymity, said the
command of a Syrian army contingent in charge of the security of
Beirut's Moslem sector intervened with the leaderships of the two
groups to stop the violence.
</TEXT>
