<FIRST>b w PM-Navy-Accidents 1stLd-Writethru a0662-a0667 11-14 0269</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Navy-Accidents, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0662-a0667,280</SECOND>
<HEAD>Navy Shutting Down Operations After Accidents</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: RFETRANSMITS a3537 to put in correct number sequence</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By SUSANNE M. SCHAFER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Military Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Navy, out of concern over a string of
accidents in recent weeks, has ordered that all normal operations
cease for 48 hours while safety procedures are reviewed, the
service announced today.
   ``Navy Secretary H. Lawrence Garrett III and the Chief of Naval
Operations Carlisle A. H. Trost have ordered a Navy-wide 48-hour
safety stand-down to be conducted within the next 72 hours,'' the
Navy said in a statement.
   The order requires every ship, squadron and shore training
facility to interrupt normal operations and review basic safety and
operating procedures, said Navy spokesman Lt. Bruce Cole.
   ``It means that they will interrupt normal training, normal
flight operations, normal field operations ... to go over basic
safety procedures and make sure that everybody has the basics,''
the spokesman added.
   ``The purpose of the stand-down is to reemphasize continuing
safety awareness among all Navy personnel,'' Cole said.
   The move comes just after the latest problem for the Navy, in
which a fire broke out aboard the amphibious assault ship USS
Inchon while it underwent shipyard maintenance in Norfolk, Va., At
least 24 people were reported injured in the incident.
   In recent weeks, the service has been plagued by a number of
deadly accidents involving a training jet crashing into an aircraft
carrier off Florida, sailors who have been washed overboard on two
different aircraft carriers and the accidental bombing of a ship by
a Navy pilot in the Indian Ocean.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
