<FIRST>u w AM-WalesaColor     11-14 0478</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Walesa Color,470</SECOND>
<HEAD>With AM-Walesa Bjt</HEAD>
<HEAD>A Bearhug for the Union Movement</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: RETRANSMITTING a3538 to put in correct number sequence</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MIKE FEINSILBER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The moment was solemn, but not so much so that
Lech Walesa, a twinkle in his eye, could not make a joke _ one
especially appreciated by the beefiest of the labor leaders in his
audience.
   Walesa, addressing the AFL-CIO, recalled dark days when as a
shipyard electrician he organized the strike that would lead, nine
years later, to the first non-communist government in the Soviet
bloc.
   ``When in August 1980, I jumped over the wall surrounding the
Gdansk Shipyard, I did not know what our protests would lead to,
but I knew perfectly well what it was that we had to do,'' he said.
   Now, he said, he wished that only such ``clear-cut situations''
confronted him. And with a self-effacing grin, he took note of the
pot belly that had come with the years.
   ``Maybe today,'' he said, ``I would have slightly more
difficulty jumping over that wall ....''
   Many a hefty union leader laughed with him.
   Walesa gave a bearhug to ``Brother Kirkland'' _ Lane Kirkland,
president of the federation _ and a morale-boosting salute Tuesday
to a labor movement that has seen its own role diminish and has had
no recent success to emulate what Walesa had achieved in Poland.
   When he made his way through the hotel ballroom, grasping at
hands, beaming with pleasure, the union chiefs cheered for 15
minutes.
   ``Lech, Lech, Lech, Lech,'' a Teamster chanted.
   Garment workers jumped on chairs to snap his picture;
steelworkers raised their hands in the V-sign; Walesa's fellow
electricians clapped in unison; a paperworker wearing a
``Solidarnosc'' button held aloft a red sign that, in Polish,
denounced Frank Lorenzo, president of strikebound Eastern Airlines.
   He V-signed them back and bowed at them, beaming.
   Pink-cheeked, his famous mustache trimmed and gray, Walesa said
he did not want to appear to be currying their favor but he thanked
the AFL-CIO over and over for standing beside ``the cause so many
people considered lost and which now, thanks to the stubbornness of
Poles and the perseverance of our friends, has put us on the road
to victory.''
   In martial-law Poland, in the days when Walesa was often under
arrest, the AFL-CIO quietly delivered millions of dollars to his
underground movement and smuggled in printing presses to let
Solidarity's voice be heard.
   ``You have proven to be our most steadfast allies in the trade
union struggle for human rights,'' he said.
   ``A vast movement for democracy and freedom is developing in my
country. It is changing the political face of Poland and of the
world. And that movement has been made possible only through the
peaceful struggle of working people, of trade unionists like you
and me, like us.''
</TEXT>
