<FIRST>r w AM-PublicTelevision     11-14 0387</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Public Television,370</SECOND>
<HEAD>Public Broadcasting Moves To Centralize Programming</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By LEE BYRD</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The three national public television
organizations announced Tuesday an agreement designed to enhance
their coordination and improve program scheduling and quality.
   The pact, involving the Corporation for Public Broadcasting, the
Public Broadcasting Service and the National Association of Public
Television Stations, will ``free public television from many of the
frustrations of the past and give it a jump start for the next
decade,'' according to CPB President Donald Ledwig.
   The agreement in principle, which now must be approved by the
organizations' respective boards as well as Congress, would make
CPB primarily responsible for developing new programs, while PBS
would focus on distribution, funding for existing programs, and
support of local stations.
   Public television in the United States is now a complex,
decentralized system with multiple sources of programming and
financing. As a consequence, producers spend much of their time
scrambling for money, and development of a national program
schedule is, at best, difficult.
   Congress, in the Public Telecommunications Act of 1988, directed
CPB and PBS to examine whether they could pool their resources with
those of local public television stations to improve national
programming. The agreement announced Tuesday is the outgrowth of
that mandate.
   PBS President Bruce Christensen called the tentative, three-year
agreement ``both a centralization and a consensus-building plan. As
a result, it will make the programming process more agile and
responsive to a quickly changing television environment.''
   Currently, about $262 million _ less than half of which is tax
money _ is spent annually by public television for national
programming. The agreement calls for PBS to directly manage $100
million of that amount. The CPB would handle the rest,
concentrating on the development of new programs, financing of the
new Independent Television Service, and minority productions.
   PBS will expand the powers of its new program executive,
Jennifer Lawson, under the agreement. She will be charged with
developing a multiyear schedule and financing plan, in coordination
with a new 17-member program policy committee drawing together
representatives of producers, minorities and stations in each
region of the country.
   David J. Brugger, president of the stations' association, said
the deal ``gives public television the opportunity to move forward
in developing the strongest possible national programming with the
funds available.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
