<HEAD>NBC Takes Big Lead in Ratings with Cosby on Top</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JERRY BUCK</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Television Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>LOS ANGELES (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Nielsen ratings for last week looked like
a replay of the week before as NBC led the way with six of its
half-hour comedies at the top.
   NBC's ``The Cosby Show'' was first and ABC's ``Roseanne'' was
again in fourth place. Every show in the Top 10 was a regular
series. Eight were repeaters from last week.
   NBC took a commanding lead in the A.C. Nielsen Co. ratings for
the week ended Nov. 12 with an average of 15.4. ABC was second with
12.7 and CBS was third with 11.8. A rating is the percentage of the
nation's 92.1 million homes tuned to a show.
   The Top 10 were: NBC's ``The Cosby Show,'' NBC's ``Cheers,''
NBC's ``A Different World,'' ABC's ``Roseanne,'' NBC's ``Golden
Girls,'' NBC's ``L.A. Law,'' NBC's ``Dear John'' and ``Empty Nest''
tied, CBS' ``60 Minutes,'' and NBC's ``Unsolved Mysteries'' and
ABC's ``The Wonder Years'' tied.
   CBS' ``Murder, She Wrote,'' eighth last week, fell to 15th place.
   The highest-rated special of the week was the first part of
ABC's ``Small Sacrifices,'' in which Farrah Fawcett played a woman
convicted of killing one of her own children. It tied for 12th
place with ABC Monday Night Football and ABC's ``Who's the Boss?''
   The final chapter of ``Small Sacrifices'' was to be broadcast
Tuesday night. Among the shows it pre-empted was ``Chicken Soup,''
which had its final showing last week and tied for 21st place with
NBC's ``Hunter.'' It will be replaced next week by the return of
``Coach.''
   NBC's ``Manhunt: The Search for the Night Stalker,'' which went
head-to-head against ABC's ``Small Sacrifices'' and CBS' ``The
Return of McCloud,'' was 20th. ``McCloud'' tied for 39th place with
ABC's ``Family Matters.''
   Jaclyn Smith's premiere in ``Christine Cromwell'' in the ABC
Saturday Mystery Movie was 43rd. It's the last element in the
series.
   NBC also is doing very well in the November sweeps. Month-long
sweeps occur three times a year and result in vicious competition
between networks. Advertising rates are based on the audience
levels recorded during the periods.
   The ratings for the first 11 days of the Nielsen sweeps period:
NBC 15.2, CBS and ABC 12.2, tied.
   ABC's ``World News Tonight'' remained ahead in the ratings for
the evening news shows. On Thursday, when the Berlin Wall was
opened, the ratings were ABC 12.0, CBS 10.3, NBC 10.1. NBC's Tom
Brokaw was the only anchorman at the wall that day. The ratings for
the week: ABC 11.1, CBS 10.3, NBC 10.0.
   The five bottom network shows, in descending order, were CBS'
``Peaceable Kingdom,'' CBS' ``Saturday Night with Connie Chung,''
the ABC News special ``Freedom Week'' and, in a tie for last place,
ABC's ``Living Dolls'' and CBS' ``Wolf.''
</TEXT>
