<FILEID>AP-NR-11-14-89 2043EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r a AM-FoodSafety     11-14 0575</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Food Safety,0591</SECOND>
<HEAD>New Techniques Needed for Food Safety in 1990s</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JAMES WEBB</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   New packaging techniques coupled with consumer
demands for fresh, chemical-free foods are challenging producers to
develop better ways of ensuring safety and informing the public,
food industry experts say.
   New safety measures and an up-front approach to consumers'
concerns have to go hand in hand with the development of new
products, according to officials who spoke on food safety issues of
the 1990s at the Food &amp; Dairy Expo, which began Saturday and ends
Wednesday.
   ``Consumers now want fresher foods,'' said David Henning,
director of quality assurance for suburban Skokie-based Kraft
General Foods, a division of Philip Morris Cos. Inc. of New York.
``They're not as anxious to have food with preservatives that in
the past controlled organisms, so we're going to have to have other
methods to ensure safety.''
   The perceived health value of fresh and refrigerated products
presents a dilemma to the food industry, said Alan Hugunin, senior
director of product technologies of the National Food Processors
Association.
   ``Whereas you can put something in a can and be sure that no
microorganisms are going to grow in there for eternity, you can't
do that with fresh and refrigerated products,'' Hugunin said.
   And better methods of packaging foods create their own
challenges.
   New packaging methods can prevent mold longer, leaving food
looking wholesome even while it grows unnoticeable organisms that
cause food poisoning, he said.
   In response, food manufacturers are increasingly using a system,
developed in the U.S. space program, of analyzing the production
process at each step from the raw material to a finished product,
according to Henning.
   The method allows food producers to prevent problems before they
occur, rather than testing food after it's been produced and _ if
there is a problem _ tracing it back to find the source, he said.
   This step-by-step method is ``the best answer anybody's come up
with yet'' to ensure food safety, Joseph Hotchkiss, an associate
professor of food chemistry and toxicology at Cornell University
said during a telephone interview Tuesday.
   But consumers seem unaware that their demands for new, fresher
foods are pushing the industry to deal with new problems involving
contamination by microorganisms. Instead, Hotchkiss said, they are
more concerned with food additives and pesticides, which are a
smaller problem.
   ``The consumer, by any objective measure, does not have the same
priorities as the scientific community on food safety,'' Hotchkiss
said.
   Hugunin said the food industry has to do a better job of
educating the public about pesticides and additives, such as the
chemical Alar, a suspected cancer-causing chemical.
   An early 1989 report on Alar-treated apples by the private
National Resources Defense Council prompted an uproar over its use,
although government and apple industry officials said the chemical
is only used on a small percentage of apples and is not dangerous
in the levels used.
   The apple industry was caught unprepared, Hugunin said.
   ``The information which was needed to respond to some of these
claims ... was just spread out all over and there was no good way
of pulling it all together quickly to respond to some of the
statements that were made,'' Hugunin said.
   As food products continue to develop and safety techniques
change, the industry has to educate consumers before concerns grow,
he said.
   The expo is sponsored by the Dairy &amp; Food Industries Supply
Association of Rockville, Md.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP891114-0139 </DOCNO>
