<FIRST>r a AM-Mistaken-MostWanted     11-14 0270</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Mistaken-Most Wanted,0279</SECOND>
<HEAD>Aspiring Actor Recognized, But Not For Roles</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LOS ANGELES (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Aspiring Actor Danny Kaufman always dreamed
of being recognized in public _ but not as one of ``America's Most
Wanted.''
   Kaufman was dining out at a Sherman Oaks restaurant where
employees thought they recognized him from the television series
about fugitive criminals.
   Only Kaufman wasn't the murder suspect they had seen _ he just
looked the part.
   But when the 25-year-old emerged from Stanley's restaurant, he
had an audience of 10 police officers, several with drawn guns.
   ``It wasn't the kind of attention I was seeking,'' Kaufman said
Monday. ``As soon as I stepped out the door my arms were grabbed
and pulled behind me. I was handcuffed in about a
second-and-a-half. I didn't know what was happening. I was scared.''
   Kaufman said it took four hours and a set of fingerprints to
convince police he wasn't 20-year-old Richard Church, who is wanted
for investigation of murder in Illinois.
   Fugitive squad Detective Douglas Le Melle said the police showed
up in force after the tip from the restaurant employees because
Church is considered dangerous and is believed to be in Southern
California.
   Le Melle said Church allegedly stabbed a former girlfriend, her
brother, mother and father in Woodstock, Ill., on Aug. 21, 1988.
The mother and father died from their wounds.
   ``He didn't come close to matching the prints, but on looks it
was close,'' Le Melle said of Kaufman.
   ``He came back and he had bruises around his wrists from the
cuffs,'' said one of the restaurant employees. ``I feel really bad
about it.''
</TEXT>
