<FIRST>u w AM-FDACommissioner     11-14 0389</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-FDA Commissioner,380</SECOND>
<HEAD>Interim Appointment Expected to Replace Young</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DEBORAH MESCE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Federal officials are considering an interim
appointment at the Food and Drug Administration while they search
for a permanent commissioner to replace Frank Young who has
resigned, sources said Tuesday.
   Unlike the current and previous FDA commissioners who were
appointed by the head of the Department of Health and Human
Services, the next commissioner will be a presidential appointment
and will require Senate confirmation.
   The change in procedure means it likely will to take longer to
put a permanent commissioner at the helm of the agency whose
responsibility is to assure the safety of drugs, cosmetics and most
food products.
   The pace of presidential appointments during the Bush
administration has been slow. At HHS, several key agencies still
have no permanent head, including the Health Care Financing
Administration, the Family Support Administration and the National
Institutes of Health.
   The FDA has been plagued recently by disclosures of bribery and
corruption in approval of generic drugs, and some lawmakers on
Capitol Hill have said Young's leaving may delay needed reforms at
the agency.
   Young will end more than five years as commissioner on Dec. 18
and become a deputy assistant secretary of health in charge of
science and environmental matters. Both jobs are in the Public
Health Service, which is part of HHS.
   Congress last year changed the law last year pertaining to the
appointment of an FDA commissioner to require Senate confirmation,
as is required of other top jobs in the administration.
   ``It's a very important job and touches so much of the consumer
safety questions. It's important that someone like that to have a
level of consideration that other appointments do,'' said a
congressional aide who worked on the measure but spoke on the
condition of anonymity.
   Sources in the department, who also spoke on the condition their
names not be used, said that because of the time it may take to
select a permanent commissioner and gain approval, officials are
considering an interim appointment.
   James S. Benson is currently the FDA's second in command as
acting deputy commissioner.
   Names being mentioned as early candidates for the permanent post
include Burton J. Lee, who is President Bush's personal physician,
and David Pinco, a Washington lawyer and former FDA official.
</TEXT>
