<FIRST>u w AM-US-Nicaragua 1stLd-Writethru a0648 11-14 0774</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-US-Nicaragua, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0648,730</SECOND>
<HEAD>RETRANSMITTING a0709 to restore matter dropped in transmission</HEAD>
<HEAD>Veteran Diplomat Recruited for Advice on Nicaragua</HEAD>
<HEAD>EDs: New with Bush comments, details on Shlaudeman; editing thruout.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By GEORGE GEDDA</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   President Bush said Tuesday that he will press
in next month's meeting with Soviet President Mikhail S. Gorbachev
for an end to the shipment of East Bloc arms to Central America.
   Bush made the comment at the outset of a meeting with the
observer team he named to monitor the February elections in
Nicaragua.
   At the same time, the State Department said it has called in
from retirement Harry Shlaudeman, a diplomat with long years of
experience on Central America, to give advice and monitor talks in
Washington between the Nicaraguan government and the Contra rebels.
   Bush was asked what the Soviet Union can do for peace in Central
America.
   ``What the Soviets can do is help facilitate free elections by
stopping to send arms into this hemisphere and support for the one
country that seems to be swimming against the tide,'' he said.
   This was a reference to the U.S. view that Soviet-manufactured
arms are abetting both the leftist government of Nicaragua and the
leftist rebels in El Salvador.
   ``I expect I'll have a chance at the Malta meeting'' with
Gorbachev ``to elaborate on that in a little bit more detail,''
Bush said.
   Separately, Bush told ministers of the Organization of American
States meeting here ``how upset I am that at a time when we're all
trying to build peace in Central America through diplomatic means,
the FMLN (guerrilla movement) in El Salvador, aided and abetted by
Nicaragua and the Cuban government, has resorted to senseless
bloodshed and gross violations of all the agreements reached to
promote peace in Central America.''
   Shlaudeman, 63, has agreed to work as a consultant to the
department on the Nicaragua talks but State Department spokeswoman
Margaret Tutwiler said he will not participate directly in the
discussions nor have substantive contact with Sandinista officials.
   Nonetheless, a senior official said Shlaudeman did have a
half-hour meeting in recent days with Sandinista diplomats at their
request. ``He was in a listening capacity,'' said the official,
asking not to be identified.
   Shlaudeman ended his 35-year diplomatic career last May after a
tour as ambassador to Brazil. He assumed his consultant's duties
last month.
   The talks between the Sandinistas and the Contras began at the
United Nations Thursday and were moved here Monday.
   Nicaraguan President Daniel Ortega called off a 19-month old
cease-fire with the rebels Nov. 1 and simultaneously proposed the
first direct discussions between the Sandinistas and the resistance
since June 1988.
   The main Sandinista objective is the demobilization of the
Contras, consistent with a communique issued by the Central
American presidents last August.
   The rebels, meanwhile, are stressing the need to restore the
cease-fire.
   Ms. Tutwiler said a new proposal was on the table at the talks
Tuesday with ``some common points of agreement.'' She had no
further details.
   Shlaudeman was the chief U.S. negotiator for bilateral
discussions between the United States and Nicaragua for an
eight-month period starting in June 1984.
   The Reagan administration broke off the talks, contending that
the Sandinista side was not negotiating in good faith. There have
been no substantive discussions between the two countries since
January 1985, and Ms. Tutwiler said that policy is unchanged.
   Shlaudeman's principal contact with the Nicaraguan government
during the 1984-85 period was Vice Foreign Minister Victor Hugo
Tinoco, who is leading the Sandinista delegation to the talks with
the Contras.
   Shlaudeman also was a special U.S. envoy to Central America,
making frequent trips to the region at the time when the
now-defunct Contadora peace process was under way.
   The Presidential Monitoring Commission will be chaired by Sen.
Richard Lugar, R-Ind., and Rep. Anthony C. Beilenson, D-Calif.,
White House spokesman Marlin Fitzwater said.
   The lawmakers will make numerous visits to Nicaragua over the
next 3{ months to monitor the election preparations and the
balloting itself, where opposition candidate Violeta de Chamorro is
seeking to unseat Ortega.
   Fitzwater said the lawmakers, in small groups, will make 15
trips to the Central American country between now and Feb. 25.
   Joining Lugar and Beilenson on the president's observer panel
are Sens. David Boren, D-Okla.; David Durenberger, R-Minn.; Nancy
Kassebaum, R-Kan.; Patrick Leahy, D-Vt.; Connie Mack, D-Fla.; John
McCain, R-Ariz.; Claiborne Pell, D-R.I.; Harry Reid, D-Nev., and
Terry Sanford, D-N.C.
   Representing the House are Reps. David Bonior, D-Mich.; William
Broomfield, R-Mich.; Rod Chandler, R-Wash.; Mickey Edwards,
R-Okla.; Henry Hyde, R-Ill.; Sonny Montgomery, D-Miss.; John
Murtha, D-Pa.; Jim Slattery, D-Kan., and Tom Tauke, R-Iowa.
</TEXT>
