<FIRST>u w AM-AFL-CIOHealth     11-14 0471</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-AFL-CIO Health,460</SECOND>
<HEAD>Labor Federation Vows National Health Care Campaign</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOHN KING</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Labor Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The AFL-CIO on Tuesday vowed an aggressive
campaign for passage of a national health care plan and Sen. Edward
M. Kennedy promised that Congress would adopt one next year.
   Delegates to the labor federation's convention endorsed a
resolution calling for an intensive lobbying campaign as well as
efforts to convince employers to join with unions in the effort.
   Labor in the past has endorsed Kennedy-sponsored proposals to
require private employers to provide private health insurance to
workers but a leader of the new campaign said the 14-million member
federation was entering the lobbying effort with an open mind.
   ``We are most interested in forging a consensus that we must as
a nation find a solution that ensures universal access to quality
care at a price we can afford,'' said John Sweeney, president of
the Service Employees International Union.
   Sweeney said the campaign, to be formally announced Wednesday,
would include meetings ``of hundreds of rank and file'' with
members of Congress in their home districts.
   He said rising health care costs have limited worker pay
increases because rising premiums have squeezed company profits and
also because employer efforts to shift insurance costs to workers
have dominated contract talks.
   To demonstrate its commitment to the campaign, several
presidents of the federation's largest unions spoke in favor of the
plan.
   ``Let us leave this convention commited to mobilizing the
roughly 90 percent of American citizens who are unhappy with our
current system,'' said United Auto Workers President Owen Bieber.
``This is an issue whose time has come and an issue on which the
labor movement must provide leadership.''
   Jack Barry, president of the International Brotherhood of
Electrical Workers, said the rising costs were due to the
``insatiable greed'' of health care providers.
   The resolution calling for the health-care campaign was passed
on an afternoon dedicated the family-related issues and speeches
from two of labor staunchest allies in Congress, Kennedy and Sen.
Barbara Mikulski, D-Md. Earlier in the day the convention heard an
emotional speech from Solidarity leader Lech Walesa, who thanked
American unions for their support of the Polish trade union he
leads.
   Also endorsed were pending congressional bills to increase
federal funds for day care and to require parental leave to care
for newborn and ill children.
   Kennedy, D-Mass., told the 800 delegates Congress would endorse
a national health care plan in 1990.
   ``The Ameican people understand the need,'' Kennedy said.
``Politicians are stating to understand. Progressive businesses are
beginning to understand. And by the time you finish the national
health care campaign you ared launching at this convention,
President George Bush will catch on too, and have no choice but to
sign this bill we intend to sent to him in 1990.''
</TEXT>
