<FIRST>u i AM-Israel 1stLd-Writethru a0603 11-14 0803</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Israel, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0603,0821</SECOND>
<HEAD>Palestinians Mark Independence Declaration; Army Sends Reinforcements</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: SUBS 5th pvs, `In the...' with 4 grafs to UPDATE with Palestinian
killed, other unrest. Picks up 6th pvs, `Defense Minister...'</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By LOUIS MEIXLER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BIR ZEIT, Occupied West Bank (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Outlawed flags lined the
streets of Bir Zeit and Palestinians throughout the occupied lands
planned marches and fireworks Wednesday to mark the PLO declaration
of independence one year ago.
   Activists in Bir Zeit said they would observe the anniversary by
reading the Palestinian independence proclamation over a mosque
loudspeaker and marching military-style under the Palestinian
flags, which Israel has outlawed.
   The army closed schools in the Gaza Strip, arrested alleged
agitators in West Bank raids and called in reinforcements to help
quell anticipated riots.
   Soldiers sealed off the Gaza Strip, searching for Palestinian
gunmen who killed an Israeli soldier Monday evening and wounded
another. The Moslem fundamentalist group Hamas, or Zeal, claimed
responsibility for the attack.
   Late Tuesday, a Palestinian was shot by soldiers and later died
from a chest wound at Ramallah Hospital in the West Bank, doctors
said. The body was snatched from the hospital, apparently by
relatives, they said.
   Israel radio identified the Palestinian as Odah Hussein Ziyad,
18, from the Kalandia refugee camp five miles north of Jerusalem.
The army confirmed the death but said it was checking to see if
soldiers were involved.
   Also in the West Bank, Manweh Bakry, 45, of Nablus, died of
chest wounds suffered in a Sept. 14 clash with troops. The deaths
raised to 615 the number of Palestinians killed by soldiers or
civilians in the 23-month-old uprising against Israeli occupation.
Forty-one Israelis have also died in the violence.
   At least 16 Palestinians were wounded in stone-throwing clashes
with Israeli troops throughout the West Bank and Gaza Strip
Tuesday, Arab sources said.
   Defense Minister Yitzhak Rabin said the attack on the soldiers
could signal plans to increase the use of guns and explosives. The
Palestine Liberation Organization has urged its followers
repeatedly not to use firearms, recommending non-violent protest
and civil disobedience instead.
   Prime Minister Yitzhak Shamir began a visit to the United
States, where he will meet with President Bush on proposals for
peace talks with Palestinians.
   Palestinian flags of black, white, green and red hung from
telephone poles and power lines throughout the West Bank and Gaza,
which Israel captured from Jordan and Egypt in the 1967 Middle East
War. Pictures of PLO chairman Yasser Arafat were pasted on
buildings.
   Children in Gaza City handed out flowers and balloons in the
flag colors. Arab motorists honked their horns and flicked on
lights as they drove down Omar Al Mukhtar Street, the main
throroughfare, witnesses reported.
   Firework rockets streaked across the sky in the early evening,
leaving red and blue trails.
   Rabin warned Palestinians against taking part in the
festivities, declaring on army radio: ``Be it the unfurling of a
flag, or the throwing of a stone or illegal gatherings, all steps
will be taken against these things.''
   In Bir Zeit, a town of 3,000 people, flags and pictures adorned
lamp posts, telephone poles and even the top of a cross on the
Roman Catholic Church, Our Lady of Guadeloupe.
   Yusef, a 26-year-old activist who would not give his last name,
said women's committes planned to dance the ``dabka,'' a
traditional Palestinian folk dance, in the streets on the
anniversary of the independence declaration Nov. 15, 1988, at a
meeting of the Palestinian Nationl Council in Algiers.
   Students from Bir Zeit University, which the army closed early
in the uprising, posted an invitation in a coffee shop to a
``Photography exhibit on the Palestinian state.''
   ``Despite the pain of so many dead and wounded, this is a moment
of joy,'' said Mahdi Abdel Hadi, a Palestinian leader in Jerusalem.
``It shows that we can change and lead our own history.''
   ``How can I celebrate with so many people killed and wounded?''
said a gasoline station attendant, who would not give his name.
``People will try to celebrate, but I think the army will suppress
them.''
   In the West Bank security sweep, soldiers detained 58
Palestinians suspected of uprising activities, Arab reporters said.
   On Monday evening, Palestinians fired 28 shots at an Israeli
patrol jeep, killing Cpl. Sarul Trechtenboit, 42, and critically
wounding another soldier, an army spokesman reported.
   Trechtenboit, who leaves four children, was the first soldier
killed in Gaza since the uprising began Dec. 8, 1987. Eight
soldiers are among the 41 Israeli victims of the violence.
   Israel radio said an anonymous caller claimed responsibility for
the attack in the name of Hamas, which opposes the PLO policy of
seeking a negotiated settlement with Israel. Hamas also has been
blamed for the kidnap-murder of two soldiers who disappeared while
hitchhiking earlier this year.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
