<FIRST>u a AM-FutureFries     11-14 0417</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Future Fries,0430</SECOND>
<HEAD>The Changing Face of Fast Food: Designer Fries</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By NICHOLAS K. GERANIOS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>KENNEWICK, Wash. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Anthony Moseley sees a world of
possibility in french fries. They can curve sideways or spiral
upward, taste like a potato or have the bite of sharp cheddar.
   In fact, the future of french fries is so bright they'll be
coming every sort of way _ except with shades, says Moseley,
marketing director for the nation's largest potato processor.
   ``Customers will still buy the normal straight potatoes, but
they've gotten a little bored with them,'' Moseley said in an
interview at the headquarters of Lamb-Weston, Inc.
   ``I think that's why seasoning comes into play,'' he said.
``People are going to more unique cuts and more flavored potato
products.''
   Lamb-Weston, which supplies 30 percent of the nation's frozen
potatoes, offers frozen tempura fries in curly or criss-cross
shapes, potato skins, cheddar fries, spicy fries, oval potato
slices and tiny baked potatoes.
   ``That's where the business is up,'' Moseley said.
   Examples include the restaurant chain Arby's, which is selling a
Lamb-Weston seasoned curly fry, he said.
   Hardee's and Rax restaurants also offer potato options, and
McDonald's is investigating an alternative potato, he said.
   Fast-food chains also are demanding low-cholesterol frying oils,
such as canola oil, to keep health-conscious customers happy,
Moseley said.
   Competition from baked potatoes, potato chips and other spud
products are threatening the market share of the venerable french
fry in restaurants and grocery stores, industry officials say.
   ``The demand for fries is not declining but holding steady,''
said Nancy McCarthy of The Potato Board in Denver. ``But chips are
going up, an average of 5 percent increase a year.''
   The nation consumes about 5.5 billion pounds of frozen potatoes
a year, and Ms. McCarthy said annual per capita consumption of
potatoes is rising, from 115 pounds in 1980 to 123 pounds in 1987.
   The biggest change is that frozen potatoes are capturing more
and more of the market as consumers become strapped for time. That
benefits Northwest growers who send the bulk of their crop to
processors.
   Consumers on average ate 74.6 pounds of processed potatoes and
47 pounds of fresh potatoes in 1987, Ms. McCarthy said. That
compared to 1980, when consumers ate 64 pounds of processed spuds
and 51 pounds of fresh, she said.
   ``It's a lot easier to pick up frozen french fries than to make
your own,'' she said. ``I don't think we're raising a generation
that can cook.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
