<FIRST>u a AM-WeatherpageWeather     11-14 0453</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Weatherpage Weather,0467</SECOND>
<HEAD>Snow And Cold Heading Down From Canada</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   The first big snow storm of the season slid onto the northern
Plains and upper Mississippi Valley on Tuesday with much colder
air, while unseasonably warm temperatures hit record highs over the
eastern and south-central states.
   A winter storm watch was posted into Wednesday for east-central
and southeastern Minnesota.
   From late Monday into early Tuesday, a minor weather disturbance
brought a light dusting of snow to much of northwestern Wisconsin
and northern and central Minnesota, with 2 inches reported at
Carlton, Minn., the National Weather Service reported.
   By Tuesday afternoon, snow was falling across most of Minnesota
and over parts of North Dakota, with up to 3 inches reported in
southern North Dakota.
   A large, cold air mass in southern Canada was expected to spill
into the north-central states during the night and spread much
colder temperatures across much of the nation east of the Rockies
over the next several days.
   A winter storm watch was posted for Wednesday over parts of
western and central Upper Michigan, primarily near Lake Superior,
with more than 8 inches of snow expected in some areas.
   Farther west, heavy snow blanketed parts of northern Wyoming
during the night and Cody had more than 10 inches of snow Tuesday.
Wind in southeastern Wyoming gusted to 55 mph near Cheyenne during
the morning.
   Elsewhere, showers and thunderstorms were scattered from the
central Gulf Coast into southern sections of the Great Lakes
region, with some locally heavy rain.
   Early morning showers and thunderstorms produced 2.5 inches of
rain at Anniston, Ala., in six hours. During the six hours up to 1
p.m. EST, 1.65 of rain fell at Fort Leonard Wood, Mo., with 1.13
inches at Jackson, Tenn.
   An early morning thunderstorm in eastern Missouri produced high
wind which downed several trees and unroofed the deck of home at
Farmington, the weather service said.
   Showers were scattered over northern New England and along the
Carolina coast.
   Unseasonably warm temperatures continued over the south-central
and eastern states, with readings generally above 70 from the
southern Plains to the Atlantic Coast, with 80s in south-central
and eastern Texas and the Florida Peninsula.
   In Texas, the temperature at Dallas was up to 87 by early
afternoon, Waco had already hit 90 and Corpus Christi reported a
record high of 91.
   Nine other cities also reported record high or record-tying
temperatures:
   Alamosa, Colo., 62; Atlantic City, N.J., 75; Cape Hatteras,
N.C., 78; Concord, N.H., 68; San Angelo, Texas, 86; Scranton, Pa.,
70, tie; Syracuse, N.Y.; 71; Worcester, Mass., 68, tie; and
Youngstown, Ohio, 68.
   Tuesday's low for the Lower 48 states was 6 degrees above zero
at Gunnison, Colo.
</TEXT>
