<DOCNO> AP891114-0155 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-11-14-89 1835EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>u a AM-RiotTrial     11-14 0527</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Riot Trial,0543</SECOND>
<BYLINE>Judge Swears in Multi-Racial Jury ^By RICHARD COLE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MIAMI (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A multi-racial jury was sworn in Tuesday to hear
the manslaughter case against a Miami police officer accused of
shooting a black motorcyclist, sparking three days of rioting in
January.
   Dade Circuit Judge Joseph Farina dismissed last-minute defense
appeals to move the trial from this racially divided city, and
scheduled opening arguments for Wednesday.
   ``This case, your honor, has been surrounded by violence since
the beginning,'' defense attorney Roy Black argued in seeking a
change of venue.
   Prosecutor Richard Shiffrin countered by saying three weeks of
intensive questioning had produced an impartial panel that would
not be influenced by fears that their verdict could spark renewed
rioting.
   The jury of two blacks, one Hispanic and three non-Hispanic
whites will decide the case against William Lozano, who fatally
shot Clement Lloyd, 23. Lloyd's passenger, Allan Blanchard, 24,
died of injuries suffered when the motorcycle crashed.
   The jury will be sequestered during the trial, which could last
up to six weeks.
   Fears that an acquittal could set off new rioting were somewhat
calmed by the presence of two blacks on the jury, said William
Sims, a member of the Dade County Community Relations Board.
   ``It's not so tense, people are just aware, watching,'' Sims
said. ``The fact that the jury resembles the tri-ethnic balance of
this community goes a long way in reducing that level of tensions.''
   The judge also brushed aside new defense attempts to unseat
black juror Ezra Simmons. A state appeals court ruled Monday that
Farina rightfully seated the black union leader after finding the
defense had challenged him solely on the basis of race.
   Black introduced new testimony from a private detective Tuesday
attempting to show Simmons was unreliable in employment hearings,
but the judge again refused to exclude the juror.
   Following Tuesday's hearing, Black complained that the judge's
rulings in the case have ``already excluded 75 percent of our
defense.''
   In earlier pre-trial motions, Farina denied defense efforts to
introduce Lloyd's drug connections and police record.
   Farina also ruled that the prosecution can use testimony about
Miami city police regulations in an attempt to show Lozano acted
negligently and unprofessionally when he shot and killed Lloyd.
   The defense, however, may bring up 5.5 grams of marijuana found
on Lloyd's body, as well as $1,500 cash he had in his pocket. They
may also tell jurors that Lloyd had alcohol and high level of THC,
marijauana's active ingredient, in his bloodstream. The judge
barred such testimony about passenger Blanchard.
   Lozano faces two manslaughter counts for the deaths of Lloyd and
Blanchard. In the subsequent racial violence, one person was
killed, 11 were wounded by gunfire and 13 buildings were burned
down.
   If convicted on both counts, he would face a maximum penalty of
60 years imprisonment.
   Lozano fired one shot, hitting Lloyd in the head and killing
him, as the motorcyclist sped away from another officer.
   The defense argues Lozano acted in self-defense against a
drug-crazed dealer who did not want to be sent back to jail, and
was willing to run the officer over to escape.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
