<DOCNO> AP891114-0157 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-11-14-89 1841EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>u i AM-France-EC     11-14 0508</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-France-EC,0521</SECOND>
<HEAD>European Community Summit Called to Consider Soviet-bloc Changes</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JEFFREY ULBRICH</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>PARIS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Leaders of the 12-nation European Community will
meet Saturday in the Elysee Palace to analyze the surge of changes
in the Soviet bloc and how they can influence Europe's future
instead of the superpowers.
   President Francois Mitterrand, in a surprise move Monday,
invited the other European Community (EC) members to a special
summit.
   There had been calls for such a meeting to be held before the
summit of Soviet President Mikhail S. Gorbachev and President Bush
set for Dec. 2-3 aboard ships off Malta.
   The EC, also known as the European Common Market, had scheduled
a summit conference for Dec. 8-9 in Strasbourg, France, but the
flood of events in Eastern Europe prompted Mitterrand to call the
special meeting in advance of the U.S.-Soviet and EC summits.
   Former French Foreign Minister Michel Jobert said in a radio
interview, ``Do we want the United States and the Soviet Union,
once again, to decide the destiny of Europe?''
   And former President Valery Giscard d'Estaing, the leader of
France's main centrist political coalition, had urged Mitterrand's
socialist government to call an emergency EC summit.
   In a radio interview Sunday, Giscard d'Estaing said it would be
``unacceptable that the first analysis of the events in Europe be
made by the Americans and the Soviets and not by the Europeans.''
   Mitterrand called Saturday's meeting as EC president. He is
president of the organization under a six-month rotating system and
his term ends with the Strasbourg summit.
   There were indications that most other EC leaders welcomed the
Elysee Palace summit.
   British Prime Minister Margaret Thatcher, in a speech Monday
night, did not refer to Mitterrand's invitation but said, ``The
Community should see what is happening as a great turning point in
Europe's history, and its response must measure up to that.''
   Hans-Dietrich Genscher, the West German foreign minister, said
it is important that ``the European Community gets together on such
a dramatic development. Besides analyzing the situation, one must
also examine what the EC can do to help the people and to ensure
that the reform process develops in a stable manner.''
   In his invitations Mitterrand said the summit was called ``to
discuss the recent developments in the situation in Europe.''
   It is rare for EC leaders to meet at the top level outside the
framework of their semiannual summits and even more unusual that
such a meeting could be organized so quickly.
   Analysts said the Elysee Palace dinner-summit could serve two
major purposes: It gives the Europeans a chance to organize their
position before the U.S.-Soviet conference and keeps the agenda of
the Strasbourg summit open for Mitterrand's two pet projects _
European monetary union and a European social charter.
   West German Chancellor Helmut Kohl had asked Mitterrand to make
the German question the central theme of the Strasbourg meeting.
That probably would have served Mrs. Thatcher and some West German
officials who are not enthusiastic about a monetary union and
social charter.
</TEXT>
