<FIRST>u i AM-Czechoslovak-Trial     11-14 0300</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Czechoslovak-Trial,0308</SECOND>
<HEAD>Human Rights Activist Convicted, Given Suspended Sentence</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Czechoslovakia</HEAD>
<DATELINE>VIENNA, Austria (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Miroslav Kusy, a leading Czechoslovak
human rights activist, was convicted Tuesday of ``harming state
interests abroad'' and given a suspended jail sentence of eight
months, an emigre source reported.
   The source, speaking privately, said the court in Bratislava
acquitted Hana Ponicka, Anton Selecky and Vladimir Manak, who were
charged with sedition last summer together with Jan Carnogursky,
another activist.
   All five had signed a statement urging Slovaks to mark the 21st
anniversary of the Soviet-led invasion of August 1968, which
crushed the brief ``Prague spring'' of reform, by laying flowers in
memory of the victims.
   About 100 supporters, who could not get into the court building
in Bratislava for the two-day trial, shouted ``Long live freedom!''
and ``Long live Dubcek!'' after the verdicts were announced.
   Alexander Dubcek, the Communist Party chief who led the 1968
reform and was disgraced afterward, attended the trial.
   The court changed original charges of sedition and subversion
against Kusy to ``harming state interests abroad'' under Article
112 of the criminal code, which appeared to be a lesser charge, the
source in Vienna said. The maximum prison term for sedition is five
years.
   Kusy, a party Central Committee secretary in 1968, was expelled
from the party after the invasion.
   Carnogursky, a Roman Catholic activist who has been held since
Aug. 14, faces charges of sedition and subversion, but his trial
was suspended because his lawyer is ill.
   He was brought to the courtroom in handcuffs Tuesday and asked
to testify as a witness, but refused, said Palach Press, a
newsletter based in London that monitors human rights in
Czechoslovakia. It said Carnogursky would be tried next Monday and
Tuesday.
   Last week, about 200 people demonstrated in Bratislava for his
release.
</TEXT>
