<FIRST>r i AM-Berlin-WelcomeMoney     11-14 0214</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Berlin-Welcome Money,0217</SECOND>
<HEAD>$82 Million of `Welcome Money' Paid Out in West Berlin</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-East Germany</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BERLIN (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The friendly weekend invasion from the East when
the Berlin Wall was opened cost the West German government $82
million in ``welcome money,'' the city's bankers said Tuesday.
   The West Berlin bank association said 1.5 million visitors from
East Germany came through the wall and banks gave each 100 marks
($55) on the government's behalf, for a total of 150 million marks,
or about $82 million.
   Figures were not available from the other parts of West Germany
visited by 1.5 million more East Germans, but the total paid in
``welcome money'' probably was double the West Berlin figure.
   By government policy, each East German visitor is entitled to
100 marks once a year. East Germans traveling abroad can take along
only 15 West German marks, equivalent to a little more than $8, and
East German marks are not covertible.
   Earlier Tuesday, West Berlin banks threatened to suspend
payments of ``welcome money'' unless Bonn covered their operating
costs, and the government agreed. The banks stayed open most of the
weekend to handle long lines of East Germans.
   Officials said the government was raising its total ``welcome
money'' allocation from 479 million marks to 779 million.
</TEXT>
