<FILEID>AP-NR-11-14-89 2148EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r i AM-Israel-Dialogue     11-14 0558</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Israel-Dialogue,0575</SECOND>
<HEAD>Palestinian Leader Talks Peace to Jewish, Arab Students</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By SERGEI SHARGORODSKY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>JERUSALEM (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   As right-wing Israelis shouted and banged their
fists on lecture hall doors Tuesday, a pro-PLO Palestinian leader
and hundreds of Jewish and Arab students discussed the bloody
conflict between their people.
   Several fistfights erupted outside the Hebrew University lecture
hall shortly after Faisal Husseini, a leading Palestinian activist,
was led in, encircled by Arab students.
   Security guards and plainclothes police scuffled with dozens of
right-wing activists wearing the knitted skullcaps of observant
Jews, and at least one Israeli was dragged out, kicking and pushing.
   But inside, the peace dialogue went on as planned by a left-wing
Arab-Jewish student group and the Jerusalem Arab Students
Committee. It was designed to mark the first anniversary of the
declaration of Palestinian independence issued by the Palestine
National Council, the PLO's parliament-in-exile.
   ``We're fighting for our own freedom and not for the enslavement
of others, for our own country and not for the destruction of
another country,'' declared Husseini, who comes from one of the
most powerful Palestinian families.
   ``I want to send a message to Israeli leaders: there's no other
way to peace but through the leaders of another people, and this
leadership is the PLO,'' he said, interrupted by loud applause.
   Israel refuses to talk to the PLO, which it officially sees as a
terrorist group bent on destroying the Jewish state. It is willing
to negotiate elections with non-PLO Palestinians from the occupied
territories and then hold talks on limited autonomy with the
elected delegates.
   Husseini, who has been jailed without trial for a total of 18
months since July 1987, insisted that Israel must talk to the PLO
if it wants to negotiate peace.
   ``I want to talk peace with (Prime Minister Yitzhak) Shamir,''
Husseini said. ``I think he's a man of war, I don't want to talk to
him and I don't like him. But he is representing the Israeli
people. Your enemies are the Palestinians and they have
representatives.''
   A Jewish student argued that Arabs from the West Bank and the
Gaza Strip could represent the Palestinian side.
   ``It's well known you receive your orders from the PLO,'' said
the student. ``The Jewish people have a psychological problem with
the PLO, so why don't you stop calling them the PLO and start peace
talks?''
   Husseini countered by saying it has been equally difficult for
him to pronounce the word ``Israel.''
   Outside, right-wingers banged on the doors, shouting: ``PLO out!
You are a leader of killers, PLO, go to hell!''
   An Israeli student jumped from his seat, shouting at Husseini:
``You're Nazis, you're killing Jews every day!'' He was dragged out
of the hall by force.
   An Arab student then demanded to know what the next stage of the
23-month-old Palestinian uprising should be.
   ``The struggle we want to lead is civil disobedience,'' Husseini
responded. ``We are pushed to it by the occupation. We can reach a
solution before that, if Israel starts to treat us as people, not
as residents or refugees.''
   At least 615 Palestinians have died of Israeli gunfire, and 41
Israelis have been slain in the rebellion.
   At the end of the three-hour meeting, security guards whisked
Husseini away through a back door _ only to find the windshield of
his car smashed.
</TEXT>
