<SECOND>AM-Salvador Rebel,0322</SECOND>
<HEAD>Salvadoran Rebel Leader Says No End to Fighting</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Salvador, Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DORALISA PILARTE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MANAGUA, Nicaragua (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A Salvadoran rebel leader said Tuesday
that El Salvador's armed forces must be purged of a ``truly
criminal'' element before the rebels will resume peace talks with
the government.
   Commander Mario Lopez of the political-diplomatic commission of
the guerrillas' Farabundo Marti National Liberation Front (FMLN)
also said there would not be an immediate end to the offensive
launched by the left-wing rebels Saturday night.
   ``This is a military campaign ... of very great scope,'' he
said. ``The general command has ordered its forces to maintain
positions and advance.''
   Lopez spoke at a news conference at the foreign correspondents'
club.
   He said civilians have been joining the rebels, but declined to
give any figures.
   ``This is a process of insurrection. I couldn't say how far it
will go,'' Lopez said.
   He said the FMLN has been seeking international mediation
between the rebels and President Alfredo Cristiani's rightist
government, but there have been no results.
   A proposal Tuesday at the Organization of American States
meeting in Washington by Nicaraguan Foreign Minister Miguel
D'Escoto could lead to such mediation, Lopez said. He did not
elaborate.
   He said before the FMLN stops the offensive and agrees to resume
peace talks there must be a ``self-purge of the armed forces'' that
would lead to more democratic conditions.
   ``The ones who govern El Salvador are the armed forces; it's a
sector within the armed forces that is making the war a great
business,'' Lopez said. ``There can be no democratic process in the
country without a purge of the armed forces.''
   He said the United States ``always has bet on a military triumph
over the FMLN and that hasn't changed with (President) Bush,'' but
the rebel leadership is open to talks with Washington.
</TEXT>
