<FIRST>r a AM-ParkJogger     11-14 0479</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Park Jogger,0493</SECOND>
<HEAD>Jogger Released From Hospital</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By SAMUEL MAULL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The jogger who was gang-raped, beaten and left
for dead during a teen-age ``wilding'' spree in Central Park was
released Tuesday from a Connecticut hospital after nearly seven
months of rehabilitation.
   The jogger, a 29-year-old investment banker originally from the
Pittsburgh area, will continue outpatient treatment at Gaylord
Hospital in Wallingford, Conn., a spokesman there said.
   She still is unable to recall the attack and its aftermath,
``but she has made good recovery and rehabilitation,'' said
hospital spokesman Gerald Main.
   On April 19, the jogger was on her nightly run in the park when
she was dragged 200 feet into the underbrush, raped, beaten with a
pipe and a rock and left unconscious.
   When police found her 3{ hours later, she was in a coma and had
lost almost 80 percent of her blood. She suffered brain contusions,
two head fractures, broken facial bones and bruises from head to
toe. Paramedics did not expect her to live.
   She remained in critical condition at a New York City hospital
until May 1, when she appeared to raise her eyebrows as her name
was called and raised her hand. She was walking a bit when she was
moved June 7 to Gaylord Hospital.
   By midsummer, she was reading novels, relearning basic math and
calling colleagues at Salomon Bros., where she worked before the
attack.
   Main said the jogger and her family thanked the public and press
for their support over the past months. ``This support has made a
difference in her ability to recover,'' he read from the statement.
   He said they also thanked news media for respecting her privacy
and anonymity and stressed that the woman's continued recovery ``is
highly dependent'' on her privacy and anonymity being maintained.
   Main would not say what time the patient left the hospital or
where she went, or comment beyond the prepared statement.
   The brutality of the attack focused attention on the phenomenon
of ``wilding,'' in which young criminals roam from victim to victim
to harass, attack and rob.
   The city's legions of joggers were unwilling to surrender the
park, which stretches 2{ miles through the center of Manhattan. In
June, prompted by the attack, the New York Road Runners Club
launched a safety program.
   Six teen-agers have been indicted in the attack: Raymond
Santana, Steven Lopez, Yusef Salaam, Kevin Richardson and Antron
McCray, all 15, and Kharey Wise, 17.
   All currently are involved in a state Supreme Court hearing in
Manhattan on whether statements they gave police should be allowed
as evidence at their upcoming trials. Defense lawyers maintain the
statements, in which nearly all the youth implicate themselves or
their codefendants, were coerced and therefore illegal.
   Police said those indicted were part of a gang of more than 30
youths on the ``wilding'' spree.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
