<DOCNO> AP891114-0170 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-11-14-89 2204EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r i AM-Ethiopia-Drought     11-14 0338</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Ethiopia-Drought,0348</SECOND>
<HEAD>UN Says Crop Failure Imperils Northern Ethiopia</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By PETER JAMES SPIELMANN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>UNITED NATIONS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Drought-induced crop failure in Ethiopia's
two rebellious northern provinces will be worse this season than in
the 1984-85 famine that killed 1 million people, according to the
U.N. Children's Fund.
   An internal document from UNICEF obtained Tuesday by The
Associated Press says up to 2 million Ethiopians could be affected
by the drought as famine conditions develop in 1990.
   In 1984-85, relief figures indicate 1 million people starved to
death in the northern provinces of Tigre and Eritrea; in 1987-88, a
massive international relief operation prevented a similar tragedy
during another crop failure.
   ``The first signs of famine already have been reported, not only
in ... Eritrea, where influxes of displaced people are on the
increase, but also in other areas, in particular Akele Guzay
district, where farmers are selling their livestock at only
one-third of the normal price,'' the report says.
   ``Livestock disposal at very low prices is one of the early
warning indicators that a drought situation is becoming alarming,''
it said.
   UNICEF officials said they will soon announce a $9.05 million
fund-raising campaign to provide food and services to northern
Ethiopia to prevent widespread starvation.
   ``This drought _ according to the assessments of the main
harvest planting made by U.N. agencies, including UNICEF, and by
the government of Ethiopia _ will be worse than in 1984-85 in terms
of crop failure,'' the report says.
   ``In Eritrea, the crop failure is estimated to be 90 to 100
percent, while in Tigre it reaches 40 percent,'' it says.
   ``Furthermore, these two regions are afflicted by civil wars
respectively 28 and 15 years old, which restrict movements of goods
and people and limit the access of assistance.''
   Rebels in those provinces are fighting for autonomy or secession
from the Marxist central government, controlled by President
Mengistu Haile Mariam.
   Up to 333,000 metric tons of grain will be needed to feed 1.85
million people, the UNICEF report says.
</TEXT>
