<FIRST>u i AM-Burma-Amnesty     11-14 0455</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Burma-Amnesty,0466</SECOND>
<HEAD>Human Rights Group Condemns Burma</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DENIS D. GRAY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BANGKOK, Thailand (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Amnesty International charged on
Wednesday that Burma's military rulers have arrested thousands of
people, carried out unfair trials and are holding political
prisoners.
   The London-based human rights group called for the commutation
of 100 death sentences that have been handed down by the martial
law government and for the release of all political prisoners.
   The Amnesty report, received in Bangkok, listed 107 ``prisoners
of conscience'' and other political prisoners believed still in
detention. Amnesty defines prisoners of conscience as people
detained solely for peacefully expressing their beliefs.
   The list of prisoners included the nation's top opposition
leader, Aung San Suu Kyi, as well as a Buddhist monk and a
novelist. Most on the list were students and members of Suu Kyi's
National League for Democracy.
   Amnesty quoted unnamed sources as saying more than 3,000 people
had been arrested since July 1989. The organization said it could
not confirm this number because it had not been able to visit
Burma, but it documented the arrests of a number of political
opponents to the regime.
   ``Amnesty believes that arrests during this period (after late
July) numbered in the thousands,'' the report said.
   Last month, the Rangoon government announced it had arrested
1,087 people for political offenses since September 1988, when a
group of military leaders brutally crushed a nationwide
pro-democracy uprising. The leaders set up a 17-man military
council and declared martial law.
   But the formation of more than 200 political parties has been
allowed and the military is promising general elections May 27 of
next year.
   The house arrest last July of Suu Kyi and Tin Oo, leaders of the
National League For Democracy, along with other senior members of
the pro-democracy party led many Western diplomats in Rangoon to
conclude that free elections were unlikely.
   The government also has said it had handed down 100 death
sentences, many by special military tribunals. Amnesty described
some of the trials as unfair by international standards.
   Similar charges have been made in recent months by the United
States, which also claims some political detainess have died under
torture. Rangoon has denied this.
   In a speech Nov. 10 Gen. Saw Maung, who heads the military
government, said citizens had nothing to be afraid of ``unless, of
course, you break the law.''
   ``There are accusations that we are following the methods of the
Japanese Kempetai. That is not true. If they say we use Gestapo
methods then they are wrong too,'' Saw Maung told a graduating
class at Burma's National Defense College. The Japanese secret
police Kempetai and the Nazi's Gestapo employed torture and
committed other atrocities during World War II.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP891114-0172 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-11-14-89 1938EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>u a AM-CosmicExplorer     11-14 0647</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Cosmic Explorer,0662</SECOND>
<HEAD>Saturday Launch For NASA's Last Unmanned Rocket, Early Universe Probe</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By LEE SIEGEL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Science Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>PASADENA, Calif. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   NASA's planned launch of its last
unmanned rocket Saturday will send the first of several satellites
to study how the universe has evolved since its birth in the ``big
bang'' 15 billion years ago, officials said Tuesday.
   The new launch date for the $150 million, 4,850-pound Cosmic
Background Explorer was announced after space agency engineers
fixed a faulty guidance computer on the rocket that will carry the
spacecraft into orbit.
   ``This is going to begin an explosion of knowledge about the
universe,'' David Gilman, manager of the $400 million Cosmic
Background Explorer program, said during a news conference at the
space agency's Jet Propulsion Laboratory.
   The satellite, the Hubble Space Telescope and three other
observatories to be placed in Earth orbit during the 1990s ``are
going to provide us with an unprecedented, unbelievable view of the
universe,'' program scientist Larry Caroff said.
   ``We will see things we haven't even imagined,'' he predicted.
``Hold on to your hats because this is going to shake up the world
of science.''
   The satellite is scheduled for launch from Vandenberg Air Force
Base on the central California coast during a 30-minute period
starting at 6:24 a.m. PST Saturday.
   The 16-by-28-foot, solar-powered satellite is to be carried into
a 559-mile-high, near-polar orbit by a 116-foot-tall Delta rocket,
the last unmanned, expendable rocket to be launched by the National
Aeronautics and Space Administration.
   NASA will continue to launch manned shuttles and possibly
unmanned cargo shuttles with reusable boosters. But the Air Force
or private companies will charge NASA to launch any payloads that
require unmanned, expendable rockets.
   The satellite's launch had been scheduled for Friday, then was
delayed until Sunday because of a malfunctioning guidance computer.
But the computer was replaced so quickly last weekend that the
launch was moved up to Saturday, said Peter Eaton, a NASA rocket
official.
   The satellite was to have originally been put in orbit by a
shuttle, but was diverted to an unmanned rocket after the 1986
Challenger disaster.
   Once in orbit and after a 30-day shakedown, the satellite will
spend up to two years measuring cosmic background radiation, which
makes up about 2 percent of the static on a television set. It
includes microwaves, heat and other electromagnetic radiation given
off by the ``big bang,'' the gargantuan explosion scientists
believe created the universe an estimated 15 billion years ago.
   ``The radiation we're measuring is actually the remnant of the
great explosion itself,'' project scientist John Mather said.
``We're looking at it as it was a very long time ago. We're seeing
the primary cosmic fossil.''
   With the three most sensitive sensors of their types, the
satellite will measure ``the collective glow of all the stars and
galaxies and whatever else has been there since the beginning,''
Mather said.
   That will help scientists learn more about what happened in the
time between three minutes after the big bang, when the first
atomic nuclei or centers formed, and 500,000 years later, when the
first atoms formed. It also will search for light from the creation
of the first stars and galaxies about 200 million years after the
primeval fireball.
   Mather said NASA will share information from the mission with
the Soviet Union, which has flown one similar research mission and
plans two others.
   A shuttle is scheduled to carry the Hubble Space Telescope into
orbit in March. An optical telescope of unprecedented power, it
also may see formation of the earliest galaxies, said Nancy
Boggess, deputy project scientist on the Cosmic Background Explorer
program.
   That will be followed by the shuttle launches of the Gamma Ray
Observatory in June and the Advanced X-ray Astrophysics Facility in
1997, Gilman said. A private, expendable rocket will launch the
Space Infrared Telescope Facility in 1999, he added.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP891114-0173 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-11-14-89 2355EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r i AM-Taiwan-Dissident     11-14 0354</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Taiwan-Dissident,0363</SECOND>
<HEAD>Taiwan Rejects Entry of Former U.S. Attorney General Clark</HEAD>
<DATELINE>TAIPEI, Taiwan (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Taiwan has refused to allow former U.S.
Attorney General Ramsey Clark to enter the country to visit a
Taiwanese dissident jailed for advocating independence for this
island, another dissident said Tuesday.
   Hsieh Tsung-min told The Associated Press that Clark, now a
human rights lawyer in New York, planned to arrive in Taipei from
Tokyo Monday. He returned to New York when he was informed of
Taiwan's refusal, Hsieh said.
   Hsieh said Taiwan authorities earlier gave Clark permission to
meet dissident Hsu Hsin-liang, 48, former publisher of a dissident
magazine, who sneaked back to Taiwan in a fishing boat from
mainland China in September.
   Hsu had been living in the United States since an
anti-government riot erupted in Kaohsiung, southern Taiwan, in
1979. Although Hsu was not in Taiwan at that time, officials claim
he helped organize the riot.
   Foreign Ministry spokesman Chen Yu-chu said only that he was
informed Clark changed his mind about his Taiwan visit while in
Tokyo.
   Donald Biship, spokesman for the American Institute in Taiwan,
which handles relations between Taiwan and the United States in the
absence of diplomatic ties, declined comment.
   Hsieh said Clark had planned to offer legal advice to Hsu during
a four-day visit. Clark also planned to discuss Hsu's case with
Taiwan's Interior Ministry and Justice Ministry, Hsieh said.
   Hsu was accused of advocating independence for Taiwan while in
the United States, and he was indicted by the Taiwan High Court
last month on sedition charges.
   He is scheduled to go on trial Saturday and could be sentenced
to 20 years imprisonment if convicted.
   Earlier this month, the U.S. State Department issued a statement
expressing concern over Hsu's case, saying Washington understood he
was indicted for activities under which foreign nationals are
protected by the U.S. government.
   The Nationalists, who fled to Taiwan in 1949 after losing a
civil war to the Communists, continue to claim they are the sole
legitimate government of all China. Both the Communists and
Nationalists consider Taiwan a Chinese province and oppose an
independent Taiwan.
</TEXT>
