<FIRST>u w AM-NicaraguaPeaceTalks     11-14 0318</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Nicaragua Peace Talks,320</SECOND>
<HEAD>Negotiations Show Little Sign of Progress</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-US-Nicaragua</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By GEORGE GEDDA</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Talks between Nicaraguan officials and the
Contra rebels remained deadlocked Tuesday night as the two sides
were unable to bridge their differences over terms for a cease-fire
and for demobilization of the insurgents, participants said.
   As the fourth day of talks ended, Nicaraguan Cardinal Miguel
Obando y Bravo told reporters he was less optimistic Tuesday night
than he was last Thursday when the negotiations opened at the
United Nations.
   Asked why there is a stalemate, Obando y Bravo said, ``It's
difficult because each side has his own point of view.''
   The head of the Sandinista delegation, Vice Foreign Minister
Victor Hugo Tinoco, said he was somewhat more optimistic than he
was after the conclusion of the talks Monday night.
   The discussions will resume Wednesday afternoon.
   Obando y Bravo is officially described as a ``witness'' at the
talks. Also participating are representatives from the United
Nations, the Organization of American States and the Honduran
government.
   A key sticking point is a Sandinista demand that rebels now
based inside Nicaraguan territory return to base camps in Honduras
immediately after a joint cease-fire is achieved. At that point,
the demobilization of the Contras would begin.
   The rebel position is that the estimated 5,000 Contras in
Nicaragua should be allowed to remain at their positions once the
cease fire is called.
   The chief Contra negotiator, Col. Enrique Bermudez, said the
rebels are wary of demobilization because it is an ``irreversible
step'' that must be accompanied by guarantees for the rebels'
safety.
   The Sandinista position further states that once all Contra
forces have returned to the base camps in Honduras, the United
States would turn over to an international commission humanitarian
funds earmarked for the Contras.
   The funds would be used ``to contribute to the peace process,''
the Sandinista proposal asserts.
</TEXT>
