<FIRST>r i AM-UN-Namibia     11-14 0214</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-UN-Namibia,0219</SECOND>
<HEAD>UN Chief Hails Namibians For Conducting Free and Fair Election</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Namibia</HEAD>
<DATELINE>UNITED NATIONS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Secretary-General Javier Perez de Cuellar
said Tuesday that Namibia's elections were free and fair and hailed
voters in the territory for their ``political maturity.''
   The U.N. chief also praised South African election officials and
U.N. poll- watchers for playing their part in making the election
run smoothly.
   ``The fact that the elections proceeded in a peaceful and
orderly manner and that the political parties observed the agreed
code of conduct during the election process was testimony to the
political maturity of the Namibian people,'' Perez de Cuellar told
the Security Council.
   The newly elected Constituent Assembly will open its
deliberations to write a constitution and organize a government
next week, said U.N. spokesman Francois Giuliani.
   Namibians voted from Tuesday through Saturday for the 72-member
assembly, which will draft a constitution and declare independence
for Namibia after 74 years of South African rule.
   The leftist South-West Africa People's Organization won 57
percent of the ballots cast, according to results announced
Tuesday. But it did not win the two-thirds majority that would have
allowed it to single-handedly write the constitution.
   The Democratic Turnhalle Alliance, a multiracial coalition that
favors a capitalist economy, finished second with 29 percent.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
