<DOCNO> AP891114-0184 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-11-14-89 2111EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>u w AM-DisabilitiesAct     11-14 0311</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Disabilities Act,300</SECOND>
<BYLINE>By ROBERT T. GREENE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The House Education and Labor Committee voted
unanimously Tuesday to approve a bill guaranteeing a wide range of
rights to disabled Americans, the first House panel to approve the
measure since the Senate passed it in September.
   Three other House committees must approve the bill _ Judiciary,
Energy and Commerce, and Public Works and Transportation.
   The version approved Tuesday was virtually the same as the
Senate measure, which passed 76-8. Some clarifications were added
to the bill, which prevents discrimination against the disabled in
employment, public accommodations, public transportation and access
to telephone service.
   The clarifications were the result of bipartisan negotiations,
just as the Senate bill was the result of negotiations with the
White House, which had sought to soften timetables and enforcement
provisions.
   The House version clarifies that although rehabilitated drug
users are considered disabled and protected under the act, a person
who currently uses drugs and is otherwise disabled is not protected.
   Although the vote Tuesday was unanimous, Republicans
unsuccessfully fought to introduce several amendments reflecting
concerns of the small business community.
   When considering the ability of a business that is part of a
larger entity to pay for changes required under the law, courts may
consider the financial resources of the overall entity, according
to one of the clarifications.
   Also, the House version says that the maximum fine of $50,000
for violations of the public accommodations provision applies to
all violations that make up a ``pattern and practice'' suit brought
by the attorney general, and not an individual violation. Second
violations carry a maximum fine of $100,000 under the same standard.
   Lawmakers had been hoping to have a House version passed and a
final bill ready for President Bush's signature by Christmas. Such
an outcome appears unlikely given the present pace of hearings.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
