<FIRST>u a AM-Navy-Accidents-Fleet     11-14 0437</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Navy-Accidents-Fleet,0450</SECOND>
<HEAD>Fire Aboard Docked Carrier Injures 31, Two Aviators Safe In F-14
Crash</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Navy-Accidents, Bjt</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto NK1</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By D.W. PAGE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NORFOLK, Va. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A fire broke out aboard a Navy carrier
Tuesday, injuring 31 people on the same day the service ordered its
ships and planes to halt normal operations for 48 hours due to a
string of accidents.
   The fire aboard the helicopter carrier USS Inchon, which was in
a shipyard for routine repairs, was the ninth serious accident
involving Navy ships and planes in the past three weeks.
   In another accident Tuesday, a Navy F-14 Tomcat fighter went
down 60 miles northwest of Key West, Fla., while on a routine
training mission, the Navy said. The two fliers parachuted to
safety.
   The fire aboard the Inchon was reported at 9:30 a.m. in the
shore power cable compartment, where lines supplying power to the
ship enter from the pier, said Lt. Cmdr. John Lloyd, a spokesman
for the Atlantic Fleet.
   The fire was extinguished within 10 minutes with help from the
USS Harlan County, which was docked nearby, Lloyd said. The fire
was contained in the compartment, but the helicopter carrier's
hangar deck sustained smoke and heat damage, he said.
   Twenty-three sailors who helped fight the fire and eight
civilians were taken to six hospitals for smoke inhalation, the
spokesman said. Nine were admitted, and the rest were treated and
released. One man was in serious condition with smoke-inhalation
burns at Sentara-Norfolk General Hospital, said Deborah Meyers, a
hospital spokeswoman.
   The 602-foot Inchon has a crew of 675 and can carry up to 2,000
Marines and 20 helicopters.
   The crash of the F-14 occurred around 1 p.m., Petty Officer 2nd
Class Michael Frost said at Naval Air Station Key West.
   The pilot, Lt. j.g. John T. Burns, 26, and the radar intercept
officer, Lt. Donovan Williams, 31, escaped without serious injury,
officials said. The two men are based at Oceana Naval Air Station
in Virginia Beach, Va.
   The crash occurred shortly before the Navy order that all
operations cease for 48 hours during the next three days while
safety procedures are reviewed.
   The order requires every ship, squadron and shore training
facility to interrupt normal operations and review basic safety and
operating procedures.
   Ten people have been killed or lost at sea and at least 45 have
been injured in the series of accidents since Oct. 29.
   The accidents included a training jet crashing into an aircraft
carrier off Florida, sailors washed overboard on two different
aircraft carriers and the accidental bombing of a cruiser in the
Indian Ocean.
</TEXT>
