<FIRST>u w AM-Education-Bush 1stLd-Writethru   11-14 0539</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Education-Bush, 1st Ld-Writethru,a0589,490</SECOND>
<HEAD>Hawkins Flunks Bush as `Education President'</HEAD>
<HEAD>EDs: INSERTS grafs 9-11: ``Replying to,'' with Cavazos' reponse</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By TAMARA HENRY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Education Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The chairman of the House Education and Labor
Committee gave George Bush failing marks as the ``education
president'' Tuesday and accused him of blocking the education
secretary from doing a good job.
   Rep. Augustus Hawkins, D-Calif., acknowledged to reporters at
the National Press Club, ``I feel rather presumptive in grading the
president but I've been asked to do so.'' He then launched into
harsh criticisms of Bush, who pledged to become the ``education
president'' if elected.
   ``There is not a single accomplishment, initiative, or
educational credit with which the president can be identified, even
if the summit is so regarded,'' said Hawkins, referring to the
recent two-day meeting of Bush and the nation's governors that
resulted in a push for national performance goals.
   However, Hawkins was kinder to Education Secretary Lauro
Cavazos, noting ``he and I are very, very friendly.''
   ``I think he's a fine, honorable man. I think he has good
motives,'' said Hawkins. ``I think that if he was not restrained,
he probably would do very well. I think under the restraints, he
can't.''
   Hawkins said that Cavazos is being hampered by policies pushed
by the Office of Management and Budget and the White House, which
``I think differ diametrically from his own philosophy.''
   ``I think he's trying to do a good job in a very desperate sort
of way but will not be able to succeed because he has to accept the
policies of the administration,'' said Hawkins, who predicted
Cavazos would not complete his term at the Department of Education.
   Asked about concrete accomplishments of Cavazos, Hawkins said,
``I don't know of any.''
   Replying to Hawkins, Cavazos said in a statement: ``The remarks
made are unfounded and the allegations misleading, at a time when
the national urgently needs a constructive dialogue between the
administration and the Congress.
   ``The president knows that this nation faces a dangerous
education deficit and we are determined to directly confront the
gravity of the situation. Business as usual will not suffice.
   ``The president and I have proposed a far-reaching education
agenda for this nation. We have invigorated the education debate
across this country ... I take great honor and consider it a
privilege to serve President Bush.''
   As for Bush, Hawkins said, ``I am afraid the president's record
is an embarrassing `0 for 4.''' He pointed to the administration's
efforts to push the concept of allowing parents toselect the school
their children will attend, even though parental choice has not
been ``adequately debated, legislated or evaluated.''
   ``The administration is promoting choice to replace full funding
and implementation of current federal elementary and secondary
education programs, as embodied in the School Improvement Act of
1988,'' he said.
   Hawkins also cited Bush's veto of the education appropriations
bill, which he said would have enabled 1 million additional
disadvantaged children to improve their reading and math skills.
Bush vetoed the legislation because it contained an expansion of
abortion funding that he opposed.
   The California Democrat also criticized Bush for excluding from
the summit educators, members of Congress and representatives from
business, teachers and parents.
</TEXT>
