<FILEID>AP-NR-11-14-89 2336EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r i AM-Mexico-Drugs     11-14 0421</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Mexico-Drugs,0436</SECOND>
<HEAD>Mexico Protests U.S. Involvement in Border Drug Efforts</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By TALLI NAUMAN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MEXICO CITY (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Foreign Ministry on Tuesday objected to
U.S. plans to deploy Marines near the U.S.-Mexican border in
anti-drug operations.
   ``The Mexican government wants to make clear that it does not
share in _ nor support _ the measures announced yesterday (Monday)
by the U.S. Defense Department regarding the use of the armed
forces in a location close to the shared border,'' the ministry
said.
   Washington announced on Monday the formation of a military
intelligence center at Fort Bliss near El Paso, Texas, that reports
said would use 75 U.S. Marines in border drug-patrol operations. El
Paso is across the border from the Mexican city of Ciudad Juarez.
   The Foreign Ministry statement said the U.S. and Mexican
governments have established effective cooperation in the war
against drugs, but Washington's ``decision made unilaterally''
could have negative repercussions along the border. It did not
elaborate on the possible effects.
   ``The Mexican government recognizes the sovereign right of all
nations to institute measures in accord with their national
interests in their respective territories,'' the statement said.
   ``However, the Mexican government believes that among neighbors,
especially in friendly countries, mutual consultation is prudent
for both sides.''
   Meanwhile, the attorney general's office announced four
Colombians were arrested and 1,320 pounds of cocaine and $2 million
were seized by police at a small airstrip near Tijuana.
   At a news conference Tuesday, the attorney general's office
identified one of the suspects as Guillermo Garcia Ramirez and said
he recently was released from a U.S. prison after serving a
sentence for drug-related charges.
   Authorities gave this account of the incident that occurred
Sunday:
   Police detained Garcia Ramirez and Jesus Antonio Hurtado Burgos
when they met the pilot and co-pilot of a Turbo Commander airplane
that arrived from Cali, Colombia.
   Pilot Luis Carlos Ramirez Valderrama and co-pilot Edinson Tosse
Munoz also were arrested at the paved landing strip near Baja
California state's main north-south highway.
   The cocaine was to be transferred to the two men waiting for the
plane for shipment to New York via California.
   Garcia Ramirez and Hurtado Burgos had arrived at the airfield in
a pickup truck, inspected the landing area and hid in underbrush.
   Some hours later, when the plane flew over, the two men directed
its landing and began to unload packets of cocaine.
   Police, in position because of information about the planned
transaction, moved in, making the arrests and seizing the cocaine
and money.
</TEXT>
