<FIRST>a a PM-BusinessMirror Adv15   11-14 0582</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Business Mirror, Adv 15,0597</SECOND>
<HEAD>$adv15</HEAD>
<HEAD>For Release PMs Wednesday, Nov. 15</HEAD>
<HEAD>Small-Business Survey Shows Economic Growth Surprisingly Strong</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOHN CUNNIFF</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Analyst</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The outlook for business conditions improved
substantially in the latest quarterly survey of small businesses,
suggesting that economic growth could be surprisingly strong for
the rest of the year.
   The survey found unexpected strength in job creation and an
improvement in the inflation picture during the third quarter, but
only slight improvement in short-term borrowing conditions.
   William C. Dunkelberg, who interprets results for the National
Federation of Independent Business, said responses leave the threat
of recession something that ``at best, is likely to occur only in
the murky 1990 future.''
   Dunkelberg, dean of Temple University's school of business and
management, said the survey revealed more companies now expect
improved economic conditions over the next six months than expect a
deterioration.
   The more confident tone of the report showed up clearly in what
the Federation calls its Small Business Optimism Index, which rose
from 99.8 in the third quarter to 102.1 points in the latest
analysis.
   The index, which uses 1978 as its benchmark (100), incorporates
responses about existing and anticipated business conditions.
   As such, it measures responses about current job openings,
satisfaction with the condition of inventories, changes in net
earnings, plans to hire and make capital outlays, expected business
conditions and expected sales.
   The lowest seasonally adjusted index since its formulation in
1974 was an 81.1 reading in the second quarter of 1980. Its highest
level was reached in the first quarter of 1984 at 108.7.
   The index, which is widely followed because of its sound
forecasting record over the years, relies on detailed, written
responses from close to 2,000 members of the federation. In the
latest survey, 1,797 responses were studied.
   The federation claims over 500,000 member firms, ranging from
extremely small enterprises such as proprietorships to companies
with sales in the hundreds of millions _ small only in relationship
to the very largest firms.
   The community it represents, says Dunkelberg, employs half the
private nonfarm work force and produces about 50 percent of the
nation's gross private product.
   Smaller companies, it is felt by some economic forecasters, are
especially sensitive to changing economic conditions.
   Studying the responses, Dunkelberg said that only 25 percent of
companies in the survey planned to raise prices, a 5-point drop
from the first quarter of 1989, ``a remarkable turnaround in
inflation pressures in the economy.''
   He saw little inflation threat in the strong demand for workers,
saying ``there is still little evidence that compensation is
responding in any substantive way to labor market tightness.''
   While labor costs are rising, he said, the gains aren't
alarming. ``Indeed, gains remain surprisingly modest,'' he said,
while conceding that a higher minimum wage could have a ripple
effect on the wage structure.
   The tightening of labor markets shown by the latest survey was
in contrast to what Dunkelberg said was a period of substantial
weakening since January. He termed the strength unexpected, and
said much of it was in the service sector.
   Little change was found in plans for capital investments. ``All
in all, no excitement, just steady spending,'' he said, but he
indicated that it might begin easing soon.
   That easing, he said, would result from companies waiting to see
just which course the economy is taking. ``So far, the signals
remain mixed, and the economy stays on an even keel.''
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Adv PMs Wednesday, Nov. 15.</NOTE>
</DOC>
