<DOCNO> AP891114-0199 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-11-14-89 1205EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>a a AM-The'90s-Poll Adv16   11-14 0711</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-The '90s-Poll, Adv 16,0730</SECOND>
<HEAD>$adv16</HEAD>
<HEAD>For Release Thurs AMs, Nov. 16, and Thereafter</HEAD>
<HEAD>Americans Upbeat on Schools, Wealth in '90s, but Fear More Pollution</HEAD>
<HEAD>With Graphic</HEAD>
<NOTE>EDITOR'S NOTE </NOTE>
<TEXT>
   This is one of a periodic series of articles,
``The '90s,'' looking ahead to the promise and peril of the
upcoming 10 years, in the environment, medicine, technology and
society.
</TEXT>
<BYLINE>By GARY LANGER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Americans foresee fewer smokers, better schools
and more cash in their wallets in the coming decade, but they
expect pollution, crime and drug abuse to worsen, a national poll
has found.
   On balance, most respondents to the Media General-Associated
Press poll expressed general optimism for the 1990s. About six in
10 expected life for others to improve, and three-quarters saw
their own lives getting better.
   Education was the brightest spot, with 58 percent expecting it
to improve in the next decade. Personal wealth also was a point of
optimism, with 56 percent expecting their family's financial
situation to improve.
   But the poll's 1,071 respondents divided about evenly on whether
the U.S. economy will improve, worsen or remain about the same. And
half expected the federal budget deficit to worsen, while just a
fifth saw it improving.
   The survey found sobering assessments on many other issues. More
than six in 10 expected pollution and crime to worsen, and almost
as many saw more AIDS, homelessness and world hunger as the year
2000 approaches.
   The environment stood out as a chief concern. Twelve percent
expected pollution to be the nation's greatest problem a decade
from now; only drug abuse was named by more, 17 percent.
   Moreover, 65 percent expected pollution to worsen in the next 10
years, and almost half said the warming of the atmosphere because
of pollution, known as the greenhouse effect, could threaten human
survival.
   Pessimism often was greatest among younger respondents, and in
many cases optimism increased with age. Fifty-two percent of those
aged 18-24 expected the United States to become involved in a war
in the 1990s; just 41 percent of their elders shared their fear.
And among the oldest group, over 64 years old, just 27 percent
expected war.
   Similarly, six in 10 in the youngest group expected drug abuse
to worsen and two-thirds of them saw acquired immune deficiency
syndrome as a growing problem, while nearer to half of the older
respondents agreed.
   One of the most widely held expectations overall was for a
Democrat to win the White House, which 72 percent called likely.
Among the least-expected developments: the demise of communism,
considered likely by just 26 percent.
   Other widely expected eventualities were cigarette smokers
shrinking to a tiny minority of the population, which 59 percent
called likely; and much greater restrictions on abortion, expected
by 56 percent.
   The poll found a lowering of some expectations in the past
decade. In a 1979 survey by the Roper Organization, 51 percent
expected the four-day work week to become common in the 1980s; when
the question was repeated in the new poll, just 41 percent held
that view for the 1990s.
   Fewer people expected new energy sources to end dependency on
oil _ 49 percent now, compared with 60 percent in 1979. And more
expected the role of nuclear power to decline _ 45 percent now,
compared with 33 percent 10 years ago.
   More also were dubious that racial and religious discrimination
could largely disappear _ 77 percent said not, compared with 66
percent in 1979. In both polls, nine in 10 doubted that poverty
would be almost eliminated.
   Among other possibilities posed for the 1990s, 37 percent said
it was likely the Republican Party would control Congress; 38
percent expected a woman to be elected president; 42 percent called
it likely U.S. astronauts will reach Mars; and 42 percent expected
cures for cancer and for AIDS.
   The poll, conducted by telephone Sept. 14-24, had a margin of
error of 3 percentage points.
   Media General Inc., a communications company based in Richmond,
Va., publishes the Richmond Times-Dispatch, the Richmond News
Leader, the Tampa (Fla.) Tribune and the Winston-Salem (N.C.)
Journal, and operates TV stations WXFL in Tampa, WCBD in
Charleston, S.C., and WJKS in Jacksonville, Fla.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Adv Thurs AMs, Nov. 16, and Thereafter</NOTE>
</DOC>
