<DOCNO> AP891114-0209 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-11-14-89 0008EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>s i BC-APN--BordersoftheHeart Adv26-1stAdd   11-14 0569</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-APN--Borders of the Heart, Adv 26-1st Add,0581</SECOND>
<HEAD>$adv26</HEAD>
<HEAD>AGENCIES AND RADIO OUT</HEAD>
<HEAD>For Release Sunday, Nov. 26</HEAD>
<HEAD>ABU TOR, Israel: rubber bullets.</HEAD>
<TEXT>
   ``Where can we hide?'' he asks, noting that the windows do not
have shutters to protect his family from stray bullets.
   Abu Saloum, a lean, intense man in his 30s, lost his radio,
color TV, videocassette player, electric fan and typewriter during
the recent curfew. The items were seized in lieu of taxes he had
refused to pay as part of a civil disobedience campaign.
   Soon after he spoke, an Israeli police van with windows screened
to protect against stone-throwing arrived on Naomi Street outside
with heavily armed police walking on either side.
   They rousted a group of teen-agers and ordered them to clear the
street of large stones apparently put up as a barricade. A reporter
saw one policeman slap an Arab teen-ager in the back of the head,
while another officer kicked a second youth.
   ``I think it is difficult to make the children understand that
we can make peace,'' says Abu Saloum, a grocer with a passion for
amateur theater. ``They see violence and get radical ideas.''
   Nisrin, his green-eyed 13-year-old daughter, says Israeli youths
in Abu Tor have become openly contemptuous. She does not go into
the Jewish area alone.
   ``They think they're superior,'' she says, adding: ``We don't
want to improve relations. We want a state.''
   Eden Green, a curly haired 17-year-old, attended three
Palestinian-Israeli encounter groups arranged by her mother, Judith.
   She says Palestinian demands seem unrealistic and extreme,
particularly those espoused by Moslem fundamentalists who argue
that Jews should live as a protected minority in an Islamic state.
   ``But I think it's important to get to know these people. If
everyone got to know the Palestinians as people, it would be harder
to use violence against them,'' she says.
   Mrs. Tavori said firebombs and other violence have destroyed the
feelings of tolerance and coexistence that used to prevail in Abu
Tor.
   ``Look and see how beautiful it is. It's been spoiled,'' she
says, gesturing from her balcony at the panoramic view that
stretches from the landmark golden cap of the Dome of the Rock
mosque in the Old City to the Judean hills and the Dead Sea beyond.
   Mrs. Tavori says she has started a diary to sort out her
confused and often conflicting reactions to her Arab neighbors
during the uprising that began in December 1987 and has taken the
lives of more than 590 Arabs and 40 Israelis.
   She recalls, for example, walking to an Arab bakery recently for
sweet knafy cake, a favorite treat before the uprising. Both she
and the owner felt uneasy.
   ``We were such good friends. But we didn't even smile at each
other,'' she says, reading from the diary.
   When she got home, she heard on the radio that an Israeli woman
and her two children burned to death on a bus in the West Bank.
``The cake stuck in my throat, and I was sorry I went.''
   But then, walking alone one day she noticed she was being
followed by an Arab man. ``He walked more quickly and I thought,
`Am I supposed to be afraid?' Then he came up and gave a flower and
said, `to a beautiful woman, a beautiful flower.'
   ``When I tell people the story, they don't believe it. Everyone
thinks I dreamed it.''
</TEXT>
