<FIRST>s a BC-APN--BotanicalGardens-List Adv26   11-14 0460</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-APN--Botanical Gardens-List, Adv 26,0473</SECOND>
<HEAD>$adv26</HEAD>
<HEAD>AGENCIES AND RADIO OUT</HEAD>
<HEAD>For Release Sunday, Nov. 26</HEAD>
<HEAD>From AP Newsfeatures</HEAD>
<HEAD>With BC-APN--Botanical Gardens</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   At a recent seminar in New York City, devotees from all over the
United States gave status reports on their efforts to build plant
conservatories to preserve or show off rare and exotic plants.
   Many of the new conservatories and renovations of existing
facilities, including the proposed $7 million Moody Gardens in
Galveston, Texas, are still in the planning stages, although some
have firm opening dates.
   Some examples:
   _The $4.1 million Olbrich Botanical Gardens in Madison, Wis., is
building a 10,000-square-foot, diamond-shaped conservatory that
will be open to the public in 1991.
   _Salt Lake City would like to have a conservatory at the State
Arboretum of Utah by 1994.
   _Chicago already has spent more than $1 million restoring its
two conservatories and will put an additional $2.1 million into the
1912 Garfield Park Conservatory and $650,000 into the 1890s Lincoln
Park Conservatory.
   _The spectacular Longwood Gardens in Longwood, Pa., once part of
the duPont estate, reopened one greenhouse last year after a
$725,000 renovation. Longwood is the showiest of any American
conservatory with more than four acres under glass. It has an
annual operating budget of $7 millioin to $8 million.
   _A new $1.8 million atrium at the Cowles Conservatory in
Minneapolis, which features art work as well as plants, has opened.
   _A $12 million renovation of the New York Botanical Garden's
Enid A. Haupt Conservatory is in the planning stages. Also in New
York, the Queens Botanical Gardens is planning a conservatory.
   _The 40,000-square-foot Phipps Conservatory in Pittsburgh was
renovated in 1987.
   _Callaway Garden's Cecil B. Day Butterfly Center in Pine
Mountain, Ga., a 8,000-square-foot conservatory costing $5.8
million and featuring a display of tropical butterflies, opened in
1988.
   _A 3,700-square-foot tropical display house, costing about a
half a million dollars, is scheduled to open March 31 at the
Norfolk, Va., Botanical Gardens.
   _A $5 million visitor's center and cactus and succulent pavilion
is planned at the Desert Botanical Gardens in Phoenix. An
additional $10 million will be raised later to build a new
administration building as well as a restaurant. The project is in
the fund-raising stage.
   _In Richmond, Va., the Lewis Ginter Botanical Garden at
Bloemendaal is beginning phase one of an ambitious 20-year program
of conservatory building that will make it the second only to
Longwood when completed. Phase one will include a display house
with a flower show 365 days a year and probably cost about $5
million. The 20-year plan calls for a $20 million outlay.
   _In Baltimore, $6.5 million is being raised for a new extension
of the Schaefer Conservatory at Druid Hills Park.
</TEXT>
