<DOCNO> AP891114-0215 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-11-14-89 0015EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>s a BC-APN--TheCourant Adv26   11-14 1138</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-APN--The Courant, Adv 26,1165</SECOND>
<HEAD>$adv26</HEAD>
<HEAD>AGENCIES AND RADIO OUT</HEAD>
<HEAD>For Release Sunday, Nov. 26</HEAD>
<HEAD>From AP Newsfeatures</HEAD>
<HEAD>(APN SUNDAY ILLUSTRATIONS: Mailed print subscribers get 3 b&amp;w photos.)
   EDITOR'S NOTE _ It's the nation's oldest continuously published newspaper,
a New England journal whose style and stance has fluctuated wildly over
its 225 years. But The Hartford Courant has endured where many others have
failed and today remains robust in a troubled industry.    ___</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By PETER VILES</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>HARTFORD, Conn. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   George Washington advertised in it,
Thomas Jefferson sued it and Mark Twain tried to buy a piece of it.
   The Hartford Courant, born in 1764 above a barbershop in what
was then a bustling river town, just celebrated its 225th birthday,
another milestone for the nation's oldest continuously published
newspaper.
   The Courant celebrated in October by opening a $15 million
addition to its main office and by cranking up the hand-operated
press that Thomas Green used to print the Courant in the late 1700s.
   The Courant was a weekly until 1837, and so cannot lay claim to
being the nation's oldest daily. That distinction belongs to The
New York Post, printed daily since 1801.
   The Courant has never won a Pulitzer Prize and has always lived
in the shadows of bigger, more acclaimed newspapers in Boston and
New York. But it has endured, outlasting 40 now-defunct Hartford
papers, and today remains a robust newspaper in a troubled industry.
   ``The fact that it has held up all these years and is still
regarded as a paper of quality is impressive,'' said Everette
Dennis, director of the Gannett Center for Media Studies in New
York. ``It's not The New York Times, but it serves its purpose.
It's a major regional newspaper.''
   With daily circulation at 225,000 and slowly climbing, the
Courant is by far the largest paper in Connecticut. It prints seven
regional editions with news from more than 70 Connecticut cities
and towns from the Massachusetts border to Long Island Sound.
   During the Revolutionary War, the Courant had _ by its own
account _ the largest circulation of any newspaper in the Colonies,
and was an influential supporter of the revolution.
   ``AMERICANS!'' the Courant blared to its readers in May 1775.
``Forever bear in mind the BATTLE of LEXINGTON! Where British
troops, unmolested and unprovoked, wantonly, and in a most inhuman
manner, fired upon and killed a number of our countrymen.''
   When the Constitution was proposed in 1787, the Courant printed
it in full as a news item. The Courant made clear its support for
the Constitution by running articles on the need for a stronger
union of the states and printing unanswered letters from the
Constitution's advocates.
   George Washington was president when he ran two ads in the
Courant in 1796. The first offered four farms for rent near his
Mount Vernon estate. The president warned he would rent only ``to
real farmers of good reputation and none others need apply.''
   During the early 1800s, the Courant, like most newspapers of the
time, adopted a bitterly partisan tone. The paper's chief target
was Jefferson, whom it saw as a godless slave owner, a tool of
France and an enemy of the Constitution.
   The Jefferson administration took notice, and indicted the
Courant for criminal libel in 1806 after the paper ran a story
strongly implying that the administration had sent 60 tons of
silver to France as a bribe.
   The Courant was vindicated six years later when the U.S. Supreme
Court dismissed the suit, ruling that English criminal common law _
the basis for the indictment _ did not apply in the United States.
   The Courant enthusiastically backed Abraham Lincoln for
president in 1860, and declared ``Victory! Victory! We've Got
'Em!'' when Lincoln won.
   But the Courant of the mid-19th century was anything but
progressive. Thomas Day, the publisher, railed against immigrants
and treated readers to large doses of his own racial and religious
bigotry.
   ``The Caucasian variety is intrinsically a better breed, of
better brain, better moral traits, better capacity every way, than
the Negro, or the Mongolian, or the Malay, or the Red American,''
he wrote.
   After the Civil War, the Courant resisted the ``new journalism''
of the day, a rambunctious style that gave readers a heavy dose of
stories on crime and personalities and relied on a relatively new
reporting technique _ the interview.
   This, the Courant wrote, was ``Ungentlemanly Journalism,''
marked by ``the vile invention of `interviewing.'''
   It was during this period of polite and principled journalism
that Mark Twain, Hartford's most celebrated writer, tried to buy
into the Courant. The offer was carefully considered and then
turned down.
   By the 1920s, the Courant's prim approach to the news had earned
it the nickname ``The Old Lady of State Street.'' A young managing
editor named Emile Gauvreau tried to change that, and for a brief
period of four years, the old lady became a flapper, heavy on
crime, sex and photographs.
   But Gauvreau's taste for the bizarre proved too much for the
staid Courant, and he was soon asked to leave. He took his talents
to the New York Evening Graphic, where he boosted circulation to
500,000 with a sensational style that earned the paper the nickname
``Porno-Graphic.''
   The Courant, meanwhile, regained its more measured voice,
although the Great Depression brought an air of quiet desperation
the paper could not ignore. The Courant published stories on ``How
to Feed Four on $9 a Week.''
   The Courant discovered its suburban readers in the postwar
years, and circulation more than doubled, from 52,000 in 1946 to
130,000 in 1964. When the paper turned 200 in 1964, it already had
13 news bureaus crowded into the small state and more than 100
correspondents phoning in local news.
   In 1965, the Courant overtook The Hartford Times in daily
circulation, and within 11 years the Times, once the city's
dominant paper, was dead. The Courant's ascendancy made the paper
an attractive property, and in 1979 the Los Angeles-based Times
Mirror Co. paid $105 million for the Courant, ending 215 years of
local ownership.
   The first years of Times Mirror management were somewhat rocky.
The paper's new emphasis on regional stories, feature writing and
investigative projects clashed with a long tradition of exhaustive
local coverage.
   In Hartford, community activists demonstrated outside the
newspaper, charging that the Courant had abandoned the city. Editor
Mark Murphy was hanged in effigy. Reporter Andrew Kreig left the
paper and wrote ``Spiked,'' a book accusing the Courant's new
management of deceiving the papers' readers in pursuit of a
Pulitzer Prize.
   Under current editor and publisher Michael J. Davies, the
Courant has returned to an emphasis on local news and has opened a
turf war against five suburban dailies by aggressively courting
local advertisers in the cities and towns surrounding Hartford.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>END ADV</NOTE>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP891114-0216 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-11-14-89 0016EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>s a BC-APN--DownsChildren Adv26   11-14 0870</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-APN--Downs Children, Adv 26,0901</SECOND>
<HEAD>$adv26</HEAD>
<HEAD>AGENCIES AND RADIO OUT</HEAD>
<HEAD>For Release Sunday, Nov. 26</HEAD>
<HEAD>From AP Newsfeatures</HEAD>
<HEAD>(APN SUNDAY ILLUSTRATIONS: Mailed print subscribers get 1 b&amp;w photo.)
   EDITOR'S NOTE _ A new television series, ``Life Goes On,'' deals with
the problems facing a youth with Down's syndrome attempting to attend a
high school with normal kids. It's a subject close to the heart of a Miami
couple who two years ago established a foundation to help children with
the disorder. Putting the children into the mainstream, they have learned,
is fraught with difficulty.    ___</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By KIM S. MARTIN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MIAMI (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Like millions of other children, 3-year-old Tiffany
Geraldi went off to begin preschool this fall. But she was soon
sent home and told not to return.
   Tiffany was excluded because she has Down's syndrome. The first
attempt at ``mainstreaming'' her with a typical preschool class had
proved unsuccessful.
   Tiffany's adoptive parents, Dr. Michael Geraldi and his wife,
Camille, were upset, but not defeated.
   They have adopted seven children with Down's, have pending
adoptions for six others and have legal guardianship of another, a
grand total of 14. They also have two children of their own.
   The Geraldis began the ``Up With Down Syndrome'' foundation in
1987 and devoted it to training, loving and caring for children
with Down's syndrome. They also counsel the natural parents of the
children.
   In addition, they provide day care for parents of other children
with the problem and teach adults with Down's how to develop better
job skills and become more independent. All of these services are
free.
   Most of the children the Geraldis have adopted, who range in age
from 2 months to 3 years, have serious medical problems.
   ``When you nourish and love them, something happens. Their
health improves dramatically,'' Ms. Geraldi says.
   The problems can range from digestive disorders to serious heart
defects. One of their children, 1-year-old Jo-layne, already has
undergone two open heart surgeries and seven other major operations.
   Down's syndrome is a genetic defect resulting from a child
having one extra chromosome. This extra chromosome can cause the
child to be born with a host of physical and mental problems.
   Symptoms can include a depressed nose, clubfeet, a raised upper
lip, wide spacing between fingers and toes and decreased mental
capacity.
   Parents have been counseled in the past to put their child in an
institution because of mental retardation, but Ms. Geraldi says
current research shows that a loving home environment allows them
to function at a higher level.
   The foundation's two group homes in the Miami suburb of Kendall
are designed to provide that support, she says.
   Ms. Geraldi, a nurse with a special education degree, says she
developed a special sympathy for children with Down's syndrome at a
very young age.
   When she was 5 years old, she helped her father, who volunteered
at a nursing home for the retarded.
   While she was working as a nurse at Miami Children's Hospital,
she met her husband and found they shared ``a love for children
that were not perfect and normal.''
   ``He was as sensitive as I was to the children,'' she says.
   Geraldi, a pediatrician, and his wife attempted to adopt a
Down's baby from various agencies, including the Department of
Health and Rehabilitative Services, but never heard from any of
them. In the meantime, they had their own two children, Renae, 12,
and Jaclyn, 11.
   But in 1986 they received a call about a very sick baby with
Down's in Mississippi who was 5 weeks old and weighed only four
pounds. They picked her up in Mississippi and, after some legal red
tape, they adopted the child, Darlene, now a healthy 3-year-old.
   The foundation is supported solely by donations and her
husband's salary, she says.
   Because of his salary, they don't qualify for any kind of state
aid, she says.
   They have spent more than $500,000 so far in medical bills and
hope to become eligible for Medicaid.
   Ms. Geraldi says that fears of Down's children that persisted
until recent years were unfounded, but many people are still uneasy
around children with the disorder.
   ``I was in the grocery store with some of the kids and when
people saw us in an aisle, they would turn and walk away,'' she
says.
   A new television series is helping change that.
   ``Life Goes On,'' a critically acclaimed weekly series, is the
story of an 18-year-old boy attempting to go to a regular high
school with normal kids.
   This experiment is known as mainstreaming and tries to integrate
Down's sufferers into normal environments.
   But Ms. Geraldi says, ``I don't think the program is very
realistic.'' She says the boy on the TV program is exceptionally
functional for someone with Down's syndrome and has less of the
physical characteristics.
   However, she says, the show does portray the difficulties of
mainstreaming.
   The children encounter ridicule from classmates and lessons from
teachers untrained in special education.
   Tiffany's teacher did not know how to discipline her when she
refused to listen. Also, other parents objected to her presence in
the class.
   ``After all I've seen, I still cried when Tiffany was sent
home,'' Ms. Geraldi says.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>END ADV</NOTE>
