<HEAD>For Release Anytime</HEAD>
<HEAD>AP WEEKEND ENTERTAINMENT AND ARTS</HEAD>
<HEAD>On Show: Gallery and Museum Shows and Exhibits</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   Montana-born E. McKnight Kauffer spent most of his life in
England creating colorful and impelling posters for the London
Underground Railway.
   His romantic landscapes early in the century, ``In Watford'' and
``Oxhey Woods,'' seduced Londoners to the British countryside. In
the 1920s, he drew abstract designs for retail stores. He also
designed museum posters, brochures and tickets for the Orient Line
and did stage and costume design.
   Works by Kauffer (1890-1954) will be on display at the
Cooper-Hewitt Museum, the Smithsonian Institution's National Museum
of Design in New York.
   ``E. McKnight Kauffer: Graphic Art and Theater Design'' will
feature more than 100 posters, advertisements, book illustrations
and theater designs from Nov. 21 through April 1.
   Here is a list of other shows at some galleries and museums in
the United States:
</TEXT>
<BYLINE>ATLANTA</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   
   High Museum of Art:
   ``Art in Berlin _ 1815-1989.'' Through Jan. 14.
   ``Land of Deepest Shade: Photographs of the South by John
McWilliams.'' Through Jan. 7.
</TEXT>
