<FILEID>AP-NR-11-14-89 0119EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r f PM-BusinessHighlights     11-14 0815</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Business Highlights,0854</SECOND>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Supreme Court has cleared the way for the
partial merger of Detroit's two daily newspapers in its first
ruling on a 1970 law aimed at saving failing newspapers.
   The high court's 4-4 split Monday affirmed a lower court ruling
that former Attorney General Edwin Meese III acted reasonably last
year when he approved plans by the Detroit Free Press and The
Detroit News to merge their business, production and advertising
staffs but maintain editorial independence.
   The federal Newspaper Preservation Act of 1970 authorizes the
attorney general to give financially failing newspapers an
exemption from federal antitrust laws.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>ALEXANDRIA, Va. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Boeing Co. has pleaded guilty to two
felony charges of illegally obtaining secret Pentagon budget
documents and agreed to pay more than $5.2 million in fines and
restitution.
   U.S. District Judge T.S. Ellis III on Monday also ordered
Boeing's board chairman and chief executive officer, Frank Shrontz,
to write a letter expressing remorse and acceptance of corporate
responsibility for the crime.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>STAMFORD, Conn. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Great Northern Nekoosa Corp. rejected
Georgia-Pacific Corp.'s $3.13 billion takeover offer as financially
disastrous for both papermaking companies, but Georgia-Pacific said
it would continue pursuing a merger.
   Great Northern's directors, which voted Sunday to reject the
bid, said Monday the $58-per-share offer was too low and that the
combination would violate antitrust law.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>STAMFORD, Conn. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   ABB Asea Brown Boveri Ltd., the world's
largest electrical equipment manufacturer, will buy Combustion
Engineering Inc. for $1.6 billion, the companies announced.
   ABB will buy all outstanding shares for $40 per share in cash,
and will also assume $230 million in long-term debt on Combustion
Engineering's books. ABB said the offer will not require financing.
The announcement was made Monday.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   NYNEX Corp. and its two unions have reached
agreement on the framework of a new contract that could end a
bitter 100-day strike at the telephone company, the president of
one of the unions said.
   NYNEX, through its subsidiaries New York Telephone and New
England Telephone, provides phone service in most of the Northeast.
   The agreement, announced Monday, affects the Communications
Workers of America, representing 40,000 NYNEX workers, and the
International Brotherhood of Electrical Workers, which bargains for
an additional 20,000 employees.
</TEXT>
