<TEXT>
   Cosmetics company Avon Products Inc. is seeking
to repel unwanted takeover advances from an alliance of powerful
investors including oil heir Gordon P. Getty, a senior Mary Kay
Corp. executive and the Fisher real estate family of New York.
   A limited partnership called Chartwell Associates, revealing its
intentions after it became known Friday that the group had bought a
stake in Avon, said Monday it may propose a merger with Avon or one
of its affiliates.
   In a summary of a document filed with the Securities and
Exchange Commission, Chartwell Associates LP disclosed it owns 6.9
percent of Avon's common stock and intends to purchase additional
shares.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The former president of the Beech-Nut Nutrition
Corp. has admitted he knowingly sold sugar water to consumers who
believed they were buying pure apple juice for their babies.
   Niels L. Hoyvald, 56, of New Lebanon, N.J., pleaded guilty
Monday in U.S. District Court in Brooklyn to 10 felony counts of
violating the federal Food, Drug and Cosmetic Act.
   Under terms of a plea agreement, U.S. District Judge Thomas C.
Platt fined Hoyvald $100,000 and sentenced him to five years
probation and six consecutive months of full-time community service.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>ATLANTIC CITY, N.J. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Entertainer Merv Griffin has offered
Resorts International Inc. bondholders 78 percent of the casino's
equity in a restructuring plan to reduce the company's nearly $1
billion debt.
   Bondholders on Sunday filed suit in Camden to place Resorts in
involuntary bankruptcy under Chapter 11 of the bankruptcy code,
said Alison MacDonald, a New York-based spokeswoman for Resorts.
   Resorts said Monday it had reached agreement in principle with
``a number of substantial holders'' of its debt about a
recapitalization plan.
</TEXT>
