<FIRST>r f PM-TreasuryAuctions     11-14 0325</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Treasury Auctions,0336</SECOND>
<HEAD>Yields Fall on 10-Year Treasury Notes, Rise on Short-Term Bills</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Yields on 10-year Treasury notes fell in
Monday's auction to the lowest level in 33 months while yields on
short-term securities rose.
   The average yield for the 10-year notes was 7.94 percent, down
from 8.03 percent at the last auction on Aug. 9. The auction was
part of the government's quarterly refunding postponed last week by
Congress' delay in raising the debt limit.
   It was the lowest rate since 10-year notes averaged 7.25 percent
on Feb. 4, 1987. The notes will carry a coupon interest rate of 7~
percent with each $10,000 in face value selling for $9,955.70.
   A total of $10 billion in notes was sold out of bids totaling
$22.8 billion.
   The Treasury will complete its refunding with the auction on
Tuesday of $10 billion in 30-year bonds. It sold $10 billion in
three-year notes last Thursday and $10 billion in 36-day cash
management bills last Friday.
   In the Treasury's regular weekly auction, interest rates on
short-term securities rose to their highest level in two weeks.
   The Treasury Department sold $8 billion in three-month bills at
an average discount rate of 7.68 percent, up from 7.67 percent last
week. Another $8 billion was sold in six-month bills at an average
discount rate of 7.51 percent, up from 7.49 percent last week.
   The rates were the highest since Oct. 30 when three-month bills
sold for 7.78 percent and six-month bills averaged 7.62 percent.
   The new discount rates understate the actual return to investors
_ 7.94 percent for three-month bills with a $10,000 bill selling
for $9,805.90 and 7.92 percent for a six-month bill selling for
$9,620.30.
   In a separate report, the Federal Reserve said Monday that the
average yield for one-year Treasury bills, the most popular index
for making changes in adjustable rate mortgages, fell to 7.87
percent last week, down from 7.89 percent the previous week.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
