<FILEID>AP-NR-11-14-89 0128EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r f PM-BusinessEducation     11-14 0421</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Business Education,0432</SECOND>
<HEAD>Business, Education, Public Policy Leaders Form Foundation</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By TAMARA HENRY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Education Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Labor, education and business leaders have
joined to launch a foundation linking the classroom with the
workplace to stimulate high school students' interest in business.
   The National Academy Foundation offers a two-year program for
high school juniors and seniors with a special curriculum designed
by educators in consultation with industry experts. Each student is
offered a paid, on-the-job summer internship with a business.
   The foundation is headed by former National Urban League
President Vernon E. Jordan Jr. and former Labor Secretary William
E. Brock. It is modeled after the successful Academy of Finance,
pioneered in 1982 by American Express Co. and its Shearson Lehman
Hutton brokerage division in New York City.
   Warning of an employment crisis within two to three years, Brock
said Monday that ``the only possible way we can avoid that is by
having a recession so deep that we would be desperately worried
about this country.
   ``We are going to run short of people. We're going to run short
of people with skills and there is no immediate response that could
be made that will stop us from running into that problem,'' he
said, pointing to the end of the ``baby boom era'' in five years,
when there will be an estimated 7 million fewer people in their
twenties than there are now.
   Along with the manpower shortage, Brock said ``our children are
being less well educated than we were. That's insane. It's the
first time in 200 years that's been true and it's true today.''
   Brock said the academy ``begins to address that problem.'' He
said there are 35 Academy of Finance programs in 17 cities and four
Academies of Travel and Tourism in two cities. More than 170
businesses have provided internships for academy students.
   More than 2,200 students are enrolled in academy programs,
including 60 percent minorities. Most of the students are juniors
and seniors, but high school freshmen and sophomores are offered
preparatory courses to qualify them for the academy by the junior
year.
   Academy courses are in addition to the regular high school
curriculum. For example, Academy of Finance students take such
courses as international finance, security operations and financial
planning. Travel and tourism classes include destination geography
and tourism computer applications.
   Brock said school districts and school boards must invite the
academy to their area and guarantee that financing for the program
will continue once business start-up money of about $50,000 ends.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP891114-0227 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-11-14-89 0132EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r f PM-AFL-CIOConvention Bjt   11-14 0470</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-AFL-CIO Convention, Bjt,0480</SECOND>
<HEAD>Labor Convention a Rowdy Show of Solidarity</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: Walesa speech scheduled 11:45 a.m. EST; lead planned. Also moving
on general news wires.</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto WX7</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOHN KING</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Labor Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The AFL-CIO is staging a rowdy show of labor
solidarity and serving notice that its unions plan to adopt a more
aggressive stance in the coming years.
   The 14.1 million-member federation opened its 18th biennial
constitutional convention Monday, beginning with a sing-along to
promote labor unity and ending by passing a resolution pledging
support for union workers involved in several major strikes.
   The most celebrated event of the week-long convention comes
today when Solidarity leader Lech Walesa appears to thank the
AFL-CIO for its support of the Polish trade union and accept the
federation's highest honor, the George Meany Human Rights Award.
   On Monday, the 800 delegates warmly welcomed the United Mine
Workers back under labor's umbrella and enjoyed a procession by
hundreds of workers involved in the strikes, one of which may soon
be over.
   Communications Workers of America President Morton Bahr told the
gathering that his union and the International Brotherhood of
Electrical Workers have reached a tentative company-wide settlement
with NYNEX Corp. and hope to resolve local issues within a week.
The two unions represent 60,000 workers who have been on strike for
15 weeks against NYNEX, which provides phone service in most of the
Northeast.
   NYNEX strikers joined their counterparts at Boeing, Pittston
Coal and Eastern Airlines in a march through the convention hall,
where delegates spent the day promoting labor solidarity and
promising to end the 1980s, a tough decade for labor, on a positive
and militant note.
   UMW President Richard Trumka, addressing the convention a month
after the Mine Workers ended 40 years of independence from the
federation, sounded a warning that anti-union employers ``who
looked upon the 1980s with great fondness are about to have their
visions shattered in the 1990s because we will never be separated
again.''
   Federation President Lane Kirkland, who first took office 10
years ago at the same hotel where the delegates are gathering this
year, said the success of the labor movement in Poland and other
nations in promoting democracy should serve as a lesson to those in
this country who doubt the need for unions.
   ``Is it not reasonable to hope, at least, that American labor's
movement toward democracy in the world will provide a new lesson
for Americans regarding the role of trade unions in promoting and
preserving freedom in our country?'' Kirkland asked.
   The delegates also received praise from Labor Secretary
Elizabeth Dole, who acknowledged the numerous policy differences
between labor and the Bush administration but added, ``The tireless
efforts of America's unions have resulted in protection for all
workers, regardless of whether they are union members.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
