<FIRST>u f PM-Dollar-Gold     11-14 0268</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Dollar-Gold,0281</SECOND>
<HEAD>Dollar Eases, Gold Rises Slightly</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The dollar eased against most major foreign
currencies in early European trading today. Gold prices were little
changed.
   Currency dealers said the dollar was stuck in a narrow range in
quiet trading ahead of the release later today of October retail
sales figures.
   ``The dollar is standing still ahead of the U.S. economic
data,'' said one trader in Milan, Italy.
   October industrial production and capacity utilization figures
were also due to be released later in the day, followed by trade
figures on Thursday.
   In Tokyo, where trading ends before Europe's business day
begins, the dollar rose 0.25 yen to a closing 143.80 yen. Later, in
London, it was quoted at 143.78 yen.
   Other dollar rates at midmorning compared with late Monday's
rates, included: 1.8566 West German marks, down from 1.8615; 1.6385
Swiss francs, down from 1.6410; 6.3015 French francs, down from
6.3140; 2.0948 Dutch guilders, down from 2.1030; 1,358.50 Italian
lire, down from 1,360.50; 1.1697 Canadian dollars, up from 1.1677.
   In London, the dollar fell slightly against the British pound.
It cost $1.5825 to buy one pound, compared with $1.5805 late Monday.
   Gold opened in London at a bid price of $391.75 a troy ounce,
compared with late Monday's $391.25. At midmorning, the city's five
major bullion dealers fixed a recommended price of $391.75.
   In Zurich, the bid price was $391.20, up from $390 late Monday.
   Earlier, in Hong Kong, gold rose $4.34 to close at a bid $391.51.
   Silver was quoted in London at a bid price of $5.34 a troy
ounce, down from Monday's $5.31.
</TEXT>
