<FILEID>AP-NR-11-14-89 0757EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r f PM-FarmScene     11-14 0514</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Farm Scene,0536</SECOND>
<HEAD>Bill May Aid Earthquake-Damaged Ag Business</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DIANE DUSTON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Agricultural businesses damaged by last
month's California earthquake may get aid under the same program
providing assistance to drought-affected farmers.
   The House approved a bill on a voice vote Monday amending the
Federal Disaster Assistance Act of 1989 to include speciality
growers and processors hit by the earthquake.
   Rep. Leon Panetta, D-Calif., sponsor of the bill that goes to
the Senate, said many agriculture businesses ``slip through the
safety net that our nation's disaster programs are supposed to
provide.''
   The earthquake that rocked Northern California damaged fruit and
ornamental trees, caused food processing plants to shut down in
mid-harvest and disrupted work at wineries.
   The legislation provides reimbursement of 65 percent of the cost
of replanting trees and seedlings. It also guarantees loans to
agricultural businesses, increasing from $200 million to $300
million the amount that may be loaned through the program.
</TEXT>
<HEAD>___</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The near destruction of 7,007 pounds of cooked
roast beef led the House to pass legislation allowing courts that
confiscate wholesome meat to donate it to charity.
   ``I introduced the bill to fill a void in the existing law,''
said Rep. Lawrence Smith, D-Fla. whose measure was approved on
voice vote Monday. The bill goes to the Senate.
   It stems from a Miami case known as U.S. vs. 7,007 Pounds of
Cooked Roast Beef, involving imported meat confiscated because it
was fraudulently labeled ``USDA choice.''
   Though inspected by a foreign agency trusted by the federal
government, it had not been inspected by the U.S. Department of
Agriculture and could not be sold with a fraudulent USDA stamp.
   When the importer relinquished the meat and the suggestion was
made that it be given to the needy, the federal court found that no
provision for such action existed in the law.
   Smith said the judge eventually got the meat to a food bank for
the poor through creative interpretation of the law.
   ``We fed 35,000 people with this meat,'' Smith said.
   His bill legalizes donation to charity as a means of disposing
of confiscated meat.
   ``This legislation costs the American taxpayer no money and
makes a significant contribution to fighting hunger in this
country,'' he said.
</TEXT>
<HEAD>___</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A study of the effects of wildfires on timber
supplies, fish and wildlife habitats, recreation and ecosystems
would be conducted under a bill passed by the House.
   The legislation, approved by voice vote Monday, establishes a
25-member National Commission on Wildlife Disasters to study lands
under jurisdiction of the National Parks Service, National Forest
Services and Bureau of Land Management.
   Under the bill, the Agriculture Department would have six months
after enactment to tell Congress what the forests damaged by fire
need to be rehabilitated.
   The bill also requires the Agriculture and Interior departments
to offer annual training programs to certify volunteer fire
fighters to fight forest fires.
   The bill would cost an estimated $250,000 over two years, but
allows for donations that could reduce the amount from the federal
treasury.
</TEXT>
