<FIRST>u f PM-RetailSales 1stLd-Writethru f0039 11-14 0490</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Retail Sales, 1st Ld-Writethru, f0039,0504</SECOND>
<HEAD>Auto Market Holds Back October Retail Sales</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: INSERTS after 4th graf, bgng, The October, 1 graf to update
with Fed reports; SUBS 2nd graf, bgng, The Commerce, to reflect adjustment
in August sales figure to 0.9 percent.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOHN D. McCLAIN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Retail sales, held back by a sluggish
automobile market, fell 1 percent in October for their first
decline in eight months, the government reported today.
   The Commerce Department said overall sales dropped to a
seasonally adjusted $144.5 billion last month after rising 0.9
percent in August and 0.7 percent in September.
   The last time retail sales fell was in February, when they
dropped 0.4 percent. They were unchanged in June.
   The October decline was the largest since a 6.7 percent drop in
January 1987.
   In other October reports, the Federal Reserve Board said that
industrial production fell 0.7 percent, due in part to the effects
of the California earthquake and a strike in the aircraft industry.
The operating rate for factories, mines and utilities fell 0.8
percentage points to 82.8 percent.
   Retail sales account for about one-third of the nation's
economic activity and are watched as a sign of the extent to which
the Federal Reserve's policy of fighting inflation by tightening
credit is slowing the economy.
   Auto sales, lacking major incentive programs during the month,
plunged 5.1 percent in October. Car sales, which represent about 20
percent of retail total, had been propped up by incentives for much
of the year and rose 0.5 percent in September and 2.2 percent in
August.
   The October decline was the largest since auto sales fell 26.5
percent in January 1987.
   Excluding the automobile category, retail sales edged up 0.2
percent.
   Sales of durable goods _ items expected to last at least three
years _ fell 2.7 percent, their steepest fall since a 2.8 percent
decline in October 1987. Durable sales were flat in September after
gaining 2 percent in August.
   The durable goods market has been particularly hit by the Fed's
interest-rate policies because sales often are financed by loans.
   Sales of building materials rose 0.9 percent after falling 1.3
percent in September and advancing 1.7 percent in August. Furniture
and other home furnishing sales edged up 0.3 percent following a
0.6 percent drop in September and a 1.6 percent gain in August.
   Sales of nondurable goods edged up 0.1 percent, following a 1.1
percent gain in September and a 0.1 percent decline in August.
   Nondurable categories showing increases were department stores,
up 0.3 percent; grocery stores, 1 percent; apparel, 0.2 percent;
and drug stores, 1 percent.
   Nondurable categories posting declines were gasoline stations,
down 0.9 percent, and restaurants and bars, off 0.2 percent.
   For the three months from August through October, overall retail
sales were up 6.3 percent. Sales for the first 10 months of 1989
were up 6 percent over the same period of 1988.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
