<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Stock prices pushed ahead this morning as hopes
persisted that the Federal Reserve Board will pursue a more
generous credit policy to spur economic growth.
   The Dow Jones average of 30 industrials rose 4.31 to 2,630.74 by
10 a.m. on Wall Street.
   Advancing issues outpaced declines on the New York Stock
Exchange with 590 up, 393 down and 516 unchanged.
   Volume on the Big Board came to 20.37 million shares after the
first 30 minutes of trading.
   The NYSE's composite index of all its listed common stocks rose
0.39 to 188.61.
   Market watchers say stocks got a lift from several reports
released before trading began today that furnished fresh evidence
of an economic slowdown.
   However, analysts said the statistics didn't paint a completely
clear picture because they were influenced by special circumstances.
   Retail sales dropped 1 percent in October, the first decline
since February. The Commerce Department said a slumping automobile
market depressed total retail sales.
   Separately, the Fed reported industrial production fell 0.7
percent in October. A strike in the aircraft industry and the
impact of the California earthquake crimped overall output.
   Traders have been hoping that the central bank will decide the
sluggish economy needs the stimulation that lower interest rates
would provide.
   In the early going, Central Illinois Public Service led the Big
Board's list of actively traded issue and gained [ to 23}.
   On Monday the Dow Jones industrial average eked out a 0.82 gain
to 2,626.43.
   Advancing issues outnumbered declines by about 6 to 5 on the
NYSE, with 806 up, 661 down and 479 unchanged.
   Big Board volume totaled 140.75 million shares, against 131.80
million in the previous session.
