<SECOND>PM-Biltmore Sale,0219</SECOND>
<HEAD>Biltmore Hotel Reportedly Sold to Japanese for $219 Million</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LOS ANGELES (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Japanese are adding to their U.S. real
estate portfolio the 66-year-old Biltmore Hotel, where the Oscar
was dreamed up, it was reported today.
   T.A.T Los Angeles Ltd., which is made up of two Japanese firms,
will pay Biltmore Partners $219 million for the recently renovated,
700-room hotel and a 24-story office tower opened two years ago,
the Los Angeles Times said, citing unidentified sources.
   The Biltmore was erected by local businessmen in 1923 for $10
million. In 1927, the Academy of Motion Picture Arts &amp; Sciences
gathered there for a banquent credited with brainstorming the
Academy Award.
   Foreign ownership of U.S. real estate gained renewed national
attention earlier this month with the purchase by Japanese
investors of a majority stake in Rockefeller Group, which owns
Rockefeller Center in New York City.
   The newspaper did not identify the Japanese firms that own
T.A.T. Los Angeles.
   Biltmore Partners bought the aging hotel in 1984 for $75 million
and spent $200 million on improvements, including $40 million for
the office tower.
   The hotel has since ``turned from a loser to a winner,'' said
Bruce Baltin, a partner in an accounting firm that specializes in
hotel consulting.
</TEXT>
