<SECOND>PM-Great Northern, 1st Ld-Writethru, f0010,0596</SECOND>
<HEAD>Great Northern Answers Georgia Pacific Antitakeover Challenge In
Court</HEAD>
<HEAD>EDS: This stands for f0065, which should have been a first lead-writethru;
LEADS with 6 grafs to UPDATE with Great Northern responding to Georgia-Pacific's
antitakeover claims; edits throughout to tighten</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JILL ARABAS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>STAMFORD, Conn. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Georgia-Pacific Corp.'s attempt to buy
Great Northern Nekoosa Corp. shifted back to federal court in
Maine, where Great Northern today responded to lawsuits challenging
regulations that make a takeover difficult legally and financially.
   Great Northern, denying that anti-takeover provisions of its
by-laws were designed to entrench management at shareholder
expense, said it was ironic that Georgia-Pacific itself has a
shareholder rights plan and supermajority voting rules similar to
the ones it is challenging in court.
   ``The directors of corporations which take such steps _ the
directors of Great Northern no less than the directors of
Georgia-Pacific _ act lawfully and responsibly when they take steps
of this nature that are reasonably calculated to promote the best
interests of the company and its shareholders in the context of a
proposed takeover,'' the Great Northern response said.
   Great Northern, which is headquartered in Connecticut but
incorporated in Maine, filed the papers in U.S. District Court in
Portland, Maine.
   Great Northern, a Norwalk, Conn.-based paper products company,
on Monday rejected Georgia-Pacific's $3.13 billion takeover bid,
saying it was too low and would be financially disastrous for both
companies.
   Great Northern also filed an antitrust suit against
Georgia-Pacific in Bridgeport, Conn.
   Georgia-Pacific, a forest products company based in Atlanta,
harshly criticized Great Northern's directors for voting Sunday to
reject the $58-a-share bid made Oct. 30.
   T. Marshall Hahn Jr., Georgia-Pacific's chairman, challenged the
antitrust allegations, saying the offer represented a 50 percent
premium above the market price of the stock before takeover
speculation drove up prices.
   Great Northern's stock closed down 75 cents Monday at $61.37{ a
share on the New York Stock Exchange. Georgia Pacific shares fell
25 cents to $46.37{.
   ``The board has put forth specious arguments in order to reject
a legitimate and negotiable proposal without offering any
alternative that meets its responsibilities to shareholders or the
company's future,'' Hahn said in a statement.
   He said the company would continue to try to meet with the board
and management, and ``pursue all necessary courses of action to
successfully realize the best interests of all concerned.''
   But Great Northern Chairman William R. Laidig said the companies
were not talking.
   ``Georgia-Pacific doesn't talk to us except through the courts
at this stage of the game,'' he said, referring to both the
antitrust suit in Connecticut and the takeover suit in Maine, where
Great Northern is incorporated.
   Great Northern, which had sales of $3.6 billion last year, makes
paper products, lumber and plywood at mills and factories in six
states. Georgia-Pacific had $9.5 billion in sales from paper,
forest products and building materials.
   Georgia-Pacific proposed buying 54 million outstanding shares of
Great Northern stock in a deal that would cost $4.5 billion,
including refinancing, fees and expenses.
   The paper industry is heading for a downturn after three strong
years, as overcapacity from expansion puts pressure on paper prices.
   Hahn said financing the acquisition would require no layoffs or
sales of assets, and would allow the company to continue spending
on capital projects.
   But Laidig said the directors believed Great Northern was solid
financially and well situated to stand alone and pursue its
long-term business agenda, which includes expansion.
</TEXT>
