<HEAD>UAL Board Authorizes Financial Adviser to Search for Alternative
to Takeover</HEAD>
<HEAD>EDS: SUBS 5th graf to CORRECT Oliver's first name to Augustus sted
August; picks up 6th graf pvs bg'ng, ``We never ...</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Directors of UAL Corp. have instructed their
financial adviser to explore alternatives to an investor group's
attempt to dump the board and take control of the airline company.
   Condor Partners presented UAL, the parent of United Airlines,
with the necessary documents Monday to gain access to the company's
list of stockholders to begin its solicitation of shareowners.
   After a meeting later in the day, the board issued a statement
saying it had authorized its financial adviser, First Boston Corp.,
to ``explore potential transactions with third parties, including
actively determining available alternative'' deals such as employee
ownership or recapitalization.
   The board said it had not received an offer from Condor or any
third party.
   But Augustus Oliver, one of Condor's three general partners,
said the board has misrepresented his group's position.
   ``We never said we were going to put forth a proposal until
being elected to the board,'' Oliver said. ``We feel that we need
to be on the board to be in a position to act on behalf of the
company.''
   Condor was formed as a takeover vehicle by Coniston Partners of
New York, which announced Nov. 3 that it had acquired 9.7 percent
of UAL.
   Coniston's immediate objective is to reduce UAL's board from 16
members to five, three of whom would be Coniston's principals.
   The other two are current board members Stephen Wolf, UAL's
chairman, president and chief executive officer, and Frank Olson.
But the company said Monday both have indicated they're not
interested in serving on a board controlled by Coniston.
   UAL's shares closed Monday at $193.25, up $3.75 in consolidated
New York Stock Exchange trading.
   It was one month ago, on Oct. 13, that a pilot-management effort
to buy the company for $300 a share collapsed for lack of financing.
   Analysts say speculators want to see UAL sold or recapitalized
quickly to minimize their losses from that setback.
   ``If I were on the board, I would assume that there are
sufficient shares held by accounts sympathetic to Coniston that
would result in a majority vote against the board,'' said Samuel
Buttrick, an analyst with Kidder Peabody &amp; Co. in New York.
   Officials of the Air Line Pilots Association chapter at United
met last week with Coniston and financier Saul Steinberg, a friend
of Wolf who is seeking government permission to buy more than 15
percent of UAL.
   Pilots said they have discussed a revised bid with UAL
management, but they hinted last week that they might resume a work
slowdown unless the UAL board recommits in the next two weeks to
majority employee ownership.
   United's Machinists union employees, who opposed the failed
buyout bid, also met last week with Coniston. They say they won't
support any highly leveraged deal that could threaten the airline's
viability or that would involve Wolf.
</TEXT>
