<FIRST>r f BC-IBM-DataStorage     11-14 0268</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-IBM-Data Storage,0277</SECOND>
<HEAD>IBM Announces Data-Storage Device; Reveals Source of Delay</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By PETER COY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   International Business Machines Corp. announced
a long-delayed set of data-storage devices on Tuesday and revealed
that the expensive delay was caused by internal problems, not a
supplier.
   The delay from the original July announcement date contributed
to a 30 percent drop in the computer giant's third-quarter
earnings. Disk drives for storing data from mainframe computers
account for about a tenth of IBM's roughly $60 billion in annual
revenue.
   Some analysts had speculated that IBM's trouble came from a
flawed part from an outside supplier. But IBM said it was a
chemistry problem that caused magnetic particles from a 10-inch
platter to cling to a read-write head, a microscopic version of the
common problem of dirty heads on a tape recorder.
   IBM solved the problem by using a different chemistry for the
thin ``raspberry jam'' layer of material that covers the magnetic
particles on the platter, according to Paul Low, president of the
General Products Division.
   The new chemistry completely solved the problem and the new 3390
disk drives are the most reliable in the industry, he said.
   The new drives can do three times the work in one-third the
floor space of models introduced just two years ago, IBM said.
   IBM said the disk drives will be shipped beginning Dec. 1 and
that the company expects to increase production enough to meet
customer demand by the April-June quarter of next year.
   IBM earned $877 million in the third quarter, down from $1.25
billion a year earlier.
</TEXT>
