<FIRST>r f PM-Earns-Mack     11-14 0416</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Earns-Mack,0428</SECOND>
<HEAD>Mack Reports $87.5 Million Loss for Third Quarter</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: Meck in 2nd graf is cq.</HEAD>
<DATELINE>ALLENTOWN, Pa. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Mack Trucks Inc. today reported a
third-quarter loss of $87.5 million, as sales in the heavy-duty
truck market continued to soften.
   Walter C. Meck, executive vice president of finance and chief
financial officer, said Mack expects losses to continue through the
fourth quarter and possibly into 1990.
   The third-quarter loss, at $2.94 per share, came on sales of
$367.4 million. In the same period a year ago, Mack earned $2.7
million, or 9 cents a share, on $501 million in revenue.
   For the first nine months of 1989, Mack reported a loss of
$105.9 million, or $3.57 a share, compared with a net profit of $18
million, or 61 cents a share, in the same 1988 period. Revenue
totaled $1.4 billion, down from $1.6 billion a year earlier.
   Mack officials said recent losses were due to a downturn in the
heavy-duty truck market, problems with introducing new products,
and the high costs of liquidating used vehicles and warranties. The
number of Mack-produced heavy-duty vehicles sold in the third
quarter was 34 percent lower than in the same period a year ago,
the company said.
   Mack's new chairman and chief executive officer, Ralph E. Reins,
said the company was facing one of the most difficult periods in
the company's 89-year history.
   ``Mack has taken a number of actions during recent months to
eliminate expenses, cut back on capital expenditures and reduce
inventory levels,'' Reins said. ``However, it is clear that further
actions are needed to improve Mack's competitiveness. A new Mack
will emerge from this effort, a leaner company, a tougher
competitor.''
   In August alone, the company announced more than 600 layoffs at
plants in Waynesboro, S.C., Hagerstown, Md., and Allentown, Pa.,
according to Mack spokesman James Santanasto. He said he did not
know the exact number of layoffs, but said the company's workforce
would be reduced by 21 percent in the last six months of 1989.
   Mack's former chairman, John B. Curcio, resigned in October as
the company announced it expected to lose about $50 million in the
third quarter. Curcio lost the position of president to Reins in
June when the company announced expected second-quarter losses, and
the chief executive position to Reins in September.
   The push to remove Curcio was apparently led by Renault's truck
operations, which owns about 45 percent of Mack's stock and has
four directors on Mack's 10-member board.
</TEXT>
