<HEAD>Dollar Mostly Lower, Gold its destruction Falls</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The dollar fell Tuesday against most major
currencies in moderate European trading after the release of
disappointing U.S. economic data.
   Gold prices also fell.
   Dealers said the dollar was knocked down by
steeper-than-expected falls in U.S. retail sales and industrial
production for October.
   Retail sales fell 1 percent last month, compared with a
predicted 0.8 percent decline, and production output dropped by 0.7
percent compared with a projected 0.2 percent fall.
   Dealers said the market's reaction was restrained before
Thursday's scheduled release of U.S. merchandise trade figures for
September.
   In Tokyo, the dollar rose 0.25 Japanese yen to a closing 143.80
yen. Lat to
encourage such spending by U.S. government and business.
   ``If you engage in any activity in our country, others will
emulate your example,'' Walesa said. ``The world is awaiting your
signal, it is watching you. Do not let the world and us wait any
longer.''
   Walesa offered the AFL-CIO repeated thanks and praise for
assistance dating back to just after the Gdansk shipyard strike he
led in 1981 to Solidarity's forced underground days, when the
federation provided an estimated $5 million worth of communications
equipment and other supplies.
   ``You have proven to be our most steadfast allies in the trade
union struggle for human freedom,'' Walesa said in the text of his
speech, saying others who have endorsed Solidarity's cause have not
backed up their rhetoric with help.
   ``Sometimes we feel as if we are swimming chained hand and foot,
trying to summon all our energy just to make it safely to shore,''
Walesa said. ``And on the shore there is a cheering crowd of people
who offer us their admiration instead of simply throwing a life
belt. We want to make it to the shore, to join the community of
democratic countries with efficient economies.''
   Walesa recalled the emigration of Poles to the United States in
search of freedom and said he had ``traveled across the Atlantic
just to tell you that hope has found its way to Poland too. For the
first time in several dozen years, Poles can feel the breeze of
freedom in their own country _ the breeze many people once had to
seek on this side of the ocean.''
   He warned that if the new Solidarity-led government in Poland
fails to revive the economy, more than Poland's new democracy and
people would suffer, and that success depended on help from abroad.
   ``If we fail to convince people that although things are
changing slowly they are nevertheless changing for the better, then
this breeze of freedom I spoke of will soon disappear, leaving
behind only a sense of bitterness accompanying unaccomplished
dreams,'' he said. ``It will result in a defeat for us, but not
only for us.''
   Walesa, a Nobel Peace Prize winner, told Bush on Monday, ``I'm
full of admiration for your country, not because it's a big power
and not because it's rich, even though one could envy that. I
admire America as a country of freedom,'' he said.
   Bush moved Walesa to tears recalling how he ``made the sign of
the cross on the foreheads of his sleeping children'' before Polish
police took him away in 1981 for 11 months during the martial law
crackdown on Solidarity.
   Now, Bush said, ``Lenin and Stalin have been disproved, not by
presidents or princes, but by the likes of an electrician from
Gdansk and his fellow workers in a brave union called Solidarity.
   ``The Iron Curtain is fast becoming a rusted, abandoned relic.
... The week that brought Lech Walesa to America is the week the
headlines proclaimed, `And the wall comes tumbling down!''' said
Bush.
