<FIRST>u f BC-AutoSales     11-14 0395</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-Auto Sales,0408</SECOND>
<HEAD>Downward Trend for Big Three Continues</HEAD>
<HEAD>With BC-Auto Sales-Table</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: AMs version planned.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By FREDERICK STANDISH</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Auto Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>DETROIT (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Sales of the nation's Big Three automakers' North
American-built cars and light trucks continued a downward spiral in
early November, falling 22.4 percent from last year, the companies
reported Tuesday.
   General Motors Corp., Ford Motor Co. and Chrysler Corp. said
they sold an average of 24,094 vehicles a day from Nov. 1-10 this
year, compared with 31,038 a day during the same time last year.
   Car sales were off 26.2 percent and truck sales were down 16.2
percent for the Big Three.
   The sales continued a trend begun in the first 10-day reporting
period of October, as the 1990 model year opened.
   Analysts had forecast slumping car and truck sales during the
fourth quarter of this year because carbuyers headed to the
showrooms weeks before to avoid 1990-model price increases and to
take advantage of incentive programs on 1989 models.
   Those programs have been whittled for 1990 vehicles.
   In October, car and light truck sales by the Big Three were down
14.1 percent from the year before. That slump pushed October's
retail sales down 1 percent, the first decline in eight months.
   The early-November sales pace of 24,094 vehicles a day was 17
percent below the 29,016 vehicle-a-day sales pace during the same
period a month ago.
   So far this year, car and truck sales by the Big Three were
running 4.3 percent behind last year's pace. Car sales were down
6.2 percent and truck sales were off 1.1 percent.
   In early November, GM posted the largest decline in car sales,
dropping 29.1 percent from the year-ago period. Light truck sales
reported by GM were 20.9 percent below last year's pace. For the
year, GM's car sales were off 7.3 percent while truck sales were up
a slim 0.3 percent.
   Ford's early-November car sales were down 23.5 percent and truck
sales were off 14.3 percent compared with last year. Year-to-date
car sales at Ford were down 1.6 percent and truck sales were
running 3.2 percent behind the year-to-date pace last year.
   Sales of Chrysler's cars were down 22.5 percent for the period,
and light truck sales were down 9.9 percent. Car sales this year
were running 11.6 percent behind last year's pace and truck sales
were down 0.6 percent.
</TEXT>
