<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Stock prices turned lower today, weighed down by
evidence of economic weakness and uncertainty about the interest
rate outlook.
   The Dow Jones average of 30 industrials fell 12.09 to 2,614.34
by 2 p.m. on Wall Street.
   Declining issues took a lead over advances on the New York Stock
Exchange with 646 up, 717 down and 539 unchanged.
   Volume on the floor of the Big Board came to 103.48 million
shares with two hours left to go.
   The NYSE's composite index of all its listed common stocks slid
0.45 to 187.77.
   Several reports released before trading began furnished fresh
evidence of an economic slowdown. But the statistics didn't paint a
completely clear picture because they were influenced by special
circumstances, analysts said.
   Retail sales dropped 1 percent in October, the first decline
since February. The Commerce Department said a slumping automobile
market depressed total retail sales.
   Separately, the Fed reported industrial production fell 0.7
percent in October. A strike in the aircraft industry and the
impact of the California earthquake crimped overall output.
   Traders have been hoping that the central bank will decide the
sluggish economy needs the stimulation that lower interest rates
would provide. But so far, the Fed has failed to ease significantly.
   Combustion Engineering led the Big Board's list of actively
traded issues and fell { to 38{. On Monday the company announced a
$1.6 billion merger deal with a Swiss company.
   Among heavily traded blue chips, food and tobacco company Philip
Morris fell 1[ to 41[ on word that Sen. Edward Kennedy, D-Mass.,
plans to introduce a bill to bolster cigarette health warnings and
sale restrictions.
   Elsewhere among the actives, Merck perked up ] to 76{. The drug
maker's stock tumbled 3~ on Monday after the company disclosed that
heavy research and sales costs will hurt short-term earnings growth.
   Stocks of the Big Three automakers showed declines after
reporting lower than expected early November car sales. General
Motors fell } to 43], Ford fell ] to 44] and Chrysler was off ] at
19~.
