<FILEID>AP-NR-11-14-89 1446EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r f AM-Dow-JournalPhone     11-14 0444</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Dow-JournalPhone,0461</SECOND>
<HEAD>Dow Jones Plans to Offer Financial News by Phone</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Dow Jones &amp; Co. Inc. said Tuesday it is
introducing an interactive 900-number telephone service that will
enable callers to get stock quotes, business and financial news,
sports reports and weather conditions.
   Dow Jones, publisher of The Wall Street Journal, plans to charge
85 cents for the first minute and 75 cents for each additional
minute for calls to its service, called JournalPhone.
   The service begins operation Wednesday and will be promoted each
weekday with advertising in the Journal.
   Its creators called the service ``a logical extension'' of the
newspaper.
   ``It picks up where the Journal leaves off and offers an easy,
convenient way to keep on top of the news as it develops throughout
the day,'' said Kenneth L. Burenga, a senior vice president of Dow
Jones.
   Callers who want to find out at mid-morning what the latest
government indicators showed, for example, can hear a recorded
report by dialing 1-900-JOURNAL and pushing the appropriate
telephone buttons as prompted by the service.
   When callers have heard enough, they can push a few more buttons
and obtain 15-minute delayed quotes on any of 6,500 stock prices;
regularly updated reports on the overall stock, bond or currency
markets; information about weather in selected cities; or reports
on sports stories or scores.
   The calls will be charged on regular monthly phone bills.
   Dow Jones is not the first newspaper publisher to provide
telephone services, although its service may offer the widest array
of reports.
   A number of newspapers, for instance, provide sports scores by
telephone for the cost of a local telephone call.
   Gannett Co. Inc.'s USA Today provides four call-in services on
900-numbers, including hotlines for sports information and scores,
weather reports, lottery results and horse racing results.
   Phil Fuhrer, vice president of Gannett New Media, said the
sports hotline receives 2.7 million calls a year at 60 cents for
the first minute and 45 cents for each minute after that. ``It
extends our coverage to 24 hours a day,'' he said.
   Dow Jones executives said they were not sure how many calls to
expect on their new service. It tested the service for three months
this past summer in Atlanta, where about 10,000 Journal readers
were invited to use the system for free. The test showed the
average calls lasted about two minutes.
   The company already provides a more expensive interactive
telephone service for active traders and plans to use the same
staff and facilities for its new service which is geared more
toward average investors.
   Dow Jones expects the new service to be profitable from the
start.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP891114-0249 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-11-14-89 1456EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r f AM-IndustrialProduction Bjt   11-14 0628</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Industrial Production, Bjt,0646</SECOND>
<HEAD>Strike, Earthquake Drive Down Overall Factory Output</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOHN D. McCLAIN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The economy's sluggish manufacturing sector
was hammered by an aircraft strike and an earthquake last month
which pounded industrial production down 0.7 percent to its lowest
level in three and a half years, the government reported Tuesday.
   But the Federal Reserve Board said that without the strike at
the Boeing Co. and the disruptive effects of the earthquake, ``the
total index would have been nearly unchanged in October, continuing
its recent sluggish trend.''
   Nevertheless, the decline was the steepest since a 1.3 percent
drop in March 1986.
   Industrial production was unchanged in September and has shown
weakness in recent months as the Fed kept a tight grip on credit to
slow the economy and curb inflation.
   The October output was foreshadowed by the Labor Department's
report earlier this month of a loss of 13,000 manufacturing jobs in
October, a drop in the average manufacturing work week and
virtually no factory overtime.
   But David Jones, an economist with Aubrey G. Lanston &amp; Co. in
New York said the sluggishness was worsened by the strike, which
added 0.4 percent to the decline, and the earthquake, which added
another 0.2 percent.
   ``If you take into account the special factors, we were down
just 0.1 percent,'' he said. ``That is much more consistent with
the pattern of proceeding months in which the industrial sector is
showing weakness while the others, particularly the service sector,
are holding up well.''
   John Silvia, an economist with Kemper Financial Services in
Chicago, said fairly steady consumer spending coupled with a weak
manufacturing sector indicates ``a little bit of a two-tier economy
showing up again similar to what we had earlier in this economic
expansion.''
   But while the Fed's interest-rate policies were having an
adverse effect on some segments of the economy, another report
indicated it was being successful in keeping inflation in check.
   In that report, the central bank said the operating rate of the
nation's factories, mines and utilities fell 0.8 percentage point
to 82.8 percent in October. Analysts generally consider an
operating rate of 85 percent or more to be inflationary because it
could lead to shortages and thus higher prices.
   Factory use had dipped in September to 83.6 percent from 83.8
percent in August. The rate posted 10-year highs of 84.3 percent
last December and January.
   Industrial production at manufacturing plants making both
durable and nondurable goods was down 0.8 percent in October after
falling 0.2 percent in September and rising 0.4 percent in July.
   Durable manufacturing was off 1.5 percent, compared with a 0.3
percent drop in September and a 0.4 percent gain in August.
Nondurable manufacturing rose 0.1 percent after declining 0.1
percent in September and rising 0.1 percent in August.
   Output was unchanged at mines, compared with gains of 2.1
percent in September and 0.6 percent the previous month. Output at
utilities was up 0.5 percent following a 1.2 percent advance in
September and a decline of 0.7 percent in August.
   The Fed said its industrial production index in October stood at
141.4 percent of its 1977 base, down from 142.4 percent a month
earlier.
   At the same time, it said the manufacturing-plant operating rate
fell from 83.7 percent in September to 82.8 percent last month. The
rate had peaked at 84.7 percent in January.
   The rate at factories producing durable goods _ big-ticket items
expected to last more than three years _ dropped 1.4 percentage
point to 80.9 percent. The rate at factories producing nondurable
goods was off 0.2 percentage point to 85.5 percent.
   The operating rate at mines was up 0.1 percentage point to 84.6,
while it rose 0.4 percentage point to 81.2 percent at utilities.
</TEXT>
