<FIRST>u f BC-BoardofTrade Close   11-14 0233</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-Board of Trade, Close,0242</SECOND>
<HEAD>Grain Futures Finish Mixed</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Grain and soybean futures prices closed mixed
Tuesday on the Chicago Board of Trade after a quiet session.
   Prices had opened lower across the board, reflecting
disappointment over China's cancellation of a wheat purchase and a
slackening of export activity. But the corn and soybean markets
rallied at midday and finished mostly higher.
   The Agriculture Department said Monday that private exporters
had reported cancellation of sales of 300,000 metric tons of U.S.
wheat to China that had been slated for delivery in the 1990-91
crop year, which begins June. 1.
   In addition to its impact on the wheat market, the cancellation
revived fears that the Soviet Union may be forced to cancel some of
its recent U.S. corn purchases due to jammed shipping routes.
   ``The wheat cancellation brings us back to the reality that
sales can be canceled,'' said William Biedermann, director of
research for Allendale Inc., a futures brokerage in Crystal Lake,
Ill.
   At the close, wheat futures were { cent to 3 cents lower with
the contract for delivery in December at $4.00{ a bushel; corn was
} cent lower to 1} cents higher with December at $2.40 a bushel;
oats were \ cent to } cent higher with December at $1.44{ a bushel;
soybeans were 1 cent to 2{ cents higher with November at $5.79 a
bushel.
