<DOCNO> AP891114-0253 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-11-14-89 1655EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r f AM-Farmers-CBOT     11-14 0567</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Farmers-CBOT,0587</SECOND>
<HEAD>Soybean Farmers' Lawsuit Accuses BOT of Illegal Price Manipulation</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By LINDSEY TANNER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Family farmers who say they suffered severe
financial losses from a Chicago Board of Trade order last summer
filed a federal class-action lawsuit Tuesday, accusing the exchange
of illegally manipulating soybean prices.
   The lawsuit seeking more than $100 million in damages was filed
by individual farmers from leading soybean-producing states and the
American Agriculture Movement, a lobbying group that represents
small farmers and rural business people in 34 states.
   The Board of Trade denied the allegations, which stem from its
emergency action July 11 ordering traders to reduce their holdings
in soybean futures contracts.
   The order caused a 20 percent drop in soybean prices and
corresponding declines in other commodities, the AAM said.
   The board's move was widely viewed as an effort to break up an
alleged attempt to corner the market by Ferruzzi Finanziaria SpA,
an Italian company and one of the world's largest soybean
processors.
   ``The CBOT's order was a bad faith and self-serving action
initiated by the CBOT's dominant grain merchants and futures
traders to create profits for their accounts and for their
clients,'' said Harvey Joe Sanner, AAM's president and an Arkansas
soybean farmer.
   Sanner spoke at a news conference at a downtown hotel,
accompanied by about 25 other farmers from Illinois, Iowa,
Missouri, Indiana, Minnesota, Ohio, Nebraska, Arkansas, Kansas and
South Dakota _ many of whom said they had been devastated by the
board action.
   ``I'm angry as hell about what has been done to we as producers
of this nation,'' said Corky Jones, a soybean farmer from
Brownville, Neb., and an AAM member.
   Jones said the order caused U.S. farmers ``in excess of a $50
billion loss on corn and about $27 billion in beans.''
   The lawsuit names as defendants the exchange, CBOT Chairman
Karsten Mahlmann and 21 other directors, and five other exchange
officials.
   After the news conference, the group _ carrying banners and
buckets of soybeans _ marched five blocks to the Board of Trade,
where they had hoped to meet with exchange officials.
   CBOT spokesman Raymond Carmichael said officials were in
meetings and refused to let the farmers enter the building. He
agreed to take the soybeans to exchange officials as a symbol of
their complaint.
   In a news release, Mahlmann said exchange officials had not seen
the lawsuit, but are ``confident in the action taken... by the
board of directors to maintain an orderly liquidation in our July
1989 soybean futures contract.''
   He said board officials ``expect this lawsuit to be proven
frivolous and do not believe it will be of any benefit to the U.S.
agriculture community.''
   ``The Commodity Futures Trading Commission vindicated our action
in their testimony before Congress supporting the exchange's
decision to maintain orderly markets,'' he said.
   The board's order required the liquidation of large positions in
its July soybean futures contracts. The exchange said it issued the
order to make Ferruzzi reduce its holdings in soybean futures
contracts.
   The Board of Trade was widely criticized by farm groups and
traders who saw the value of their futures holdings drop when
soybean futures prices fell sharply July 12.
   AAM attorney John Arens said the lawsuit was filed on behalf of
all farmers hurt by the order, ``about 95 percent'' of the nation's
growers, but that anyone can ``opt out'' if they choose.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
