<FIRST>u f AM-CommodityRdp     11-14 0679</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Commodity Rdp,0708</SECOND>
<HEAD>Platinum Soars To 6-Month High</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: Note material in 9th graf pvs, The report ... designated by
dashes on Johnson Matthey platinum report is embargoed until 12:01 a.m.
EST Wednesday. Time set by source.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DAVID DISHNEAU</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   Platinum futures prices climbed to six-month highs on the New
York Mercantile Exchange Tuesday, extending a rally that has lifted
the metal's value by more than 6 percent since Nov. 3.
   ``It's been incredible,'' said Nina Lipton, research director
for Platinum Guild International, a platinum trade association.
   On other futures markets, gold and silver also advanced; cocoa
futures plunged; energy, livestock and meat futures were lower; and
grains and soybeans were mixed.
   Platinum futures settled $11.30 to $13.10 higher with the
contract for delivery in January at $525.70 a troy ounce, the
highest price for a near-month contract since May 15.
   Platinum, like gold and silver, has risen sharply in value since
Oct. 13, when a 190-point plunge in the Dow Jones industrials
average sent nervous investors scrambling for the perceived safety
of precious metals. January platinum settled at $491.60 on Oct. 13.
   Analysts said Tuesday's gains reflected strong buying by both
commercial and speculative traders and marked something of a return
to the market by Japanese interests.
   ``Most of the strength came in from the Far East,'' said Peter
Cardillo, commodities trading adviser with Josephthal &amp; Co. in New
York.
   Buying also was fueled by speculation that a report due out
Wednesday from London-based Johnson Matthey PLC, the world's
largest platinum refiner, would project a production shortfall in
1989 for the fifth year in a row.
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
   The report, released Wednesday morning in New York, projected
1989 platinum production at 3.31 million ounces and demand at 3.43
million ounces, resulting in a projected deficit of about 120,000
ounces to be filled with stockpiled supplies.
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
   On New York's Commodity Exchange, gold settled $2.20 to $2.40
higher with December at $394.90 a troy ounce; silver was 9 cents to
10.3 cents higher with December at $5.408 a troy ounce.
   Cocoa futures plunged to new 14-year lows on New York's Coffee,
Sugar &amp; Cocoa Exchange on continued trade selling stemming from
indications of greater availability of African-origin cocoa.
   Cocoa settled $13 to $40 lower with December at $941 per metric
ton.
   Oil futures prices fell on the New York Mercantile Exchange,
primarily because of large supplies of gasoline in New York harbor.
   After the close, the American Petroleum Institute released
figures showing a 4.5-million-barrel decline in U.S. gasoline
inventories last week, contrary to expectations for higher
supplies. The API's reported increases of 2 million barrels of
crude oil and 1.8 million barrels of petroleum distillates were
near expectations.
   West Texas Intermediate crude oil settled 9 cents lower to 1
cent higher with December at $19.50 a barrel; heating oil was
unchanged to .31 cent lower with December at 57.45 cents a gallon;
unleaded gasoline was .75 cent lower to .15 cent higher with
December at 50.31 cents a gallon.
   Frozen pork bellies crashed in a technical sell-off on the
Chicago Mercantile Exchange with some contracts settling down the
permitted daily limit of 2 cents a pound.
   Expectations for steady-to-lower cash prices prompted selling of
hog and cattle futures.
   Live cattle settled .20 cent to .72 cent lower witih December at
74.42 cents a pound; feeder cattle were .15 cent to .70 cent lower
with November at 83.05 cents a pound; live hogs were .10 cent ot
.60 cent lower with December at 48.22 cents a pound; frozen pork
bellies were 1.55 cents to 2 cents lower with February at 63.15
cents a pound.
