<SECOND>AM-Shearson-Management, 1st Ld-Writethru,0603</SECOND>
<HEAD>Slumping Shearson Slates Executive Suite Shakeup</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: SUBS penultimate graf with closing stock price; PICKS UP last
graf pvs, `Clearly the...</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By STEFAN FATSIS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Shearson Lehman Hutton Inc. said Tuesday it was
planning a major shakeup in senior management, following a recent
round of up to 800 layoffs, slumping profits and a weak stock price.
   The planned reorganization at Shearson, the second-largest Wall
Street firm behind Merrill Lynch &amp; Co., comes during a lean period
throughout the securities industry.
   But analysts said the spotlight on Shearson stemmed largely from
the 61 percent ownership of the company by American Express Co.,
which reportedly wants to reduce its stake but wants Shearson to be
more profitable first.
   Shearson reported third-quarter earnings of $66 million, but
most of that came from a one-time $77 million pretax gain from the
sale of its Lehman Management Co. and investment banking fees from
Time Inc.'s acquisition of Warner Communications Inc.
   American Express' share of Shearson's third-quarter profit was
$41 million.
   The company also was stung by news that its debt was being
reviewed for possible downgrading and by an accounting scandal last
year at its Boston Co. money-management unit.
   ``American Express is probably furious,'' said Perrin Long, a
securities industry analyst with Lipper Analytical Services. ``With
a 61 percent ownership, it's a drain on American Express'
earnings.''
   A Shearson spokesman said that under the reorganization the firm
will promote a number of younger executives to more prominent
positions and reassign others throughout the company to create a
new identity for the brokerge firm.
   The spokesman, who asked that he not be identified, said the
reorganization will occur within several weeks and will ``broaden
the management and bring along a new generation to ensure the
company is managed as best as possible.''
   ``The process grows out of the fact that the company has grown
and diversified for the past several years,'' he said. ``Don't
think of it in terms of the staff cutbacks from last week.''
   Shearson began laying off some of its 38,500 employees last
Monday and notified others in a two-paragraph newsletter that more
across-the-board cuts were planned. Shearson cited, among other
things, the slowdown of stock market activity since the 1987 stock
market crash.
   The company had declined to say exactly how many employees would
lose their jobs. But officials said privately that as many as 800
people, or 2 percent of the total work force, could be cut. That
would be the largest staff reduction on Wall Street this year.
   A year ago, Shearson laid off about 1,200 employees. Since then
it has trimmed 300 more jobs. Several other Wall Street firms also
have retrenched in varying degrees this past year.
   Last month, Moody's Investors Service Inc. said it was reviewing
the firm's debt with an eye toward a possible downgrading. The
credit rating agency cited increased competition in the securities
business and Shearson's use of large, sometimes risky short-term
bridge loans to finance takeovers and mergers.
   Shearson stock closed up 25 cents at $14.62{ in New York Stock
Exchange trading Tuesday. American Express sold the stock to the
public in March 1987 at $34 a share and hit a low of $12.50 a share
after the October 1987 crash.
   ``Clearly the firm has not been performing up to expectations
and the business, which was sterengthening through the summer, has
taken a turn for the worse,'' said Lawrence Eckenfelder, a
securities analyst with Prudential-Bache Securities Corp.
</TEXT>
