<FIRST>u f AM-McCaw-Lin     11-14 0416</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-McCaw-Lin,0432</SECOND>
<HEAD>McCaw Says it Has Lined up Financing for LIN Bid</HEAD>
<DATELINE>KIRKLAND, Wash. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Nearly two dozen financial institutions
have agreed to supply McCaw Cellular Communications with $3 billion
to help McCaw finance its offer for conmtrolling interest in LIN
Broadcasting Corp.
   McCaw said Tuesday that the $3 billion, along with approximately
$1.2 billion of existing cash and marketable securities, provided
McCaw with the funding necessary to close its tender offer for 22
million shares of the New York-based concern.
   In addition, McCaw said it expected to receive approximately
$1.3 billion in a separate sale of some cellular telephone assets
to Contel Cellular Inc., a subsidiary of Contel Corp.
   Proceeds from that sale, expected in early 1990, would go to
reduce bank debt, McCaw said in a news release.
   McCaw has been an unwelcome suitor at LIN, which has taken
various steps to avoid a takeover, including agreeing to merger its
cellular operations with those of BellSouth Corp., the regional
telephone company based in Atlanta.
   In national over-the-counter trading Tuesday, LIN rose 37{ cents
a share to $117 while McCaw fell 75 cents a share to $37.25.
   McCaw said 22 institutions in North America, Japan and Europe
had agreed to put up the $3 billion requested by McCaw, and that
the syndicate would have put up as much as $7 billion.
   In a stormy battle, McCaw has been trying to buy LIN since last
June. Its latest offer, on Oct. 10, was $125 a share for 22 million
shares, which would give McCaw a 50.3 percent ownership of LIN.
   Additionally, McCaw's offer includes a private market value
guarantee, assuring long-term stockholders of full market value for
their remaining shares in five years.
   Shortly before McCaw's financing announcement Tuesday, LIN
issued a news release saying McCaw was required by Securities and
Exchange Commission rules to leave its offer open for at least five
business days after it announced committed financing.
   It said McCaw's offer expiration date of Nov. 17, this Friday,
would not meet the five-day requirement.
   Efforts to reach Donald Guthrie of McCaw's headquarters in
Kirkland were unsuccessful. A woman who answered the telephone in
his office but refused to give her name said the company would have
no comment on whether the expiration date would be extended.
   McCaw is the nation's largest cellular company, serving 45
million parties in 114 markets in 23 states.
   LIN has major ownership interests in cellular markets in New
York, Philadelphia, Los Angeles, Dallas-Fort Worth and Houston.
</TEXT>
