<FIRST>r f AM-FortuneProducts     11-14 0456</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Fortune Products,0473</SECOND>
<HEAD>Fortune Names Top Products of '89</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   It's a small world, getting smaller, Fortune
magazine says.
   Four of the top 11 products the magazine named for 1989 are
small enough to fit in the pocket of a raincoat _ a video game, a
camcorder, a razor and a telephone.
   Another is a version of a product that a couple decades ago
required a separate room to store it: a computer.
   The list, published in the Dec. 4 issue, includes:
   _Nintendo Game Boy: The paperback-sized toy plays the company's
popular video game cartridges, which slip into the back of the
unit. For $89.95, the game with a 2{-inch diagonal screen includes
headphones, cables and the first Soviet-developed video game.
   _Sony CCD-TR5 Handycam: The 28-ounce device costs $1,500. Sony
touts the 8mm camcorder for its automatic features and small size.
   _Mazda Miata MX-5: Waiting lists for the convertible sports car
are reported at up to a year. The Miata lists at $13,800, but
Fortune said some dealers are much charging higher prices.
   _``Batman'': The Warner Bros. summer-release movie already has
brought in $250 million in revenue, making it the fifth-largest
grossing picture in history. Tie-in products, such as the home
video version, could bring the studio another $75 million. Both
Warner Bros. and Fortune are owned by Time Warner Inc.
   _Compaq LTE: The looseleaf notebook-sized computer weighs six
pounds and has the power of the most sophisticated personal
computers. LTE models are priced from $2,399 to $4,999.
   _Motorola Micro TAC Personal Telephone: The portable cellular
phone, which fits in a shirt pocket, weighs just over 12 ounces and
measures 15.8 cubic inches. About half the size and weight of its
closest rival, the telephone costs from $2,495 to $3,495.
   _Cholesterol fighters: Fortune cited products that ``help you
avoid the artery-clogging stuff,'' including cereals containing the
plant psyllium such as General Mills' Benefit and Kellogg's
Heartwise.
   _Epogen: The genetically engineered drug made by Amgen
eliminates the need for frequent blood transfusions for kidney
dialysis patients. It was approved by the federal Food and Drug
Administration this year.
   _Gillette Sensor: The much-ballyhooed razor contains twin
chromium blades individually mounted on tiny springs that adjust to
facial contours. Gillette spent $200 million and 10 years
developing the $3.75 razor.
   _Arco EC-1: Atlantic Richfield Co.'s reformulated fuel is
designed for pre-1975 cars and trucks that produce a lot of
pollution. Arco claims the leaded fuel, which was introduced in the
Los Angeles area in September, could cust pollution from the
vehicles by 20 percent.
   _Hewlett-Packard Co.'s LaserJet IIP: The laser printer is
praised as the the first inexpensive model of its kind, with a list
price of $1,495 and discounted retail price of about $1,000.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
