<HEAD>Dollar Off, Gold Up</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: LEADS with 3 grafs to add time element and CORRECT rise in Comex
gold to $2.30 an ounce sted $3.30; picks up 4th graf, Currency dealers
.... Precedes LONDON-BC</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The dollar fell sharply against all key
currencies Tuesday while the West German mark continued to take
center stage in foreign exchange.
   Gold prices, meanwhile, gained ground.
   On the Commodity Exchange in New York, gold bullion for current
delivery settled at $393.30 a troy ounce, up $2.30 from late
Monday. Republic National Bank of New York quoted a late bid for
gold at $392.50 an ounce, $2.40 higher.
   Currency dealers said continued signs of an economic slowdown in
the United States helped depress the dollar by renewing speculation
that the Federal Reserve would lower interest rates. A reduction in
interest rates could hurt the dollar's value.
   The government reported Tuesday that retail sales slipped 1
percent in October while industrial production declined 0.7
percentage point that month.
   Dealers, however, said that attention in the marketplace was
again concentrated on cross trading as the mark continued to climb.
They said the flood of East Germans into West Germany has raised
the possibility of higher inflation in West Germany and higher
interest rates there.
   The dollar fell to 1.8540 marks from 1.8615 in London, and to
1.8350 marks from 1.8615 in New York.
   In Tokyo, where trading ends before Europe's business day
begins, the dollar closed up 0.25 Japanese yen to 143.80 yen. It
traded at 144 yen in London, and at 143.05 yen in New York, down
from 143.925.
   The dollar was also weaker against the British pound. Sterling
bought $1.5810 in London, up from $1.5805 late Monday. It traded at
$1.5945 in New York, up from $1.5820.
   Other late dollar rates in New York, compared with late Monday's
quotes, included: 1.6175 Swiss francs, down from 1.64145; 6.2280
French francs, down from 6.3135; 1,343.00 Italian lire, down from
1,359.75; and 1.16975 Canadian dollars, down from 1.16845.
   Late dollar rates in Europe compared with Monday: 1.6380 Swiss
francs, down from 1.6410; 6.2925 French francs, down from 6.3140;
2.0925 Dutch guilders, down from 2.1030; 1,357.00 Italian lire,
down from 1,360.50; and 1.1710 Canadian dollars, up from 1.1677.
   Gold fell in London to a late bid of $390 an ounce from $391.25
late Monday. In Zurich, gold fell to $389 an ounce from $390.
   Earlier, in Hong Kong, gold rose $4.34 to a closing bid of
$391.51 an ounce.
   Silver prices were mixed. On New York's Comex, silver bullion
for current delivery rose to $5.408 a troy ounce from $5.297 late
Monday. Silver traded in London at $5.31 an ounce, unchanged.
</TEXT>
