<HEAD>Another Report on Ted Turner Interest in Bidding for MGM-UA</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BEVERLY HILLS, Calif. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   MGM-UA Communications Co. declined
comment Tuesday on the latest report linking broadcast and cable
executive Ted Turner to efforts to purchase the motion picture
studio.
   The Wall Street Journal, quoting an unidentified executive close
to the company, reported Tuesday that Turner Broadcasting has been
in ``serious negotiations'' for three weeks to buy MGM-UA.
   ``We have no comment,'' MGM-UA spokeswoman Mary Hardy said.
   In Atlanta, Turner Broadcasting System Inc. spokesman Arthur
Sando didn't immediately return telephone calls.
   MGM-UA declined comment last week on a Hollywood Reporter story
that Turner and Tele-Communications Inc., the nation's largest
cable-TV system operator, had initiated preliminary talks about a
joint bid.
   Tele-Communications and its 54 percent-owned United Artists
Communications Inc. affiliate are putting together the latest bid,
possibly in partnership with Turner, the Wall Street Journal said.
   ``All we are saying is that we've been approached on the subject
and we have it under study,'' Tele-Communications Senior Vice
President Robert Thomson told the Wall Street Journal.
   A call was placed to Tele-Communications, which is based in
Denver, but all of the company's top executives were said to be
unavailable for comment.
   Turner bought MGM-UA from Kirk Kerkorian in 1986 and later sold
it back except for most of the rights to the library of MGM films.
Rights to about 1,000 United Artists films are now considered the
company's greatest asset.
   Turner has wanted the UA film library since getting control of
MGM's film library two years ago, the unidentified executive told
the Wall Street Journal. ``He covets the Pink Panther and James
Bond,'' the executive was quoted.
   MGM-UA had agreed to be acquired by Qintex Australia Ltd. in a
$1.5 billion transaction that fell apart last month.
   Others previously expressing interest in MGM-UA include Rupert
Murdoch's News Corp. and Paramount Communications Inc.
   Filmmaking at MGM-UA has nearly halted in the year and a half
since Kerkorian started looking for a buyer.
</TEXT>
