<FILEID>AP-NR-11-14-89 2322EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r f BC-MeredithSuit     11-14 0398</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-Meredith Suit,0410</SECOND>
<HEAD>Transferred Federal Employees File Suit, Seek Millions From Meredith</HEAD>
<DATELINE>DES MOINES, Iowa (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A class-action lawsuit filed Tuesday on
behalf of an estimated 2,000 federal employees seeks millions of
dollars from Meredith Corp. for allegedly cheating transferred
civil servants in contracts to buy their homes.
   The civil suit filed in U.S. District Court by 10 federal
employees and on behalf of all others in similar circumstances
accuses Meredith and its Meredith Relocation Corp. of fraud, breach
of contract, unjust enrichment, restraint of trade and violations
of the Racketeer Influenced and Corrupt Organizations Act.
   Last month, the U.S. Justice Department sued the Des
Moines-based media and real estate company, seeking more than $7.7
million for similar alleged violations involving the relocation of
government employees.
   The class-action suit was filed because the Justice Department
said it could not represent individual federal employees with
claims against Meredith, said Jane Lang, a partner of Sprenger &amp;
Land, a law firm with offices in Washington and Minneapolis that
specializes in such litigation.
   ``Our suit is intended to compensate the employees for what they
lost,'' she said.
   Meredith is best known for its Better Homes and Gardens and
Ladies' Home Journal magazines. Its relocation service also is
known as Better Homes and Gardens Family Relocation Service.
   Larry Riley, a Meredith spokesman, said the company stood by a
statement denying wrongdoing that it issued Oct. 25, after the
federal government filed its suit. In that statement, Meredith said
it believed its relocation service acted properly.
   Meredith, which laid off 30 workers at offices in Iowa,
California, Connecticut and Colorado when the contract was canceled
a year early, has its own $6 million claim pending against the
federal government.
   Under a two-year contract signed in May 1986 with the federal
General Services Administration, Meredith agreed to buy homes and
perform other relocation services for transferred federal workers
in 24 central and Western states. The government estimated the
value of the contract at $103.3 million.
   The contract was canceled after one year following a government
audit that the government said disclosed Meredith intimidated
appraisers to lower the valuations of federal employees' homes. The
Justice Department claims that efforts by Meredith to obtain lower
appraisals resulted in delays in the sales of the homes, forcing
employees into accepting distressed prices.
   The class-action suit makes similar claims. It seeks unspecified
actual and punitive damages.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
